The protein is localized to the [/ontology/go/0005737/annotation/page/1 cytoplasm]. Null mutant in ''lrrA'' arrest at the mound stage and do not form a tip
column2: indicating that they have defects in [/ontology/go/0031154/annotation/page/1 culmination during sorocarp development]. The mutant is defective in [/ontology/go/0043327/annotation/page/1 chemotaxis to cAMP] and [/ontology/go/0043326/annotation/page/1 chemotaxis to folate]
column3: and has weak [/ontology/go/0031589/annotation/page/1 cell-substrate adhesion] and [/ontology/go/0016337/annotation/page/1 cell-cell adhesion]. Also
column4: the mutant has delayed expression of cAMP signaling genes during development
column5: including [/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA] and [/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16051212 Liu et al. 2005]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0272799	Petra Fey	The ''icmA'' gene encodes the conserved isoprenylcysteine carboxyl methyltransferase in ''Dictyostelium''. The protein was shown to have [/ontology/go/0004671/annotation/page/1 protein-S-isoprenylcysteine O-methyltransferase activity]. The ''icmA''-null mutant shows defects in early development
column2: such as no cell polarization ([/ontology/go/0030010/annotation/page/1 establishment of cell polarity]) or streaming
column3: aberrant cAMP wave formation
column4: and in some cases loose mound formation that may proceed to form aberrant fruiting bodies ([/ontology/go/0060176/annotation/page/1 regulation of aggregation involved in sorocarp development]). In the mutant
column5: the starvation-induced expression of the cAMP receptor [/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1] is delayed
column6: also reflected in the fact that mutant membranes bind only 34% of the CAMP that wild-type membranes bind. However
column7: in pulsed mutant cells the cAMP relay response is 3 times larger than in wild type. In addition
column8: Ras GTPase ([/gene/DDB_G0293434 rasG]) has been shown to be methylated and in the ''icmA''-null mutant RasG
column9: as well as CRAC ([/gene/DDB_G0285161 dagA]) are mislocalized in cAMP-pulsed cells. In sum
column10: these data show that isoprenylcysteine methylation is required for signalling in response to cAMP ([/ontology/go/0008277/annotation/page/1 regulation of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway]) and development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17699599 Chen et al. 2007)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column3: encoded by the [/gene/DDB_G0275617 tbpA] gene)and TBP-associated factors (TAFs) on the TATA-box sequence upstream of the initiation start site. TFIIA binds to TBP to stabilise TBP binding to the TATA element. In yeast
column4: TFIIA is dispensable for accurate initiation of transcription but plays an important role in transcriptional activation
column5:
functioning as either an antirepressor or a coactivator.

column1: DDB_G0294094	Pascale Gaudet	''lrra'' encodes a protein with 19 leucine-rich repeats (LLRs). LRRs associate with Ras proteins to facilitate their interaction with other proteins. The interacting partner(s) of LrrA are not known but LrrA failed to interact with rasD in a two-hybrid experiment. The ''lrrA'' gene is expressed during growth and early development. The protein is localized to the [/ontology/go/0005737/annotation/page/1 cytoplasm]. Null mutant in ''lrrA'' arrest at the mound stage and do not form a tip
column2: indicating that they have defects in [/ontology/go/0031154/annotation/page/1 culmination during sorocarp development]. The mutant is defective in [/ontology/go/0043327/annotation/page/1 chemotaxis to cAMP] and [/ontology/go/0043326/annotation/page/1 chemotaxis to folate]
column3: and has weak [/ontology/go/0031589/annotation/page/1 cell-substrate adhesion] and [/ontology/go/0016337/annotation/page/1 cell-cell adhesion]. Also
column4: the mutant has delayed expression of cAMP signaling genes during development
column5: including [/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA] and [/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16051212 Liu et al. 2005]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column3: regulating the [/ontology/go/0006265/annotation/page/1 DNA topological change]. While it is similar to cytoplasmic topoisomerases II

column5: and has been shown to localize to the [/ontology/go/0005739/annotation/page/1 mitochondrion] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/PUB3360  (Komori et al.

DDB_G0291039	Robert Dodson	The motor domain in the kinesin encoded by ''kif11'' is at the N-terminus and belongs to the CENP-E family of domains of kinetochore-associated proteins that align chromosomes during mitosis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14641909  (Kollmar and Glockner 2003)]. Disruption of the ''kif11'' showed that Kif11 is not required for mitotic spindle assembly
column2: cell growth or development. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18430243  (Nag et al. 2008)]. Microtubule distributions appear normal in ''kif11'' null cells but the effects of expression of the truncated 380-kDa form of dynein were less pronounced in ''kif11'' cells than in wild type cells suggesting that dynein and Kif11 cooperate to some extent in organizing the radial interphase microtubule distribution. Imaging of GFP-labeled Kif11 expressing cells indicates that Kif11 is a plus-end directed motor that accumulates at microtubule plus ends. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23333327  (Kosem et al. 2013)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0285319 Karen Kestin Histones form the nucleosomal core ([/ontology/go/0000786/annotation/page/1 nucleosome]) ([/ontology/go/0006334/annotation/page/1 nucleosome assembly]) that is fundamental to chromatin structure (). The histone octamer is composed of an H3-H4 tetramer (two H3-H4 dimers) coupled with an H2A-H2Btetramer (two H2A-H2B dimers). The histone H1 linker protein plays a role in packaging nucleosomes into the 30 nmfiber found in chromatin ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9177486 Bukenberger et al. 1992]).
In ''Dictyostelium discoideum'' and ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae''
column2: only one copy of histone H1 appears to be present
column3: in comparison to other eukaryotes which have multiple copies and subtypes([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7867938 Hauser et al. 1995]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9046096 Ushinsky et al.1997]). Two putative H2A family members
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0279667 H2AX] and [/gene/DDB_G0286747 H2AZ]
column6: and three H2Adomain-containing proteins
column10: are present in ''Dictyostelium''. Two H2B domain-containing proteins also exist inthe ''Dicty'' genome: [/gene/DDB_G0293758 H2Bv1] and [/gene/DDB_G0276273 H2Bv2]. There are three histone H3proteins
column15: [/gene/DDB_G0291185 H3v1] and [/gene/DDB_G0277979 H3v2]. We have also identified two histone H4proteins
column17:
which have identical protein sequences but non-identical nucleotide sequences.
A functional histone H1 in ''Dictyostelium'' was originally identified by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3923431 Parish andSchmidlin (1985)]. Through micrococcal nuclease digestion
column18: they showed that a lysine-rich proteinfunctions as an H1 histone to bring the two DNA strands together at their exit point from the nucleosome. HistoneH1 was later cloned by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7867938 Hauser and colleagues (1995)]
column19: who showed throughSouthern blot analysis that H1 exists in a single copy in the ''Dicytostelium'' genome. Their protein sequenceanalysis revealed the presence of the globular domain found higher eukaryotes and a putative cdc2 kinasephosphorylation site. They did not find
column21: a nucleotide binding loop or a consensus cAMP-dependent phosphorylationsite. This is consistent with the findings of [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1321059 Heads et al. (1992)]
column22: whoshowed that growth-associated H1 histone kinase phosphorylates histone H1 in a cAMP independent manner.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column6: and three H2Adomain-containing proteins

column15: [/gene/DDB_G0291185 H3v1] and [/gene/DDB_G0277979 H3v2]. We have also identified two histone H4proteins

column1: DDB_G0284791	Petra Fey	''Dictyostelium cpnC'' belongs to the highly conserved copines
column2: a family of ubiquitious Ca(2+)-dependent phospholipid-binding ([/ontology/go/0005544/annotation/page/1 calcium-dependent phospholipid binding]) proteins. In their N-terminal half
column3: copines contain two Ca(2+)- and phospholipid-binding domains (C2 domains) present in such proteins as phospholipase C and protein kinase C. Much of the C-terminal half consists of a von Willebrand Factor type A domain (VWFA) typically found in the extracellular portions of membrane proteins like integrins. Thus copines represent a fusion of intracellular (C2) and extracellular (VWFA) domains. However
column4: there are no signal sequence or hydrophobic transmembrane sequences in the predicted proteins suggesting copines are intracellular proteins. Copines are thought to be involved in membrane trafficking. It is of particular interest that copines
column5: first found in the highly phagocytic protozoan ''Paramecium'' and then isolated from mammalian spleen and liver
column6: seem to be abundant in cells and organs that are
column8: phagocytes. In this context it comes as no surprise that phagocytic ''Dictyostelium'' has a total of six copine genes[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16343335  (Damer et al. 2005)]. The widespread distribution of copines from protozoans to mammals and their high similarity suggest they play important role(s) in eukaryotic biology. Reviewed in [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12440769  (Tomsig and Creutz

column1: DDB_G0289555	Karen Kestin	The ''arkA'' gene was identified in a screen for suppressors of the protein phosphatase [/gene/DDB_G0276155 spnA]mutant ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14597204 Aubry et al. 2003]). ArkA contains several functionaldomains
column2: including a protein kinase domain ([/ontology/go/0004672/annotation/page/1 protein kinase activity]) that is classified in the tyrosine kinase-like (TKL)group of protein kinases. The ''arkA'' transcript is developmentally regulated such that two peaks inexpression are detected by Northern blot at 8 hours and 15 hours after starvation. Spatial expression of thetranscript is highly enriched in the prestalk region in the slug and in the stalk and the tip of the fruitingbody. Subcellular localization is detected in the cortex
column3:
most likely associated with the cytoskeleton ([/ontology/go/0030863/annotation/page/1 cortical cytoskeleton]).
Disruption of the ''arkA'' gene results in abnormal fruiting bodies
column4: whereas overexpression results in severemorphological defects ([/ontology/go/0007275/annotation/page/1 multicellular organismal development]). Expression levels of developmental markers [/gene/DDB_G0280531 lagC]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0277853 ecmA]
column6: and [/gene/DDB_G0277141 cotC] are not affected in ''arkA-'' cells
column8: the spore-specific [/gene/DDB_G0289075 spiA] transcript is elevated in comparison to wild-type. Additionally
column9: yeast two-hybrid analysis showsthat ArkA interacts with 14-3-3 ([/gene/DDB_G0269138 fttB]) and [/gene/DDB_G0292998 rasB] but not with [/gene/DDB_G0292996 rasD]
column11: or [/gene/DDB_G0283537 rasS] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14597204 Aubry et al.2003]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0276887	Pascale Gaudet	FbxA belongs to a family of proteins that contain an F-box and WD40 repeats and that target specific proteins for degradation via proteasomes ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10898960 Nelson et al. 2001]). This class of protein usually forms part of a <u>S</u>kp1
column3:
F-box [/ontology/go/0019005/annotation/page/1 SCF ubiquitin ligase complex] that targets specific protein substrates for ubiquitination and degradation ([/ontology/go/0006511/annotation/page/1 ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10725352 Ennis et al. 2000]).One of the targets of FbxA is the cAMP phosphodiesterase [/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12796307 Tekinay et al. 2003]).

column4: most structures arrest at the mound stage
column5: and in those that progress further the spore mass fails to fully ascend the stalk. The development of ''fbxA'' null cells is hypersensitive to ammonia
column6:
the signaling molecule that regulates [/ontology/go/0031154/annotation/page/1 culmination during sorocarp development]. The mutant causes wild-type cells that have begun to express spore-specific genes to accumulate in the prestalk compartment of the developing organism ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10725352 Ennis et al. 2000]).
The ''fbxA'' transcript is absent in growing cells and appears early in development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10725352 Ennis et al. 2000]) and is highly enriched in the prestalk cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10898960 Nelson et al. 2001]).

column10:
leading to an increase in cAMP and PKA activity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11390363 Mohanty et al. 2001]).Null mutations in [/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA] or [/gene/DDB_G0280961 dhkA] partially restores the developmental defects observed in ''fbxA'' null cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12796307 Tekinay et al. 2003]).

DDB_G0286183	Pascale Gaudet	''agps'' is an oxidoreductase with [/ontology/go/0008609/annotation/page/1 alkylglycerone-phosphate synthase activity]
column2: responsible for the formation of alkyldihydroxyacetonephosphate (alkyl-DHAP) through the exchange of the acyl moiety of acyl-DHAP with a fatty alcohol. This reaction required FAD. This essential reaction generates the ether bond in the [/ontology/go/0008611/annotation/page/1 ether lipid biosynthetic process]. In other organisms
column3: this takes place in the [/ontology/go/0005777/annotation/page/1 peroxisome]. Consistent with this
column4:
the ''Dictyostelium'' protein has a type 1 peroxisomal targeting signal at the C terminus.
The ''Dictyostelium'' Agps protein has been crystallized ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17562315 Razeto et al.
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17601746 Razeto et al.
column7: 2007]). The catalytic site contains five conserved residues: Asp237
column11: and Tyr508. Mutagenesis of the Arg352 residue diminishes agps activity
column12:
while mutation of Tyr508 abolishes the activity.
Defects in human ''AGPS'' causes rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata (RCDP)
column13:
a peroxisomal disorder defined by the inability of patients to synthesize ether phospholipids. This results in serious developmental defects and death before 10 years of age.
Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0276353 Pascale Gaudet The TorA protein is a novel protein with predicted coiled-coil motif near its carboxy terminus. The protein is localized to large clusters at one end of the [/ontology/go/0005739/annotation/page/1 mitochondrion].
''torA'' was isolated during a REMI mutant screen for genes required for chemotaxis. The mutant forms small plaques on bacteria due to defects in [/ontology/go/0043327/annotation/page/1 chemotaxis to cAMP]
column2: but it exhibits normal phagocytosis and detection of cAMP. The defects caused by mutations in ''torA'' are rescued by expression of [/gene/DDB_G0269152 mekA]. Overexpression of ''torA'' leads to surface-dependent growth: cells are unable to grow is suspension ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11157987 van Es et al. 2001]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0277221	Pascale Gaudet	Clathrin is part of the vesicles coat ([/ontology/go/0030118/annotation/page/1 clathrin coat]) involved in endocytosis from the plasma membrane
column2:
as well as traffic from endosomes and the trans-Golgi network. The clathrin protein is composed of three 190-kDa heavy chains (encoded by ''chcA'') and three ~30-kDa light chains ([/gene/DDB_G0277403 clc]) that form the clathrin triskelion.
The ''Dictyostelium'' clathrin heavy chain sequence has 57% identity with the mammalian protein. mRNA levels are highest during vegetative growth and decline as the cells progress through development. The concentration of clathrin heavy-chain protein is the same in cells grown in liquid media (high rates of pinocytosis) as in cells grown with bacteria([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1605855 O'Halloran and Anderson 1992]). GFP-clathrin distribute into punctate loci found throughout the cytoplasm
column3: on the plasma membrane
column4: and concentrated to a perinuclear location([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10848635 Damer and O'Halloran 2000]). ''chcA'' null mutants have reduced pinocytosis and defective processing and localization of lysosomal protein ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8034739 Ruscetti et al. 1994]).In addition
column5: these mutants display about 40% of the level of extracellular cyclic AMP binding normally found in wild-type cellsAggregation is delayed
column6: and the fruiting bodies have an irregular shape. ''chcA''- cells failed to sort correctly and never produced functional spores([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9053320 Niswonger and O'Halloran 1997]). ''chcA''- cells have defective cytokinesis in suspension that result from their inability to assemble myosin II into a functional contractile ring ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9238018 Niswonger and O'Halloran 1997]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11223952 Gerald et al. 2001]). Study of cell motility using the ''chcA'' muatnt suggests that clathrin suppresses pseudopod formation and stabilizes the uropod in the posterior half of a crawling cell ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10591622 Wessel et al. 2000]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0274387	Pascale Gaudet	''Dictyostelium'' development is sensitive to Li+ treatment. Mutants that lack the ''dpoA'' gene

column4: ([/ontology/go/0004287/annotation/page/1 prolyl oligopeptidase activity]). Inositol (1
column6: 5) trisphosphate (IP3) levels
column7: known to be affected by Li+
column8: are increased in the ''dpoA'' mutant ([/ontology/go/0009966/annotation/page/1 regulation of signal transduction]). IP3 concentrations increase via an unconventional mechanism that involves enhanced dephosphorylation of inositol (1
column12: 6) pentakisphosphate. Loss of DpoA activity therefore counteracts the reduction in IP3 concentration caused by Li+ treatment. No genetic interaction was observed with [/gene/DDB_G0272110 gskA]
column13: another major cellular target of Li+ ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10329620 Williams et al. 1999]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0272837	Pascale Gaudet	''ifkA'' and [/gene/DDB_G0276829 ifkB] encode homologs of a kinase that phosphorylate the translation initiation factor eIF2alpha ([/ontology/go/0004686/annotation/page/1 elongation factor-2 kinase activity])
column2: ([/ontology/go/0006445/annotation/page/1 regulation of translation]). The two Ifk proteins possess all of the hallmarks of typical GCN2 proteins
column3:
including the characteristic kinase domain and the HisRS domain. ''ifkA'' is expressed during growth and drops dramatically soon after the onset of development.
Disruption of the ''ifkA'' gene causes defects in early development. ''ifkA'' null cells aggregate earlier than parental cells due to a more rapid establishment of the cAMP pulsing system. Cells lacking a functional IfkA protein form larger mounds and subsequent developmental structures ([/ontology/go/0007275/annotation/page/1 multicellular organismal development])
column4:
([/ontology/go/0009653/annotation/page/1 anatomical structure morphogenesis]). This defect was linked to a reduced extracellular level of Countin ([/gene/DDB_G0274597 ctnA]). Efficient translation of ''ctnA'' mRNA requires increased phosphorylation of eIF2a by IfkA [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12697064 (Fang et al. 2003)].
In ''Dictyostelium''
column5: two members of the GCN2 (also known as PEK
column6: pancreatic eukaryotic translation initiation factor kinase) family of protein kinases have been identified: [/gene/DDB_G0272837 ifkA] and[/gene/DDB_G0276829 ifkB]. Putative proteins belonging to the GCN2 family are: [/gene/DDB_G0276043 ifkC]
column10: and [/gene/DDB_G0292734 DDB_G0292734].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0267418	Karen Kestin	S-Adenosyl-L-homocysteine hydrolase (SAHH) catalyzes the reaction S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + H<sub>2</sub>O =L-homocysteine + adenosine. S-[/ontology/go/0004013/annotation/page/1 adenosylhomocysteinase activity] was first characterized in ''Dictyostelium'' in a [/ontology/go/0030552/annotation/page/1 cAMP binding] protein with a molecular weight of 47 kilodaltons that likely exists as a 190 kilodaltontetramer ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6299402 Gunzburg et al. 1983]). The ''sahA'' gene was later identifiedand cloned
column2: and its amino acid sequence is highly conserved with mammalian SAHH ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3288206 Kasir etal. 1988]
column3: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3139100 Guitton et al. 1988]). The biochemistry of SahAhas been extensively studied and has been shown to be activated by bound NAD+ and reversibly inactivated by cAMP andthe adenosine analog 2'-deoxyadenosine ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6319183 Hohman and Veron 1984]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6091559 Hohman et al. 1984]). Inactivation of the SahA protein by cAMP occurs via dissociationof SahA from NAD+
column5: however
column6:
inactivation by 2'-deoxyadenosine is through the reduction of bound NAD+ to NADH ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2991881 Hohman et al. 1985]).
Cellular localization of SahA has been observed in the [/ontology/go/0005737/annotation/page/1 cytoplasm]
column8: and in the [/ontology/go/0005938/annotation/page/1 cell cortex] of vegetative amoeba ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15358428 Yamada and Sameshima 2004]) and in the [/ontology/go/0031252/annotation/page/1 leading edge] of chemotaxing cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17172447 Shu et al. 2006]). SahA isalso a component of [/ontology/go/0031002/annotation/page/1 actin rod]s
column9: which are large structures made of hexagonally arranged actin tubulesfound in the nuclei and cytoplasm of germinating spores ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11728467 Kishi et al.2001]). Additionally
column10: the translocation of the SahA protein between the cytoplasm and the cell cortex isregulated in response to hypertonicity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15358428 Yamada and Sameshima 2004]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0268258	Robert Dodson	The motor domain in the kinesin encoded by ''kif12'' belongs to the MKLP1 family of mitotic kinesins and is found near the N-terminus but preceeded by a 120 aa extension [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14641909  (Kollmar and Glockner 2003)]. Kif12 has two nuclear localization signals that localize it to the nucleus during interphase. As cells enter metaphase
column2: Kif12 leaves for the cytoplasm and localizes along spindle fibers [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15546981  (Lakshmikanth et al. 2004)]. Cells in which ''kif12'' is deleted are unable to grow in suspension but can multiply by traction-mediated cytofission when attached to a surface submerged by medium. Under these conditions
column3: the large
column4: multinucleated mutant cells divide asymmetrically
column5: forming smaller cells that survive as long as they capture at least one nucleus. Very little myosin II ([/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA])
column6: accumulates in the cleavage furrow and the rate of separation of the nuclei during karyokinesis is reduced. It was suggested that Kif12 might transport vesicles containing myosin II along mitotic extranuclear microtubules towards the center of the cell to be inserted into the cleavage furrow membrane [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15546981  (Lakshmikanth et al. 2004)]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22379107  (Kee et al. 2012)]. Like each of the other mitotic kinesins
column8: ''kif12'' mRNA levels are low in growing cells and increase to relatively high levels between 12 and 18 hrs of development before returning to very low levels [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0288361	Robert Dodson	The motor domain in the kinesin encoded by ''kif13'' belongs to the BimC/Eg5 family of mitotic kinesins that drive spindle pole separation during mitosis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14641909  (Kollmar and Glockner 2003)]. Kif13 was found to co-purify along with more than 80 other proteins in samples enriched in centrosomes [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16512674  (Reinders et al. 2006)]. ''kif13'' null cells grow at rates indistinguishable from wild type suggesting that other kinesins can substitute for any vital roles of Kif13. However
column2: the spindle halves separate prematurely in ''kif13'' null cells
column3: indicating that Kif13 may play a specialized role in maintaining spindle integrity at the terminal stages of division [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18712789  (Tikhonenko et al. 2008)]. Like each of the other mitotic kinesins
column4: kif13 mRNA levels are low in growing cells and increase to relatively high levels between 12 and 18 hrs of development before returning to very low levels [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0272875	Petra Fey	''Dictyostelium cpnB'' belongs to the highly conserved copines
column2: a family of ubiquitious Ca(2+)-dependent phospholipid-binding ([/ontology/go/0005544/annotation/page/1 calcium-dependent phospholipid binding]) proteins. In their N-terminal half
column3: copines contain two Ca(2+)- and phospholipid-binding domains (C2 domains) present in such proteins as phospholipase C and protein kinase C. Much of the C-terminal half consists of a von Willebrand Factor type A domain (VWFA) typically found in the extracellular portions of membrane proteins like integrins. Thus copines represent a fusion of intracellular (C2) and extracellular (VWFA) domains. However
column4: there are no signal sequence or hydrophobic transmembrane sequences in the predicted proteins suggesting copines are intracellular proteins. Copines are thought to be involved in membrane trafficking. It is of particular interest that copines
column5: first found in the highly phagocytic protozoan ''Paramecium'' and then isolated from mammalian spleen and liver
column6: seem to be abundant in cells and organs that are
column8: phagocytes. In this context it comes as no surprise that phagocytic ''Dictyostelium'' has a total of six copine genes[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16343335  (Damer et al. 2005)]. The widespread distribution of copines from protozoans to mammals and their high similarity suggest they play important role(s) in eukaryotic biology. column1: DDB_G0276025	Petra Fey	The ''zakA'' gene encodes a dual-specifity kinase with an N-terminal STE kinase related domain and a C-terminal TKL domain. DDB_G0271916	Pascale Gaudet	''rtoA'' was initially isolated by shotgun antisense cDNA as a gene required for [/ontology/go/0030587/annotation/page/1 sorocarp development] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8643519 Spann et al.
column2: 1996]). Defects in ''rtoA'' results in cells that have an abnormally high percentage of prestalk cells. Unlike wild type cells
column3: ''rtoA'' mutant cells' propensity to differentate into prestalk or prespore cells is independent of their position in the cell cycle at starvation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8951083 Wood et al.
column4: 1996]). RtoA levels vary during the cell cycle. During development
column5: expression of RtoA is restricted to prespore cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10747962 Brazill et al.
column6: 2000]). ''rtoA''- cells have aberrant regulation of calcium levels during the cell cycle
column7: indicating that [/ontology/go/0006874/annotation/page/1 cellular calcium ion homeostasis] may be linked to the [/ontology/go/0045595/annotation/page/1 regulation of cell differentiation] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11330860 Azhar et al.
column8: 2001]). The ''rtoA''- mutation affects the [/ontology/go/0006885/annotation/page/1 regulation of pH] in the cytosol as well as in the endocytic and exocytic vesicles. The RtoA protein contains several repeats of a serine-rich motif
column9: which catalyzes the fusion of phospholipid vesicles ''in vitro''. Consistent with a role in [/ontology/go/0006944/annotation/page/1 membrane fusion]
column10: ''rtoA''- cells have a defect in the fusion of endocytic vesicles and decreased [/ontology/go/0006887/annotation/page/1 exocytosis] rates ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10747962 Brazill et al.
column11:
2000]).
Partial uppression of the ''rtoA'' phenotype can be observed in an insertional mutant that disrupts both [/gene/DDB_G0275689 abcG2] and [/gene/DDB_G0275687 abcG18] (''mdrA1/mdrA2''). The triple null ''abcG2-/abcG18-/rtoA-'' has greatly reduced endocytosis rates. Also
column12: the cytosolic and endosomal pH of ''abcG2-/abcG18-/rtoA-'' are abnormal
column13: indicating that the product of these genes are required for proper [/ontology/go/0048388/annotation/page/1 endosomal lumen acidification] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11719559 Brazill et al.
column14:
2001]).
''rtoA''- cells are more resistant to infection by the pathogen ''Legionella pneumophila''
column15: probably because due to their defect in endocytic vesicles fusion ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15679845 Li et al.
column16: 2005]). It is also less efficient at phagocytosing the fungus ''Cryptococcus neoformans''
column18: ''C. neoformans'' replicates as well in ''rtoA-'' mutants as in wild type cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12933827 Steenbergen et al.
column19:
2001]).
A region of the ''rtoA'' promoter necessary for the response to osmotic stress have been identified (Tsujioka and Williams 2007
column20: personnal communication to dictyBase; the complete communication is available on the '''rtoA Community Annotation Page'''
column21: see link just above the Summary). The region between -144 and 256 relative to the start codon of the Curated Model is essential for up-regulation of ''rtoA'' following exposure to 100 mM sorbitol. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0272568	Petra Fey	''Dictyostelium'' cofilin-2 (''cofC'') was identified as a cofilin-related protein from the ''Dictyostelium'' cDNA project. It has significant homology to conventional cofilin [/gene/DDB_G0277833 cofA] and contains residues responsible for actin binding ([/ontology/go/0003779/annotation/page/1 actin binding]). Cofilin-2 was shown to depolimerize actin filaments ([/ontology/go/0030042/annotation/page/1 actin filament depolymerization]) in a dose- and pH-dependent manner and to decrease the viscosity of an actin solution
column2: but it did not co-sediment with actin filaments. In contrast to ''cofA''
column3: the cofilin-2 protein is not expressed in vegetative cells but predominantely during aggregation. Immunohistochemistry showed that cofilin-2 colocalized with actin at substrate adhesion sites. However
column4: disruption of the ''cofC'' gene did not result in any adhesion defect
column5: mutants appeared to be normal. Cofilin-2 did not rescue a yeast mutant deficient in conventional cofilin
column6: suggesting ''cofC'' has different function(s) than ''cofA''. Aggregation-specific expression suggests ''cofC'' plays a role in destabilizing the actin cytoskeleton ([/ontology/go/0015629/annotation/page/1 actin cytoskeleton]) during development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11683919  (Aizawa et al.

DDB_G0277859	Petra Fey	The ''mlcE'' gene codes for the essential myosin light chain (ELC) of myosin II. Antisense or mlcE-null mutants resemble [/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA] mutants. They grow poorly in suspension and become large and multinucleate. Despite the cytokinesis ([/ontology/go/0000910/annotation/page/1 cytokinesis]) defect myosin localizaion in the cells was shown to be normal. While mlcE- cells are able to respond to chemoattractant with proper directionality
column2: their rate of movement is reduced ([/ontology/go/0006928/annotation/page/1 cell motility]). Aggregation is delayed
column3: and only 50 % of the aggregates progress further to form shorter fruiting bodies with thicker stalks ([/ontology/go/0030587/annotation/page/1 sorocarp development]). Studies using lacZ reporter constructs expressed from cell type specific promoters showed the localization of prespore cells is more susceptible to the loss of ELC ([/ontology/go/0016477/annotation/page/1 cell migration]) than prestalk cells. In myosin purified from the mlcE- cells the actin-activated ATPase activity ([/ontology/go/0030898/annotation/page/1 actin-dependent ATPase activity]) was greatly reduced. This result and the proper localization of myosin in mlcE- cells suggest that its phenotypic defects primarily arise from defective contractile function of myosin rather than its mislocalization [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1535025  (Pollenz et al. 1992)]
column4:
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7593282 (Chen et al. 1995)].
Deletion mutations showed that both the amino and carboxyl termini of the ELC are required for binding to the myosin heavy chain (MHC). When these mutants were analyzed for their ability to complement the cytokinesis defect displayed by mlcE- cells
column5: a correlation to the level of ELC carried by the MHC was observed
column6: indicating that a stoichiometric ELC-MHC association is necessary for normal myosin function in vivo [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7499275  (Ho et al. 1995)]. The ELC wraps around an alpha-helix that extends from the myosin head
column7: where it is believed to play a structural support role. However
column8: substitution mutations of charged residues in loops I
column11: and helix G of the ELC lead to reduced actin-activated ATPase activity despite stoichiometric binding to the heavy chain. This result suggests that the ELC contributes to myosin's enzymatic activity in addition to providing structural support for the alpha-helical neck region of MHC [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9020178  (Ho et al. 1997)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0281899	Petra Fey	The ''drkC'' gene encodes the receptor-like tyrosine kinase VSK3 ([/ontology/go/0004713/annotation/page/1 protein-tyrosine kinase activity]) that is involved in [/ontology/go/0006909/annotation/page/1 phagocytosis]. Gene expression peaks in vegetative cells (0 to 2 hours)
column2: which coincides with the time cells feed by endocytosis. VSK3 null mutants showed defects in the fusion between phagosomes and lysosomes ([/ontology/go/0001845/annotation/page/1 phagolysosome formation]). In addition
column3: VSK3 is located in the late [/ontology/go/0030670/annotation/page/1 phagocytic vesicle membrane]. It has been shown that the N-terminus of the protein is located inside the vesicle
column4: whereas the C-terminal kinase domain resides in the cytoplasm where ATP is abundant for [/ontology/go/0005524/annotation/page/1 ATP binding]. ''Dictyostelium'' contains two more genes ([/gene/DDB_G0289791 drkA]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0289709 drkB]) that encode putative receptor kinases with an N-terminal signal peptide
column6: a transmembrane domain
column7: and a C-terminal kinase domain [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17664333  (Fang et al. 2007)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0268920	Petra Fey	The MADS-box (for the initials of the first identified members: MCM1
column3: Deficient from Arabidopsis and SRF from humans) is a in a highly conserved 60 amino-acid region that contain a dimerization and a DNA-binding domain. There are 4 proteins that contain a MADS box in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome: [/gene/DDB_G0281387 srfA]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0282835 srfB]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0268920 mef2A]
column6:
and [/gene/DDB_G0283483 srfD] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9729488 Escalante and Sastre 1998]).
Mef2A has been found to be more similar to animal Mef-2 proteins than to SRF proteins. Mef2A mutant strains show reduced growth when feeding on bacteria and are able to develop
column7: but spore production is significantly decreased. Prespore cell differentiation is greatly reduced and prestalk differentiation is slightly abnormal
column8: especially in the tip organizer. A comparison of the genes transcribed by mutant and wild-type strains during development indicates that prestalk gene expression is enhanced
column9: while prespore gene expression is decreased [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23577638  (Galardi-Castilla et al. 2013)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0284601	Petra Fey	CK2 (casein kinase II)
column3: is one of the most highly conserved proteins in eukaryotic cells. The protein kinase usually forms a tetramer
column4: comprised of two catalytic alpha or alpha' subunits
column5: and two regulatory beta subunits. The ''Dictyostelium'' [/gene/DDB_G0276885 casK] gene encodes a previously cloned CK2 alpha chain [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1448100  (Kikkawa et al.
column6: 1992)]. In addition
column7: the ''Dictyostelium'' genome contains another putative alpha chain [/gene/DDB_G0286481 DDB_G0286481]
column8: and a single ortholog of the CK2 beta chain
column9:
''csnk2b''.
The CK2 alpha chain encoded by [/gene/DDB_G0276885 casK] has been identified by PCR
column10: based on similarity. Northern blot analysis of [/gene/DDB_G0276885 casK] during development
column11: as well as CK2 activity ([/ontology/go/0004682/annotation/page/1 protein kinase CK2 activity]) throughout development both show a constitutive expression and presence of CK2 during the ''Dictyostelium'' life cycle. Attempts to delete the ''casK'' gene failed
column12: indicating that it is an essential gene [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1448100  (Kikkawa et al.
column16: only (haploid) cells carrying disruptions in both CK2 alpha chains are inviable [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2196445  (Padmanabha et al.
column17:
1990)].
Protein kinase CK2 represents a family of closely related kinases with broad specifity. There are hundreds of target molecules
column18: implicating CK2 in many signalling pathways ([/ontology/go/0007165/annotation/page/1 signal transduction])
column19: including such involved in cell survival. For recent reviews see [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12396231  (Litchfield
column24:
2002)].
The presence of a second putative CK2 alpha- and one putative CK2 beta chain in ''Dictyostelium'' suggests that the tetrameric holoenzyme in this organism consists of two different alpha chains and two identical beta chains. However
column25: currently there is no eperimental evidence that these putative genes are expressed and further investigation is necessary.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0273995	Petra Fey	The ''icmA'' gene encodes the conserved isoprenylcysteine carboxyl methyltransferase in ''Dictyostelium''. The protein was shown to have [/ontology/go/0004671/annotation/page/1 protein-S-isoprenylcysteine O-methyltransferase activity]. The ''icmA''-null mutant shows defects in early development
column2: such as no cell polarization ([/ontology/go/0030010/annotation/page/1 establishment of cell polarity]) or streaming
column3: aberrant cAMP wave formation
column4: and in some cases loose mound formation that may proceed to form aberrant fruiting bodies ([/ontology/go/0060176/annotation/page/1 regulation of aggregation involved in sorocarp development]). In the mutant
column5: the starvation-induced expression of the cAMP receptor [/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1] is delayed
column6: also reflected in the fact that mutant membranes bind only 34% of the CAMP that wild-type membranes bind. However
column7: in pulsed mutant cells the cAMP relay response is 3 times larger than in wild type. In addition
column8: Ras GTPase ([/gene/DDB_G0293434 rasG]) has been shown to be methylated and in the ''icmA''-null mutant RasG
column9: as well as CRAC ([/gene/DDB_G0285161 dagA]) are mislocalized in cAMP-pulsed cells. In sum
column10: these data show that isoprenylcysteine methylation is required for signalling in response to cAMP ([/ontology/go/0008277/annotation/page/1 regulation of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway]) and development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17699599 Chen et al. 2007)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0283983	Robert Dodson	The ''hnfA'' gene is DIF induced
column2: expressed in pstO cells and is essential for normal development. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21389049  (Blagg et al. 2011)] demonstrated that ''hfnA'' is important for the timing of culmination
column3: the regulation of slug movement and localisation of pstO cells. HfnA appears to regulate the activity of filamin complexes
column4:
which are in turn needed for phototactic slug migration and correct cell type motility and patterning during development. These studies provide the first step in defining the molecular relationship between the input DIF-1 signal and output cell type-specific behaviours that lead to sorting out.

DDB_G0277831	Petra Fey	A family of four highly related cell-surface receptors is responsible for the responses to cAMP at different stages of development in ''Dictyostelium''. The members are all 7 transmembrane G protein-coupled proteins but show different affinities to cAMP as well as different cell type specificities [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2049880  (Saxe et al.
column3: 1995)]. ''carD'' is expressed from late aggregation to culmination and encodes the low affinity CAR4 receptor that is enriched in prestalk cells and controls cytodifferentiation during late stages of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1537842  (Johnson et al.
column4: 1992]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7958880  Louis et al.
column5:
1994)].
CAR4 plays an essential role in regulating expression of certain prestalk specific genes by inactivating the protein kinase GSK3 (gene ''[/gene/DDB_G0272110 gskA]''). Furthermore
column6: CAR4 stimulates a protein tyrosine phosphatase that removes the phosphate from GSK3
column10: has a higher affinity for cAMP and activates GSK3 by stimulating the protein tyrosine kinase ZAK1 (gene ''[/gene/DDB_G0276025 zakA]''; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15380246  Kimmel and Firtel
column12: CAR3 and CAR4 antagonistically regulate GSK3 to establish cell fate choice. CAR3 signaling favors prespore differentiation and CAR4 signaling favors prestalk differentiation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12408804  (Kim et al.
column13: 2002)]. It has been suggested that cell-type specific expression of receptors with different affinities for cAMP directs pattern formation in response to regional differences in cAMP concentration ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7958880  Louis et al.
column14: 1994)]. Further studies indicated that the switching of cAMP receptor subtypes during development enables the organism to respond to changing concentrations of the chemoattractant and thus program morphogenesis appropriately [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9578623  (Kim et al.

DDB_G0277829	Petra Fey	A family of four highly related G-protein coupled receptors
column3: CAR2
column4: CAR3
column5: and CAR4 (genes ''[/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1]'' ''[/gene/DDB_G0288179 carB]''
column6: ''[/gene/DDB_G0277829 carC]''
column9: mediate developmental responses to cAMP [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2049880  (Saxe et al.
column11: 1995)]. CAR1 and CAR3 have 56% amino acid identity and show approximately equal affinity to cAMP in vitro [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1537842  (Johnson et al.
column12: 1992)]. Both are coupled to trimeric G proteins with the Galpha2 subunit. CAR1 is expressed immediately after the initiation of development while CAR3 onset of expression is in tight aggregates. There are approximately 5
column13: 000 CAR3 sites per cell. Disruption of carC does not result in an obvious phenotype [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8382181  (Johnson et al.
column14: 1993)]. Disruption of ''carA'' on the other hand results in cells that are unable to aggregate but can still respond to added cAMP by relaying the signal and synthesizing cGMP as long as 100X higher concentrations of cAMP are used than needed for signaling in wild type cells. However
column15: a double ''carA'' / ''carC'' mutant lacking both receptors shows no response to cAMP and an abolished synthesis of cGMP phenotype [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7949426  (Insall et al.
column16:
1994)].
CAR3 has a high affinity for cAMP and activates GSK3 (gene ''[/gene/DDB_G0272110 gskA]'') by stimulating the protein tyrosine kinase ZAK1 (gene ''[/gene/DDB_G0276025 zakA]''; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15380246 Kimmel and Firtel
column18: the lower affinity CAR4 receptor stimulates a protein tyrosine phosphatase that removes the phosphate from GSK3
column21: CAR3 and CAR4 antagonistically regulate GSK3 to establish cell fate choice. CAR3 signaling favors prespore differentiation and CAR4 signaling favors prestalk differentiation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12408804  (Kim et al.
column22: 2002)]. It has been suggested that cell-type specific expression of receptors with different affinities for cAMP directs pattern formation in response to regional differences in cAMP concentration ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7958880  Louis et al.
column23: 1994)]. Further studies indicated that the switching of cAMP receptor subtypes during development enables the organism to respond to changing concentrations of the chemoattractant and thus program morphogenesis appropriately [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9578623  (Kim et al.
column24: 1998)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0278495	Petra Fey	One of the first enzyme activities seen to increase specifically during ''Dictyostelium'' development was alkaline phosphatase [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13563787  (Krivanek and Krivanek
column3: 1965 ]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5344104  Loomis
column4: 1969) ]. Both a 5' nucleotidase and a classical alkaline phosphatase contribute to the activity assayed with the chromogenic substrate p-nitrophenyl phosphate. Mutant strains carrying deletions of ''alp'' lack the classical alkaline phosphatase but retain the 5' nucleotidase; they develop just as well as wild type strains in the laboratory [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12717731  (Rutherford et al. 2003)]. In vegetative cells
column5: alkaline phosphatase is found in vesicles associated with the plasma membrane rather than with cisternae of the contractile vacuole complex [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15511086  (Clarke and Maddera
column6:
2004)].
The specific activity of alkaline phosphatase increases first in early development and is highest during culmination. It is expressed in prestalk regions during development and in the lower and upper cup of the fruiting body [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12204284 (Ubeidat et al. 2002)]. Synthesis of mRNA can be inhibited as early as 10 hrs after development onset without affecting the increase in alkaline phosphatase during culmination [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5344104 (Loomis
column7: 1969)]. Direct measurement by RNA-seq showed that ''alp'' mRNA had accumulated to near maximal levels by 10 hrs of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Since the enzyme does not accumulate significantly until culmination
column8: translation or enzyme stability appears to be subject to developmental regulation. Basic annotations have been added for this gene

DDB_G0287875	Robert Dodson	The ''dydA'' gene was identified through a bioinformatics screen for proteins with potential Ras/Rap1 binding domains. DydA was found to be a new member of the MRL family of adaptor proteins that localizes to the leading edge of chemotaxing cells. ''dydA'' null cells exhibit chemotaxis defects
column2: as well as elevated F-actin and assembled myosin II levels
column3: increased and extended phosphoinositide-3-kinase activity
column4: and extended phosphorylation of PKB and PKBR1. In addition
column5: DydA was shown to bind RasG
column6: and to be phosphorylated by glycogen synthase kinase 3. Based on these results
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23135995  Koelsch et al. 2013] propose that DydA helps integrate the function of several signaling pathways to regulate cell polarity and chemotaxis.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0277671	Pascale Gaudet	DNA-dependent RNA polymerase catalyzes the transcription of DNA into RNA using the four ribonucleoside triphosphates as substrates ([/ontology/go/0003899/annotation/page/1 DNA-directed RNA polymerase activity]). Three distinct zinc-containing RNA polymerases are found in eukaryotic nuclei: [/gene/DDB_G0275759 rpa1] for the ribosomal RNA precursor ([/ontology/go/0006360/annotation/page/1 transcription from RNA polymerase I promoter])
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0279193 rpb1] for the mRNA precursor ([/ontology/go/0006366/annotation/page/1 transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter])
column4: ([/ontology/go/0005665/annotation/page/1 DNA-directed RNA polymerase II
column5: core complex])
column6: and [/gene/DDB_G0277199 rpc1] for 5S and tRNA genes ([/ontology/go/0006383/annotation/page/1 transcription from RNA polymerase III promoter])
column7:
([/ontology/go/0005666/annotation/page/1 DNA-directed RNA polymerase III complex]).
RNA polymerase III is a multisubunit complex. The subunits encoded by [/gene/DDB_G0277199 rpc1] (ortholog of ''S. cerevisiae RPO31'')
column15: and [/gene/DDB_G0287707 rpc11] (''RPC11'') are unique to RNA polymerase III. Orthologs of ''RPC31'' and ''RPC17'' have not been identified in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome. Two subunits
column16: [/gene/DDB_G0291362 rpc19] and [/gene/DDB_G0282339 rpa5] (''RPC19'' and ''RPC40'' in ''S. cerevisiae'')
column17: are common to RNA polymerase I and RNA polymerase III and correspond to subunits 3 and 11 of RNA polymerase II. Subunits [/gene/DDB_G0291636 rpb5]
column21: and [/gene/DDB_G0283365 rpb12] are common to all three RNA polymerases ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12407181 Peyroche et al. 2002]
column22: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12381659 Schramm and Hernandez 2001]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0288769	Robert Dodson	Research by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22239817  Sultana et al. 2012] showed that CAP
column2: an important regulator of cell polarity
column3: determines aggregation
column4: cell adhesion and development in ''Dictyostelium discoideum''. Expression of CAP in ''acaA'' null cells led to the restoration of cell polarity
column5: streaming and aggregation defects in ''acaA'' null mutants
column6: but failed to completely restore development
column7: suggesting the requirement of ACA and associated signaling for this process. In addition
column8: the role of CAP in influencing the expression of cell adhesion molecules DdCAD1 and csA that mediate calcium-dependent and -independent cell adhesion
column10: suggested that CAP acts at the intersection of signaling to link cell polarization to aggregation
column11: cell adhesion and multicellular development. Basic annotations have been added to this gene

DDB_G0268144	Robert Dodson	The ''vwkA'' gene has been demonstrated to play a role in contractile vacuole dynamics and in hypo-osmotic shock survival [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19843280  (Betapudi et al. 2009)]. ''vwkA'' null cells display large numbers of engorged contractile vacuoles that fail to undergo proper fusion with the plasma membrane. The authors further show that vwkA- cells have an aberrant cortical myosin II organization
column2: and that perturbation of myosin II abundance or activity also results in defective contractile vacuole dynamics. Their results suggest a role for myosin II-based cytosolic tension in contractile function and for a role for VwkA in the regulation of these events.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0269424	Robert Dodson	''gxcB'' encodes a Rac guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF
column2: RacGEF). RacGEFs are key components of signaling networks in which they activate Rho family GTPases by promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP. GxcB contains a domain organization of three calponin homology (CH) domains in its N-terminus and a typical GEF domain composed of a diffuse B-cell lymphoma homology (DH)/pleckstrin homology (PH) tandem domain at its C-terminus. ''gxcB'' is maximally expressed from the vegetative growth phase to early stages of development
column3: with expression declining sharply after about 12 hr. of development. GxcB is localized to the cortical region and late endosomes. GxcB both binds to and bundles F-actin filaments. ''gxcB'' null mutants display slight irregularities in the organization of the actin cytoskeleton and a slight delay in development; however there is a 30% reduction in the rate of exocytosis in the mutant cells. These results suggest that ''gxcB'' is involved in a signaling pathway that is required for regulation of the actin cytoskeleton during exocytosis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16781009 Strehle et al. 2006]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0269610	Robert Dodson	''gxcT'' encodes a Rac guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF
column2: RacGEF). RacGEFs are key components of signaling networks in which they activate Rho family GTPases by promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP. GxcT localizes to the cytosol
column3: both in the presence and absence of cAMP stimulation. ''gxcT'' null mutants have defects in both growth and cytokinesis. The mutants also have a developmental defect
column4: failing to aggregate normally and forming smaller fruiting bodies. ''gxcT'' null mutants also have defects in chemotaxis to cAMP
column5: with a reduced speed of chemotaxis and decreased directional accuracy of movement toward the cAMP source. The mutant cells are less polarized than wild type cells
column6: and pseudopods often extended from the lateral sides of the cells. In response to cAMP gradients
column7: PIP3 production and Ras activation are not well oriented toward the cAMP gradient in ''gxcT'' null cells suggesting that ''gxcT'' orients the position of PIP3 production and Ras activation in a chemoattractant gradient. ''racE'' ([/gene/DDB_G0280975 racE]) null cells display many of the same phenotypes as ''gxcT'' null mutants
column8: and GxcT binds to RacE in a GST pull down assay. In addition
column11: and RacF1 ([/gene/DDB_G0269176 racF1]). These results suggest that GxcT has GEF activity toward ''racE''
column14: and that GxcT and RacE are involved in a signaling pathway regulating the stability and orientation of spatial sensing during chemotaxis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24248334 Wang et al. 2013])
column15: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26940518 Rivero et al. 2016]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0285433	Pascale Gaudet	In mammalian cells
column2: phosducin binds to G proteins and modulate their activity. Phylogenetic analyses revealed that there are three groups of phodsucin proteins. ''Dictyostelium''
column3: like mammalian cells and ''Drosophila''
column4: has one member from each group: [/gene/DDB_G0292850 phlp1]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0285433 phlp2]
column6: and [/gene/DDB_G0293848 phlp3]. Phosducins consist of an N-terminal domain containing three helices which binds the alpha subunit of G proteins
column7:
and a C-terminal domain which bears similarity to thioredoxin and binds to the beta/gamma subunit of G proteins.
Phlp2 lack many residues in the C-terminal region that are expected to be required for G beta/gamma binding. The cellular role of Phlp2 is unknown
column8: but appears to be essential for growth: null mutants divide for a few generations and die. The putative ortholog from ''S. cerevisiae''
column10: is also essential ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/199357 Blaauw et al.2003]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0283389	Pascale Gaudet	Rhesus proteins (Rh) are glycoproteins present on the cell surface of red blood cells in mammals and are involved in ammonium ion export ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12846905 Hemker et al.
column2:
2003]).
''Dictyostelium'' has two genes encoding proteins with significant similarity to Rh proteins
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0283389 rhgA] and [/gene/DDB_G0280059 rhgB]. RhgA is localized to the [/ontology/go/0000331/annotation/page/1 contractile vacuole]
column4: suggesting a role in osmoregulation. However
column5: analysis of a null mutant has not revealed any defect is the response to osmotic stress ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11220631 Benghezal et al.

column1: DDB_G0277889	Karen Kestin	Ammonia signaling is essential to the developmental program of ''Dictyostelium''. It is involved in regulatingchemotaxis
column2: the choice between slug migration and culmination
column3: and cell-type specification via differential geneexpression. Ammonia concentrations are regulated in part by environmental factors
column4: however
column5: cellular processes such astransport ([/ontology/go/0008519/annotation/page/1 ammonium transmembrane transporter activity]) and metabolism can alter intracellular concentrations. In the ''Dictyostelium'' proteome
column6: three putative ammonium transporters exist: [/gene/DDB_G0277503 amtA]
column8: and [/gene/DDB_G0267424 amtC]. The transcriptlevels of the three ''amt'' genes are constant throughout development
column12: are both distinct and complementary. The ''amtA'' gene is generallyexpressed in the prestalk regions
column13: although it is also found in the upper and lower cups of the sorus and in regionscontacting the substratum. The ''amtB'' transcript is observed primarily in prepore regions and in the spore region ofthe sorus
column14: but is absent from the upper and lower cups. Expression of ''amtC'' is similar to that of ''amtB''
column16: it appears transiently in the anterior tip during the first finger stage. Disruption of the ''amtC'' gene results in larger multicelluar structures and developmental arrest at the slug stage
column17: although a smallpercentage of slugs are able to fruit after 40+ hours of starvation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14686953 Follstaedt et al.2003]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0288287	Robert Dodson	''atg101'' encodes a homolog of human ATG101
column2: a small protein that associates with ATG13 in the ATG1 complex ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20603609 Calvo-Garrido et al. 2010)]. The interaction of Dictyostelium ATG101 and ATG13 ([/gene/DDB_G0269162 atg13]) was confirmed in 2-hybrid assays. Autophagy was strongly reduced in mutant cells lacking ATG101. Strains carrying null mutations in ''atg101'' form multi-tipped aggregates that fail to make normal fruiting ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26246495 Mesquita et al. 2015)]. The multi-tipped phenotype of mutants in ''atg101'' is similar to that of mutants in other autophagy genes ''atg6'' ([/gene/DDB_G0269244 atg6A])
column3: ''atg7'' ([/gene/DDB_G0271096 atg7])
column4: ''atg9'' ([/gene/DDB_G0285323 atg9])
column5: ''tipC'' ([/gene/DDB_G0267422 tipC])
column6: and ''tipD'' ([/gene/DDB_G0275323 tipD]). mRNA from atg101 accumulates throughout development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column7: 09-MAR-2017 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis and Ricardo Escalante

column1: DDB_G0286931	Petra Fey	The gene ''hephA'' was identified in a screen for suppressors of the HSB1 mutant
column2: where the gene [/gene/DDB_G0277399 piaA] has been mutated. Pia is part of the TORC2 complex
column3: and the HSB1 (G917A) mutation causes a temperature-sensitive abolished ACA (adenylate cyclase A; [/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA]) activity
column4:
leading to an abolished aggregation phenotype [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12413895 (Pergolizzi et al. 2002)].
The ''hephA'' gene encodes a predicted ubiquitin ligase
column5: containing a HECT and a PH domain in the C-terminal third of the protein (HectPH1). REMI mutants with insertions upstream of those domains rescued the HSB1 phenotype
column6: spontaneous chemotaxis and development were restored. While the obvious developmental phenotypes were rescued in the HSB1/HECTPH-Ko suppressor mutant
column7: ACA stimulation was not restored but bypassed. However
column9: the adenylate cyclase B ([/gene/DDB_G0267376 acrA]) was shown to play an essential role in the HSB1 rescue. When the ''hephA'' gene is deleted
column10: aggregation is delayed and development is asynchronous
column11: while sensitivity to cAMP is increased. These results indicate that inactivating the HectPH1 ubiquitin ligase increases the cellular sensitivity to cAMP
column12: allowing cell development in response to very low cAMP levels in the HSB1 mutant
column13: thus suggesting that HectPH1 is involved in the desensitization of cAMP signalling [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28049717  (Pergolizzi et al. 2017)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated 21-MAR-2017 PF; annotation contributions: PMID 28049717 Barbara Pergolizzi

DDB_G0292810	Robert Dodson	beta-glucosidase was one of the first developmentally regulated enzymes to be used as a stage specific marker in ''Dictyostelium''. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/4982890 Coston and Loomis 1969)]. Two electrophoretically separable isozymes were found to accumulate at different stages of development. Mutations in the ''gluA'' locus affected both the early and the late isozyme that appear to differ in post-translational modifications ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/57116 Dimond and Loomis 1976)]
column2: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6162850 Knecht and Dimond 1981)]. mRNA from the ''gluA'' locus is present between 2 and 6 hours of development and then remains at a low level until 16 hours when it accumulates again to reach a peak at 22 hours that is three fold higher than the early developmental peak ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8288612 Bush et al. 1976)]
column3: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. The GluA protein has a signal sequence at the N-terminus for secretion followed by a stretch of 49 polar amino acids that is cleaved off to generate the mature protein. Like other acid hydrolases in growing cells
column4: beta-glucosidase is found in lysosomes and secreted into the surrounding medium. During culmination ''gluA'' is expressed uniquely in the Pst 0 region of prestalk cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12796308 Maeda et al. 2003)]. Analyses of ''gluA'' null mutants indicate that beta-glucosidase acts as a block to selfing in macrocyst formation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/57116 Dimond and Loomis 1976)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column5: 20-JAN-2016 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

DDB_G0277503	Pascale Gaudet	Ammonia signaling is essential to the developmental program of ''Dictyostelium''. It is involved in regulatingchemotaxis
column2: the choice between slug migration and culmination
column3: and cell-type specification via differential geneexpression. Ammonia concentrations are regulated in part by environmental factors
column4: however
column5: cellular processes such astransport ([/ontology/go/0008519/annotation/page/1 ammonium transmembrane transporter activity]) and metabolism can alter intracellular concentrations. In the ''Dictyostelium'' proteome
column6: three putative ammonium transporters exist: [/gene/DDB_G0277503 amtA]
column8: and [/gene/DDB_G0267424 amtC]. The transcript levels of the three ''amt'' genes are constant throughout development
column9: as determined by RT-PCR ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14686953 Follstaedt et al. 2003]); however
column11: another group has found the ''amtA'' gene to be strongly expressed until after the post-aggregation stage ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17951519 Yoshino et al.2007]). Discrepancies were also found in the spatial expression pattern: Follstaedt ''et al.'' localized ''amtA'' to the prestalk cells using ''in situ'' hybridization; while cell separation followed by Northern blotting showed an enrichment in prespore cells (Yoshino ''et al.''). The ''amtB'' transcript is observed primarily in prepore regions and in the spore region of the sorus
column12: but is absent from the upper and lower cups. Expression of ''amtC'' is similar to that of '' amtB''
column14: it appears transiently in the anterior tip during the first finger stage. Disruption of the '' amtC'' gene results in larger multicelluar structures and developmental arrest at the slug stage
column15:
although a small percentage of slugs are able to fruit after 40+ hours of starvation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14686953 Follstaedt et al.2003]).
The ''amtA'' null mutant forms small aggregates and small fruiting bodies ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14686953 Follstaedt et al.2003]
column17: the mutant has increased intracellular ammonium levels and reduced extracellular ammonium levels
column18: indicating a role for AmtA in ammonium export. This defect in ammonium homeostasis is also associated with decreased spore viability ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17951519 Yoshino et al. 2007]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0284127	CGM_DDB	Gene has been comprehensively annotated
DDB_G0290009	CGM_DDB	Sepiapterin reductase (SR
column2: EC: 1.1.1.153) participates in the biosynthesis of L-erythro-tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)
column3: a co-factor for aromatic aminoacid hydroxylation
column4: nitric oxide synthesis
column5: and glyceryl-etherhydroxylation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10727395 Thony et al. 2000]). The first reaction in BH4 biosynthesis is catalyzed by GTP cyclohydrolase I ([/gene/DDB_G0288481 gchA])
column6: which converts GTP to dihydroneopterin triphosphate (H2-NTP)
column7:
which is transformed to 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin (PPH4) by 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin synthase (PTPS) ([/gene/DDB_G0279095 ptsA]). The diketo compound is reduced further to BH4 by SR through two consecutive reductions.
Cells in which ''sr'' has been knocked out still produce a small amount of pteridine (L-erythro-biopterin and D-threo-biopterin)
column8: possibly through a different pathway involving aldehyde reductase ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21256841 Choi et al. 2005]). The mutant exhibits decreased growth rates
column11: and increased sensitivity to oxidative stress. The authors propose that tetrahydropterines have an antioxidant function in ''Dictyostelium'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17976377 Kim et al. 2007]). Basic annotations have been added to this gene

DDB_G0272618	Robert Dodson	The superpathway of oxidative and non-oxidative branches of the pentose phosphate pathway serves as an alternative way to oxidize glucose. This pathway couples NADP in its oxidative reactions
column2:
thereby synthesizing NADPH. The net reaction for this superpathway is 3 glucose 6-P + 6 NADP+ + H2O <=> 6 NADPH + 6 H+ + 3 CO2 + glyceraldehyde 3-P + 2 beta-D-fructose-6-P. Enzymes involved in the pentose phosphate pathway are: glucose 6-phosphate-1-dehydrogenase ([/gene/DDB_G0273131 g6pd-1]); 6-phosphogluconolactonase ([/gene/DDB_G0292898 pgl]); 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase ([/gene/DDB_G0277885 gnd]); ribose-5-phosphate isomerase ([/gene/DDB_G0276711 rpiA]); ribulose phosphate 3-epimerase ([/gene/DDB_G0278275 rpe]); transketolase ([/gene/DDB_G0272618 tkt-1]); and transaldolase ([/gene/DDB_G0280909 tal]).

column3: ''atg1'' null mutants reduced transketolase activity
column4: suggesting the presence of a regulatory pathway between autophagy and the pentose phosphate pathway in ''Dictyostelium''. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26246495 Mesquita et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0278729	Robert Dodson	Basic annotations have been added to this gene
DDB_G0269162	Robert Dodson	''atg13''
column2: the Dictyostelium homolog of yeast ATG13 was found by 2-hybrid assay with the protein kinase ATG1 ([/gene/DDB_G0292390 atg1]) as bait ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26246495 Mesquita et al. 2015)]. ''atg13'' encodes an 88 kDa protein with a short N-terminus sequence with similarity to plant and fungal ATG13 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20603609 Calvo-Garrido et al. 2010)]. In addtion to ATG1
column3: yeast 2-hybrid assays also show that ATG13 interacts with ATG101 ([/gene/DDB_G0288287 atg101]) to form the ATG1 complex that helps initiate phagophore formation. The phenotype of ''atg13'' null cells is similar to that of of ''atg1'' null cells: no measurable autophagy occurs and the cells fail to aggregate or develop ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26246495 Mesquita et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0271138	Pascale Gaudet	The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column2: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column3: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export ([/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport])
column4: ([/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane]). Seven different families (A to G) have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column5: domain topology
column6: and function. ''Dictyostelium'' has 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication) and 11 ABCA family members: [/gene/DDB_G0291994 abcA1]
column17: One of the defining characteristics of the A family is the presence of a regulatory domain with multiple sites for phosphorylation by various protein kinases in the region after the first ABC domain [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 (Anjard and Loomis 2002)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0276885	Petra Fey	CK2 (casein kinase II)
column3: is one of the most highly conserved proteins in eukaryotic cells. The protein kinase usually forms a tetramer
column4: comprised of two catalytic alpha or alpha' subunits
column5: and two regulatory beta subunits. The ''Dictyostelium'' ''casK'' gene encodes a previously cloned CK2 alpha chain [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1448100  (Kikkawa et al.
column6: 1992)]. In addition
column7: the ''Dictyostelium'' genome contains another putative alpha chain
column9: and a single ortholog of the CK2 beta chain
column10:
[/gene/DDB_G0284601 csnk2b].
The CK2 alpha chain encoded by ''casK'' has been identified by PCR
column11: based on similarity. Northern blot analysis of ''casK'' during development
column12: as well as CK2 activity ([/ontology/go/0004682/annotation/page/1 protein kinase CK2 activity]) throughout development both show a constitutive expression and presence of CK2 during the ''Dictyostelium'' life cycle. Attempts to delete the ''casK'' gene failed
column13: indicating that it is an essential gene [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1448100  (Kikkawa et al.
column17: only (haploid) cells carrying disruptions in both CK2 alpha chains are inviable [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2196445  (Padmanabha et al.
column18:
1990)].
Protein kinase CK2 represents a family of closely related kinases with broad specifity. There are hundreds of target molecules
column19: implicating CK2 in many signalling pathways ([/ontology/go/0007165/annotation/page/1 signal transduction])
column20: including such involved in cell survival. For recent reviews see [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12396231  (Litchfield
column22: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12631575  (Meggio & Pinnal
column24: and [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12062170  (Ahmed et al.
column25:
2002)].
The presence of a second putative CK2 alpha- and one putative CK2 beta chain in ''Dictyostelium'' suggests that the tetrameric holoenzyme in this organism consists of two different alpha chains and two identical beta chains. However
column26: currently there is no eperimental evidence that these putative genes are expressed and further investigation is necessary.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0279925	Petra Fey	The ''mlkA'' gene encodes the myosin light chain kinase (MLCK-A). The MLCK-A was purified
column2: and found to phosphorylate ([/ontology/go/0004672/annotation/page/1 protein kinase activity]) the ''Dictyostelium'' RMLC (myosin regulatory light chain
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0276077 mlcR]) with high specificity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3032987  (Griffith et al.
column4: 1987)]. RMLC phosphorylation occurs only on serine residues ([/ontology/go/0004674/annotation/page/1 protein serine/threonine kinase activity]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3029131  (Berlot et al.
column5: 1987)] and S13 has been identified as the phosphorylation site [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7806572  (Ostrow et al.
column6:
1994)].
Despite the high sequence similarity of ''mlkA'' with calcium/calmodulin-dependent protein kinases
column7: including myosin light chain kinases from higher eukaryotes
column8: it was shown that there is neither a calmodulin binding domain ([/ontology/go/0005516/annotation/page/1 calmodulin binding])in the ''mlkA'' sequence
column9: nor calcium/camodulin-dependent activation ([/ontology/go/0004685/annotation/page/1 calcium- and calmodulin-dependent protein kinase activity]) of the kinase [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1651931  (Tan & Spudich
column11: in ''Dictyostelium'' whole cell lysates as well as in ammonium sulfate fractions
column12: no calcium/calmodulin-regulated MLCK-A activity was detected [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2380188  (Tan & Spudich
column14: two activation mechanisms of the MLCK-A have been identified: autophosphorylation at T289 ([/ontology/go/0046777/annotation/page/1 protein amino acid autophosphorylation]) in the C-terminal autoinhibitory domain
column15: and phosphorylation in the activation loop at T166 by a yet unidentified kinase [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8947030  (Smith et al.
column16: 1996a)]. Although the Dictyostelium MLCK kinase has not been identified
column17: rat calcium-calmodulin-dependent protein kinase kinase can be used as a surrogate activator of MLCK-A
column18: phosphorylating it on Thr-166 [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14570871  (Tokumitsu et al.
column19: 2004)]. Residues 283-288 function as an autoinhibitory sequence
column20: and although autoinhibition is fully relieved by T166 phosphorylation
column21:
removal of the autoinhibitory domain alone does not generate maximum enzymatic activity. Thus phosphorylation of T166 by an upstream kinase releases autoinhibition and increases the catalytic activity of the MLCK-A.
Early studies found that cAMP stimulation ([/ontology/go/0019933/annotation/page/1 cAMP-mediated signaling]) increases RMLC phosphorylation due to a transient activitation of the MLCK-A [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3029131 (Berlot et al.
column22: 1987)]. Liu and Newell reported that the MLCK-A in cGMP-deficient mutant strains failed to phosphorylate the RMLC in response to cAMP
column23: implicating cGMP in the regulation of MLCK-A activity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7983143  (Liu & Newell
column24: 1996)]. More recently it was shown that MLCK-A activation through T166 phosphorylation is indirectly activated by cGMP ([/ontology/go/0019934/annotation/page/1 cGMP-mediated signaling]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9789030  (Silveira et al.
column25:
1998)].
A ''mlkA''-null mutant was generated
column26: and
column28: showed a slight cytokinesis defect ([/ontology/go/0000910/annotation/page/1 cytokinesis]). The defect became more severe when cells were grown with heat-killed bacteria. However
column29: the cytokinesis inefficiency is mild in comparison to [/gene/DDB_G0276077 mlcR] and [/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA] mutants. Also
column30: different from those mutants
column31: ''mlkA''-null cells were able to complete development. Because there is still phosphorylated RMLC present in ''mlkA''-null mutants
column32: it has been suggested that there is at least one more kinase that phosphorylates the RMLC [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8901579  (Smith et al.
column34: it has been shown that MLCK-A is the only kinase that is responsible for RMLC phosphorylation during chemotaxis ([/ontology/go/0050920/annotation/page/1 regulation of chemotaxis])
column35: and that this process is activated by cGMP and [/gene/DDB_G0291079 gbpC] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16546177  (Goldberg et al.
column36:
2006)].
MLCK-A is in the CAMK group of the protein kinase superfamily. It is 48-51% identical to four other putative ''Dictyostelium'' CAM kinases ([/gene/DDB_G0275057 DDB_G0275057]
column40: it is not known whether one or more of these kinases represents other MLCK(s)
column41: or if the other ''Dictyostelium'' MLCK enzyme(s) are more distantly related.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0292758	Petra Fey	Mob1 was originally identified in ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' as a binder of [/gene/DDB_G0280995 mps1]
column2: a kinase involved in mitotic regulation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9436989 Luca and Winey 1998]). Mob1 serves as a substrate for Mps1 and functions to regulate the NDR kinases (nuclear Dbf2-related
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0278457 ndrA]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0288753 ndrB]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0284839 ndrC]
column6: and [/gene/DDB_G0289543 ndrD]) in mammals
column7: which are involved in cell proliferation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15067004 Devroe et al.2004]). The Mob1 family of proteins are highly conserved but have no characterized function. In ''Dictyostelium''
column14:
it does not cluster with Mob1 proteins from other species.
MobA has been shown to bind to [/gene/DDB_G0278457 ndrA] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21134080 (Kastner et al. 2011)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0278457	Petra Fey	The AGC family of serine/threonine protein kinases derives its name from the founding members: PKA (protein kinase A/cAMP-dependent protein kinase)
column3: and PKC (protein kinase C). Other subfamilies exist within the AGC group
column4: including Akt/PKB
column5: NDR (nuclear Dbf2-related)
column6: PDK (phosphoinositide-dependent protein kinase)
column7:
and RSK (ribosomal S6kinase).
There are 20 AGC family kinases in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome
column8: among those are 4 NDR group kinases
column13: [/gene/DDB_G0289543 ndrD]. NdrA has been shown to be involved in phagocytosis
column14: especially during the engulfment step. The protein localizes to the centrosome and during prometaphase to the spindle. In addition
column15: several proteins have been identified to bind to NdrA: [/gene/DDB_G0278969 empC]
column17: and [/gene/DDB_G0292758 mobB] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21134080  (Kastner et al. 2011)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
