DDB_G0269150	Pascale Gaudet	''lvsA'' was isolated as a mutant that has a large volume sphere phenotype. ''lvsA''- cells have a [/ontology/go/0000910/annotation/page/1 cytokinesis] defect similar to that of ''Dictyostelium'' clathrin heavy-chain mutants ([/gene/DDB_G0277221 chcA]) but less pronounced defects in[/ontology/go/0006907/annotation/page/1 pinocytosis] and [/ontology/go/0006909/annotation/page/1 phagocytosis].In addition
column2: ''lvsA'' null mutant has defects in [/ontology/go/0007032/annotation/page/1 endosome organization]
column3: as does [/gene/DDB_G0271504 lvsB] null mutant ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10588668 Kwak et al. 1999]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11865029 Cornillon et al. 2002]). Localization studies have shown that GFP-LvsA is primarily associated with the membranes of the contractile vacuole system and that it has a punctate distribution in the cytoplasm. In ''lvsA'' mutants the contractile vacuole becomes disorganized and calmodulin ([/gene/DDB_G0279407 calA]) dissociates from the contractile vacuole membranes. Consequently
column5: ''lvsA-'' mutants have an aberrant [/ontology/go/0006971/annotation/page/1 hypotonic response] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11872142 (Gerald et al. 2002)]. A truncated version of LvsA missing the 689 N-terminal amino acids rescues cytokinesis defects and partially rescues defects in osmoregulation of ''lvsA''- mutant. Further deletions resulted in the complete loss of LvsA function. The association of LvsA with the contractile vacuole is perturbed by the loss of [/gene/DDB_G0269130 phgA]
column6: a protein important for vacuole function. The exact function of LvsA is not known
column7:
but it has been shown to bind membranes ([/ontology/go/0005543/annotation/page/1 phospholipid binding])in a GTP-independent manner ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15086784 Wu et al. 2004]).
A double mutant in [/gene/DDB_G0280955 DDB_G0280955] and ''lvsA'' suppresses the large contractile vacuole phenotype of disgorgin-
column8: while overexpression of GFP-lvsA enhances it
column9:
suggesting ''lvsA'' is involved in the organization of the contractile vacuole ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18636095 Du et al. 2008]).

DDB_G0279343	Karen Kestin	The Aurora family of serine/threonine protein kinases ([/ontology/go/0004674/annotation/page/1 protein serine/threonine kinase activity]) were originally identified in ''Drosophila melanogaster''mutants defective in spindle-pole behavior. The name "Aurora" stems from the auroraphenomenon observed in the night sky over the polar regions. Both Aurora A and Aurora B kinases have been found in metazoans
column2: while only one Aurora kinase has been identified in ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae''
column3:
''Schizosaccharomyces pombe'' and ''Dictyostelium discoideum''. Aurora A kinases associate with the centrosome during mitosis and have been shown to be involved in proper centrosome positioning and spindle assembly. Aurora B kinases are localized to the equator of the mitotic spindle and are thought to play a role in kinetochore attachment to the microtubule spindle and other important events in mitosis.
The ''Dictyostelium'' Aurora kinase has been shown to have properties of both Aurora A and Aurora B kinases. Like Aurora A
column4: it localizes at to the [/ontology/go/0000922/annotation/page/1 spindle pole]s in early mitosis. Like Aurora B
column5: it binds to [/gene/DDB_G0267690 icpA] (DdINCENP) and localizes to the [/ontology/go/0005813/annotation/page/1 centrosome]
column6: the [/ontology/go/0051233/annotation/page/1 spindle midzone]
column7: and the late [/ontology/go/0032154/annotation/page/1 cleavage furrow] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18326585 Li et al.

DDB_G0282375	Pascale Gaudet	''amiB'' (aggregation minus B)
column2: was isolated as a REMI mutant that does not aggregate upon starvation ([/ontology/go/0031152/annotation/page/1 aggregation involved in sorocarp development]). ''amiB'' encodes the putative ortholog ofthe mediator complex subunit 13 med13 transcriptional co-activator involved in ([/ontology/go/0006367/annotation/page/1 transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter]). When starved
column3: ''amiB''- cells fails to produce cAMP. Moreover
column4: ''amiB''- cells do not turn off the expression of one of the growth-phase genes
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0278721 cprD]
column6: and fail to turn on the expression of [/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA] following starvation. The ectopic expression of [/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA]
column7:
[/gene/DDB_G0275445 mybB] or [/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC] rescues the developmental defect of the ''amiB''- mutant. AmiB is thought to play a role early in development by stimulating [/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA] expression which is essential for cAMP signaling ([/ontology/go/0007242/annotation/page/1 intracellular signaling cascade]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10651904 Kon et al. 2000]).
''amiB''- cells have aberrant morphology when placed in starvation buffer: rather than forming pseudopods
column8: they form larger locomotory structures ressembling lamellipodia of fish keratocytes. The distribution of actin
column10: and [/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA] in ''amiB''- mutant is similar to that observed in fish keratocytes. These results suggest that AmiB is important for [/ontology/go/0006935/annotation/page/1 chemotaxis] and [/ontology/go/0006928/annotation/page/1 cell motion] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15259052 Asano et al. 2004]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0275617	Pascale Gaudet	The TATA binding protein (TBP) binds TATA elements located upstream of the transcription initiation site. In general
column2: TBP is a known TFIID subunit
column3: the large (~750-kDa) multisubunit complex composed of TBP and TBP-associated factors (TAFs). It is a universal transcription factor
column4: required for initiation by all three eukaryotic RNA polymerases: [/gene/DDB_G0288449 rpc2]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0288257 rpb2]
column6: and [/gene/DDB_G0293560 rpa2]. TBP-TATA association nucleates the assembly of the transcription pre-initiation complex. The crystal structure of Arabidopsis TBP revealed a remarkable structure containing a new DNA binding fold
column7:
resembling a molecular "saddle" that sits astride the DNA (reviewed by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9618449 Hampsey] in 1998).
''D. discoideum'' TBP has been shown to be a component of TFIIIB
column8: which includes [/gene/DDB_G0281215 brf1] and [/gene/DDB_G0283405 bdp1]. The protein also interacts with the ORF1 proteins of non LTR retrotransposons TRE5-A and TRE5-B
column9: which both integrate upstream of tRNAs. The TBP structure has been determined and was found to be very similar to human TBP
column10: and brf1 and ORF1 binding sites have been mapped ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21900496  (Chung et al. 2007)]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0293850	Pascale Gaudet	The size of ''Dictyostelium'' fruiting bodies is controlled at least in part by a secreted counting factor (CF)
column2: a multisubunit complex. The role of CF in size regulation has not yet been elucidated
column3:
although a negative effect on cytosolic glucose levels has been observed.
NADPH-coupled aldehyde reductase reduces a wide variety of aldehydes to the corresponding alcohols
column4: including converting glucose to sorbitol ([/ontology/go/0042593/annotation/page/1 glucose homeostasis]). The levels of this enzyme appears to be regulated by CF. Cells in which the ''alrA'' gene
column5: encoding aldehyde reductase ([/ontology/go/0004032/annotation/page/1 aldehyde reductase activity])
column6: has been disrupted
column7: form aggregates much larger than wild type cells ([/ontology/go/0031158/annotation/page/1 negative regulation of aggregate size involved in sorocarp development]). ''alrA''- cells have reduced [/ontology/go/0006928/annotation/page/1 cell motion]. ''alrA''- cells secrete reduced levels of [/gene/DDB_G0274597 ctnA] and [/gene/DDB_G0273175 cf50-1]
column8:
two components of CF. This could explain why ''alrA''- cells form large groups ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14551196 Ehrenman et al. 2004]).
''alrA'' is highly upregulated by glutathione (GSH) depletion. The enzyme glutamate-cysteine ligase
column10: catalyzes the the first and limiting step in GSH biosynthesis. Null mutants in ''gcsA'' have an absolute requirement for exogenous GSH. ''alrA'' overexpression protects [/gene/DDB_G0284651 gcsA] null mutants from GSH depletion
column11: while underexpression makes the cells more sensitive. ''alrA'' also protects from the toxic by-product of glycolysis methylglyoxal
column12: by breaking it down to non-toxic lactic acid using GSH as a co-factor ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18990192 Choi et al. 2008]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0269196	Robert Dodson	''tubC'' encodes gamma-tubulin which is localized at the center of the microtubule aster where it forms a complex with Spc98 ([/gene/DDB_G0283909 spc98]) to nucleate polymerization of alpha/beta ??/?? tubulin (tubA
column3: ([/gene/DDB_G0269196 tubB]) dimers [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9275182  (Ueda et al. 1997)]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9427688  (Euteneuer et al. 1998)]
column5: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12018385  (Daunderer and Graf
column6: 2002)]. Microtubules radiate from centrosomes that are found ahead of the nucleus in migrating cells. The centrosome is repositioned shortly after the extension of a new pseudopod. If no reorientation occurs within 30 seconds of the extension
column7: the pseudopod is retracted. Centrosomes appear to stabilize the direction of movement rather than establishing where the cell will go. The morphological changes in centrosomes were followed through the cell cycle by labelling the organelle with GFP fused to gamma- ??-tubulin (Ueda
column9: 1999 9880333). About 100 different proteins contribute to centrosomal functions including the products of ''tubC''
column17: ([/gene/DDB_G0278809 cepG]). [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15548420  (Graf et al. 2004)]. The abundance of ''tubC'' mRNA is less than 2% that of tubA mRNA in growing cells but increases rapidly between 10 and 14 hours of development
column18: mostly in prestalk cells [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. ''tubC'' may have a critical role during culmination.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

This small 26 kDa protein binds to PdsA and reduces its affinity for cAMP about a thousand fold ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/230476 Kessin et al. 1979)]. mRNA from ''pdiA'' accumulates to a peak at 2 hours and disappears by 6 hours before reaccumulating to a second peak at 11 hours ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Addition of cAMP between 2 and 6 hours repressed the second peak ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7851634 Wu et al. 1995)]. ''pdiA'' null cells fail to develop spiral cAMP waves
column5: and aggregation territories and fruiting bodies are much smaller and more numerous than in wt ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9391092 Palsson et al. 1997)]. Both caffeine and adenosine rescued the ''pdiA'' null phenotype and induced formation of larger aggregates ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22269093 Jaiswal et al. 2012)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column6: 01-DEC-2017 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

DDB_G0287587	Robert Dodson	Starved Dictyostelium cells aggregate into groups of roughly 10(5) cells. Cells in which the ''smlA'' gene is disrupted form small aggregates. The ''smlA'' mRNA is expressed in vegetative and early developing cells
column2: and decreases at about 10 hours of development. The sequence of the cDNA and the derived amino acid sequence of the SmlA protein show no significant similarity to any known sequence. Immunofluorescence and staining of Western blots of cell fractions indicates that SmlA is a 35x10(3) Mr cytosolic protein present in all vegetative and developing cells and is absent from ''smlA''- cells. The absence of SmlA does not affect the growth rate
column3: cell cycle
column4: differentiation
column5: or developmental speed of cells. Synergy experiments indicate that mixing 5% smlA cells with wild-type cells will cause the wild-type cells to form smaller fruiting bodies and aggregates. SmlA appears to regulate the secretion or processing of a secreted factor that regulates aggregate size
column6: counting factor (CF) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8787732 (Brock et al.1996)]. Compared with wild-type or [/gene/DDB_G0274597 ctnA] countin cells
column7: ''smlA''- cells have large cAMP pulses and small cGMP pulses [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11371560 (Tang et al.2001)]. ''smlA'' null cells have decreased adhesion
column9: increased amounts of polymerized actin and the ABP-120 actin-crosslinking protein
column10: as well as increased phosphorylation and redistribution of myosin ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11090633 Roisin-Bouffay et al.2002]
column11: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11818526 Tang et al.2002]). The presence of adenosine rescued the ''smlA'' null decreased aggregate size phenotype and induced formation of larger aggregates ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22269093 Jaiswal et al. 2012)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0291970	Petra Fey	''Dictyostelium'' cofilin was identified through a search for actin monomer binding proteins ([/ontology/go/0003785/annotation/page/1 actin monomer binding]) in whole cell lysates. A 15 kDa protein was isolated and purified
column2: which was shown to depolimerize actin filaments ([/ontology/go/0030042/annotation/page/1 actin filament depolymerization]) in a dose-dependent manner and to decrease the viscosity of actin filaments. This activity was inhibited by phosphatidylinositides. Cloning the cofilin gene resulted in the identification of 2 identical genes
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0277833 cofA] and ''cofB'' that differed only in their intron and promoter sequence. When promoter activities were tested
column4: only ''cofA'' was found to be expressed
column5: predominantly in vegetative cells. No promoter activity was detected for ''cofB''
column6: suggesting that ''cofB'' might be a pseudogene. This data is in conflict with the fact that several ESTs have been detected for this gene. Attempts to delete the ''cofA'' gene failed
column7: while deletion of ''cofB'' yielded mutants with no detectable phenotype. This confirmed that ''cofB'' is not expressed and suggested that ''cofA'' is an essential gene [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7738034  (Aizawa et al.
column8:
1995) ].
Overexpression of ''cofA'' was shown to stimulate bundling of actin filaments ([/ontology/go/0051017/annotation/page/1 actin filament bundle formation]) in alpha-actinin ([/gene/DDB_G0268632 abpA]) -induced actin latticeworks
column9: probably by severing the filaments [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8636212  (Aizawa et al.
column10: 1996) ]. In overexpressing cells also showed that cofilin
column11: together with the actin-interacting protein [/gene/DDB_G0278733 DAip1]
column12: plays a pivotal role in reorganizing the actin bundles in response to hyperosmotic stress ([/ontology/go/0006972/annotation/page/1 hyperosmotic response]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10421841  (Aizawa et al.
column13: 1999) ]. To investigate the actin depolimerization activity of cofilin further
column16: that both native and recombinant cofilin sever actin filaments ([/ontology/go/0006972/annotation/page/1 hyperosmotic response])
column17: but to different extents [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10744862  (Ichetovkin et al.
column19: cofilin was found to be dependent on the MADS box transcription factor [/gene/DDB_G0281387 srfA]. The authors found an expression profile of cofilin that differed from that published for ''cofA''. While ''cofA'' expression was originally tested by promoter activity and later confirmed by western blot
column20: this analysis was done by Northern blot. As a consequence of the discrepancy the authors referred in their paper not to cofilin A ([/gene/DDB_G0277833 cofA])
column21: but to the identical cofilin B [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15075287  (Escalante et al.
column22: 2004) ].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column2: while nramp2/nramp1 double knockout strains display aggregation defects. Single and double mutants display differential sensitivity to cell growth under conditions of iron overload or depletion
column3: suggesting that Nramp1 and Nramp2 act synergistically to regulate iron homeostasis.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0277843	Robert Dodson	''scaA'' (sca1
column2: DG1105) was identified as a member of a Ras signaling complex
column3: termed the Sca1 complex
column4: which also includes the RasGEF proteins [/gene/DDB_G0284329 gefA] and [/gene/DDB_G0276963 gefH]
column5: and the protein phosphatase [/gene/DDB_G0283601 pppA]. The Sca1 complex regulates the RasC-TORC2-Akt/PKB pathway at the leading edge of chemotaxing cells and undergoes TORC2 and Akt/PKB-dependent negative feedback regulation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20493808 Charest et al. 2010]) .Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0268618	Robert Dodson	The ''pinA'' gene encodes a parvulin-type peptidyl prolyl cis-trans isomerase. ''pinA'' was shown to be a functional homolog of ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' ESS1. ''pinA'' null mutants have a decreased growth rate
column2: reduced spore formation and display abnormal prespore-prestalk patterning suggesting that ''pinA'' is important for growth
column3: cell patterning
column4: and cell differentiation. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27836548  (Haokipp et al. 2016)]Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0271686	Robert Dodson	''grlB'' encodes a member of the evolutionarily conserved family of seven transmembrane receptors that are coupled to G-proteins ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16735079 Prabhu and Eichinger
column3: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16527814 Taniura et al. 2006)]. GrlB is the major GABA receptor during early development where it is partially responsible for the prestarvation response ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23548898 Wu et al. 2013)]. Aggregation is delayed about 2 hours in mutants lacking GrlB. Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column4: 13-DEC-2016 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis; annotation contributions PMID:23548898 Chris Janetopoulos

column1: DDB_G0282461	Robert Dodson	''grlC'' encodes a member of the evolutionarily conserved family of seven transmembrane receptors that are coupled to G-proteins ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16735079 Prabhu and Eichinger
column3: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16527814 Taniura et al. 2006)]. GrlC is a member of the family of type 3 GPCRs that resemble metazoan GABA<sub>B</sub> receptors ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17501984 Prabhu et al. 2007)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column4: 15-DEC-2016 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

DDB_G0291117	Robert Dodson	NoxA ([/gene/DDB_G0289653 noxA])
column2: NoxB ([/gene/DDB_G0287101 noxB]) and NoxC are homologs of the heme-containing subunit of NADPH oxidase flavocytochromes that generate superoxide for defense and signaling. Each of them has 6 predicted transmembrane regions and uses 4 histidine moieties to bind 2 heme groups. Mutations that inactivate the ''nox'' genes in the genetic background of strain JH10 result in a developmental block at the tipped mound stage
column3: but have no effect on growth in association with bacteria. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950752  (Lardy et al. 2005)]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16367873  (Benghezal et al. 2006)]. A triple mutant in which ''noxA''
column5: ''noxB''
column6: and ''noxC'' are disrupted in the genetic background of strain AX2 develops normally
column7: but has defects in the defense response to bacteria. The Sentinel cells that normally provide innate immunity in slugs are unable to generate superoxide when all 3 of the ''nox'' genes are deleted. Reactive oxygen species (ROS) stimulate S cells to take up bacteria by phagocytosis and to release mitochondrial DNA nets that trap extracellular bacteria. ''noxA''/''noxB''/''noxC'' triple null mutants release very few DNA nets and fail to clear bacteria from the slugs. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26927887  (Zhang et al. 2016)]. ''noxA'' is expressed at high levels in vegetative cells and at lower levels during development. ''noxB'' and ''noxC'' are only expressed after 6 hrs of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950752  (Lardy et al. 2005)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0275687	Pascale Gaudet	[/gene/DDB_G0275689 abcG2] and ''abcG18'' are present in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome as a tandem. In insertional mutant that disrupts both [/gene/DDB_G0275689 abcG2] and ''abcG18'' (''mdrA1/mdrA2'') results in release from the developmental block and the suppression of the defect in initial cell type choice caused by loss of the [/gene/DDB_G0271916 rtoA] gene. AbcG2 is localized to the endosome. ''abcG2-/abcG18-'' cells have an endocytosis rate roughly 70% that of wild-type ([/ontology/go/0006897/annotation/page/1 endocytosis]). The triple null ''abcG2-/abcG18-/rtoA-'' has even lower endocytosis rates
column2: about 20% that of wild type cells. The exocytosis rates of ''abcG2-/abcG18-''and ''abcG2-/abcG18-/rtoA-'' are roughly that of wild-type. ''abcG2-/[/gene/DDB_G0275687 abcG18]-'' endosomes have an unusually high pH ([/ontology/go/0030641/annotation/page/1 regulation of cellular pH])
column3:
whereas ''abcG2-/abcG18-/rtoA-'' endosomes have an almost normal pH [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11719559 (Brazill et al. 2000)].
The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column4: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column5: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export([/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport]). Seven different families have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column6: domain topology
column7: and function. Sequences from the well-advanced ''Dictyostelium'' genome project have allowed to recognize 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication) of this superfamily. The ABCG family is characterized by the ABC domain preceding the transmembrane domain([/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane]). All of the members of this family in animals are half-transporters while all of the fungal members are full transporters with two ABC-transmembrane units. No members of this family are found in bacteria. ''Dictyostelium'' and ''Arabidopsis'' have members of both types[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012  (Anjard and Loomis 2002)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0267436	Pascale Gaudet	The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name. In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column2: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export. Seven different families (A to G) have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column3: domain topology
column4: and function. ''Dictyostelium'' has 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication) and 4 ABCF family members: [/gene/DDB_G0285997 abcF1]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0284047 abcF2]
column6: [/gene/DDB_G0275637 abcF3] and [/gene/DDB_G0267436 abcF4]. The ABCF family is characterized by two ABC domains and no transmembrane domains. [/gene/DDB_G0285997 abcF1] and [/gene/DDB_G0267436 abcF4] are the most closely related to GCN20 from yeast and so are candidates for translational regulators [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6420574 (Anjard and Loomis 2002)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0293002	Pascale Gaudet	''tagA'' is expressed at the onset of development and is required for the differentiation of a subpopulation of prespore cells. Wild-type cells express ''tagA'' in prespore cells and in mature spores. TagA appears to be required for the specification of an initial population of prespore cells in which tagA is expressed ([/ontology/go/0030154/annotation/page/1 cell differentiation]). ''tagA'' mutants elaborate multiple prestalk cell regions during development and produce spores asynchronously and with low viability. TagA appears to play a general role in [/ontology/go/0045595/annotation/page/1 regulation of cell differentiation] since ''tagA'' mutants express a spore coat protein gene
column3: within vacuolated cells that form part of the stalk and they express a prestalk/stalk-specific gene
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0269132 ecmB]
column5:
within cells that become spores[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12756178 (Good et al. 2003)].
ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters are [/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane] proteins involved [/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport] ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column6: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). ''Dictyostelium'' has 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication). [/gene/DDB_G0293002 tagA]
column9: and [/gene/DDB_G0286123 tagD] are members of the B family of ABC transporters. These four genes have a similar structure
column10: with a serine protease domain ([/ontology/go/0008236/annotation/page/1 serine-type peptidase activity]) N-terminal of the half-transporter
column11: a domain organization unique to ''Dictyostelium''. ''tagA'' is located on chromosome 6
column13: ''tagC'' and ''tagD'' genes are located next to each other on chromosome 4 and appear to have arisen by tandem duplications. They encode proteins that are more than 65% identical
column14: with the differences located mostly in the terminal regions. In the central region
column15: their nucleotide sequences are more than 95% identical([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 Loomis and Anjard 2002]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0287691	Pascale Gaudet	The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column2: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column3: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export([/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport])
column4: ([/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane]). Seven different families (A to G) have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column5: domain topology
column6: and function. ''Dictyostelium'' has 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication) and 13 ABCC family members: [/gene/DDB_G0280541 abcC1]
column18: and [/gene/DDB_G0280459 abcC15]. Transporters of the C family have been shown to transport glutathione conjugants as well as to export cadmium ions. They are always found as full transporters with two copies of the transmembrane-ABC unit. Many of the genes of this family in humans and other animals have an additional transmembrane domain at the N terminus [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 (Anjard and Loomis 2002)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0288061	CGM_DDB	Using an apoaequorin expressing strain
column2: Ludlow ''et al.'' showed that ''Dictyostelium'' posseses P2X receptors that facilitate rapid Ca<sup>2+</sup> influx in response to extracellular ATP and ADP. Deleting [/gene/DDB_G0272004 p2xA] or [/gene/DDB_G0288061 p2xE] did not influence this behavior
column3: suggesting these genes are not involved. However
column4: this study proposes possible roles for [/gene/DDB_G0275293 p2xB]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0275191 p2xC]
column6:
or [/gene/DDB_G0288335 p2xD] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18486207 (Ludlow et al. 2008)].
Most recently
column7: Ludlow ''et al.'' showed that p2xB and p2xE
column9: have ATP-gated channel activity when expressed in ''Xenopus'' oocytes. However
column10: Na<sup>+</sup> rather inhibited this activity to various degrees in these P2x channels
column12: and NH4<sup>+</sup> ions elicited a large response. Interestingly
column14: but not p2xE are permeable to Cl<sup>-</sup> ions. No such ATP-gated channel activity was found for p2xC and p2xD. All ''Dictyostelium'' P2x proteins localize to the [/ontology/go/0031164/annotation/page/1 contractile vacuolar membrane]
column15: and not to the plasma membrane like P2X receptors from other organisms. By using a protease protection assay on tagged receptors the authors demonstrated that the transmembrane loop region containing the agonist (ATP) binding site lies within the lumen of the vacuole. A quintuple p2xA/B/C/D/E null mutant in wild type background AX2 shows a reduced response to the calmodulin inhibitor calmidazolium
column16: suggesting a role of the ''Dictyostelium'' proteins in the [/ontology/go/0050848/annotation/page/1 regulation of calcium-mediated signaling]. The quintuple null mutant also shows a slight delay in its [/ontology/go/0006971/annotation/page/1 hypotonic response] when placed in water
column18: single mutants in a AX2 background do not show any osmoregulatory defect. Taken together
column19: this study suggests that it is still unclear which molecules are responsible for the extracellular purinergic response in ''Dictyostelium'' and it raises the possibility that the P2x receptors may play a role in the release of intracellular Ca <sup>2+</sup> stores in response to an ATP stimulus from within the contractile vacuole [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19833731  (Ludlow et al. 2009)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column2: Ludlow ''et al.'' showed that ''Dictyostelium'' posseses P2X receptors that facilitate rapid Ca<sup>2+</sup> influx in response to extracellular ATP and ADP. Deleting [/gene/DDB_G0272004 p2xA] or [/gene/DDB_G0288061 p2xE] did not influence this behavior
column3: suggesting these genes are not involved. However
column4: this study proposes possible roles for [/gene/DDB_G0275293 p2xB]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0275191 p2xC]
column6:
or [/gene/DDB_G0288335 p2xD] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18486207 (Ludlow et al. 2008)].
Most recently
column7: Ludlow ''et al.'' showed that p2xB and p2xE
column9: have ATP-gated channel activity when expressed in ''Xenopus'' oocytes. However
column10: Na<sup>+</sup> rather inhibited this activity to various degrees in these P2x channels
column12: and NH4<sup>+</sup> ions elicited a large response. Interestingly
column14: but not p2xE are permeable to Cl<sup>-</sup> ions. No such ATP-gated channel activity was found for p2xC and p2xD. All ''Dictyostelium'' P2x proteins localize to the [/ontology/go/0031164/annotation/page/1 contractile vacuolar membrane]
column15: and not to the plasma membrane like P2X receptors from other organisms. By using a protease protection assay on tagged receptors the authors demonstrated that the transmembrane loop region containing the agonist (ATP) binding site lies within the lumen of the vacuole. A quintuple p2xA/B/C/D/E null mutant in wild type background AX2 shows a reduced response to the calmodulin inhibitor calmidazolium
column16: suggesting a role of the ''Dictyostelium'' proteins in the [/ontology/go/0050848/annotation/page/1 regulation of calcium-mediated signaling]. The quintuple null mutant also shows a slight delay in its [/ontology/go/0006971/annotation/page/1 hypotonic response] when placed in water
column18: single mutants in a AX2 background do not show any osmoregulatory defect. Taken together
column19: this study suggests that it is still unclear which molecules are responsible for the extracellular purinergic response in ''Dictyostelium'' and it raises the possibility that the P2x receptors may play a role in the release of intracellular Ca <sup>2+</sup> stores in response to an ATP stimulus from within the contractile vacuole [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19833731  (Ludlow et al. 2009)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0280541	Pascale Gaudet	The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column2: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column3: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export([/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport])
column4: ([/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane]). Seven different families (A to G) have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column5: domain topology
column6: and function. ''Dictyostelium'' has 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication) and 13 ABCC family members: [/gene/DDB_G0280541 abcC1]
column18: and [/gene/DDB_G0280459 abcC15]. Transporters of the C family have been shown to transport glutathione conjugants as well as to export cadmium ions. They are always found as full transporters with two copies of the transmembrane-ABC unit. Many of the genes of this family in humans and other animals have an additional transmembrane domain at the N terminus [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 (Anjard and Loomis 2002)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0275689	Pascale Gaudet	''abcG2'' and [/gene/DDB_G0275687 abcG18] are present in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome as a tandem. AbcG2 is localized to the endosome ([/ontology/go/0005768/annotation/page/1 endosome]). ''abcG2-/abcG18-'' cells have an endocytosis rate roughly 70% that of wild-type ([/ontology/go/0006897/annotation/page/1 endocytosis]). column3:
whereas ''abcG2-/abcG18-/rtoA-'' endosomes have an almost normal pH [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11719559 (Brazill et al. 2000)].

DDB_G0269214	Pascale Gaudet	The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column2: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column3: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export ([/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport]). Seven different families have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column4: domain topology
column5: and function. Sequences from the well-advanced ''Dictyostelium'' genome project have allowed to recognize 71 members of this superfamily (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication). The ABCG family is characterized by the ABC domain preceding the transmembrane domain ([/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane]). All of the members of this family in animals are half-transporters while all of the fungal members are full transporters with two ABC-transmembrane units. No members of this family are found in bacteria. ''Dictyostelium'' and ''Arabidopsis'' have members of both types ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 Anjard and Loomis 2002]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ([/ontology/go/0042626/annotation/page/1 ATPase activity
column2: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances]). In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column3: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export ([/ontology/go/0006810/annotation/page/1 transport]). Seven different families have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column4: domain topology
column5: and function. Sequences from the well-advanced ''Dictyostelium'' genome project have allowed to recognize 71 members of this superfamily (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication). The ABCG family is characterized by the ABC domain preceding the transmembrane domain ([/ontology/go/0016021/annotation/page/1 integral to membrane]). All of the members of this family in animals are half-transporters while all of the fungal members are full transporters with two ABC-transmembrane units. No members of this family are found in bacteria. ''Dictyostelium'' and ''Arabidopsis'' have members of both types ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 Anjard and Loomis 2002]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0275011	Robert Dodson	To investigate the minimal requirements for chemotaxis
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22081140  Kortholt et al. 2011] obtained quantitative data on Ras activation and chemotaxis in cAMP and folic acid gradients using a variety of Dictyostelium mutant cell lines from the four signaling pathways that contribute to chemotaxis: PI3K
column3: TorC2
column4: PLA2
column5: and sGC. Their results demonstrate that Ras is activated at the leading edge
column6: through a pathway consisting of G-alpha/beta/gamma
column7: which does not depend on either of the four pathways. The authors measured chemotaxis of mutant cells exposed to cAMP gradients with different steepness and found that many mutants will chemotax in shallow gradients
column8: despite a reduced sensitivity. Expression of multiple pathways increases sensitivity
column9: with some combinations of pathways exhibiting weak amplification while others produce good chemotaxis with strong signal amplification. The results of cluster analysis revealed that one cluster of signaling pathways
column11: is involved in inducing orientation of the cell towards the gradient
column12: while a second cluster consists of cGMP + PLA2 and functions as a memory of current direction. Thus one individual pathway does not contribute strongly to chemotaxis
column13: but it can synergize with other pathways
column14: which together increases the sensitivity about 150-fold. These results suggest a conceptual model of chemotaxis in which a basal signaling module consisting of heterotrimeric and monomeric G proteins provides activation of Ras at the leading edge
column15: which is sufficient for chemotaxis.Basic annotations have been added to this gene

DDB_G0287101	Robert Dodson	NoxA ([/gene/DDB_G0289653 noxA])
column2: NoxB and NoxC ([/gene/DDB_G0291117 noxC]) are homologs of the heme-containing subunit of NADPH oxidase flavocytochromes that generate superoxide for defense and signaling. Each of them has 6 predicted transmembrane regions and uses 4 histidine moieties to bind 2 heme groups. Mutations that inactivate the ''nox'' genes in the genetic background of strain JH10 result in a developmental block at the tipped mound stage
column3: but have no effect on growth in association with bacteria. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950752  (Lardy et al. 2005)]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16367873  (Benghezal et al. 2006)]. A triple mutant in which ''noxA''
column5: ''noxB''
column6: and ''noxC'' are disrupted in the genetic background of strain AX2 develops normally
column7: but has defects in the defense response to bacteria. The Sentinel cells that normally provide innate immunity in slugs are unable to generate superoxide when all 3 of the ''nox'' genes are deleted. Reactive oxygen species (ROS) stimulate S cells to take up bacteria by phagocytosis and to release mitochondrial DNA nets that trap extracellular bacteria. ''noxA''/''noxB''/''noxC'' triple null mutants release very few DNA nets and fail to clear bacteria from the slugs. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26927887  (Zhang et al. 2016)]. ''noxA'' is expressed at high levels in vegetative cells and at lower levels during development. ''noxB'' and ''noxC'' are only expressed after 6 hrs of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950752  (Lardy et al. 2005)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0287823	Robert Dodson	An ''lrrB'' disruptant strain grows and develops normally until the tipped mound phase
column2: but subsequent development is delayed by several hours and results in misshapen fruiting bodies. Gene expression in ''lrrB'' null cells is aberrant during growth
column3: including multiple genes that are either under
column4: or over-expressed. In addition
column5: LrrB was determined to interact with 3 proteins: FttB
column6: CldA
column7:
and CldB. The additional finding that 3 LrrB-regulated genes are similarly misregulated in a ''cldA'' disruptant strain suggests that LrrB and CldA interact to control gene expression during growth and early development. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20457612 (Sugden et al. 2010)]
Further research by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21396932 Sugden et al. 2011] characterized the role of ''lrrB'' in multicellular development. Slug formation in ''lrrB'' null mutants is delayed
column8: and the slugs are highly defective in both phototaxis and thermotaxis. ''LrrB'' also develops differently in the darkness than in the light; in the dark
column9: mutants arrest development as an elongated mound
column10: a process termed dark stalling by the authors. LrrB null slugs are defective in pstO prestalk cell differentiation and display aberrant gene expression patterns
column11: including reduced expression of the ecmB gene. In addition
column13: lacking a basal disc and sometimes containing multiple stalk fragments. These results suggest that LrrB is an adaptor protein which is active in diverse developmental signaling pathways. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0286069	Robert Dodson	DNA double-strand breaks (DSBs) can be repaired by either non-homologous end-joining (NHEJ) or homologous recombination (HR). In vertebrates
column2: NHEJ is initated when Ku70/Ku80 heterodimers bind to DNA ends and recruit the catalytic subunit of DNA-dependent protein kinase (DNA-PKcs). Homologs of these components in Dictyostelium are encoded by ''ku70''
column4: and ''dnapkcs'' ([/gene/DDB_G0281167 dnapkcs]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16243037  (Hudson et al. 2005)]. Both Ku70 and Ku80 are members of the family of ATP-dependent DNA helicases and are coordinately expressed during growth and early development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16112620  (Block and Lees-Miller
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Poly ADP-ribose is generated by the polymerase Adprt1a ([/gene/DDB_G0278741 adprt1A]) at sites of DNA DSBs. Poly ADP-ribose polymers promote NHEJ by binding Ku70 at DSBs and attaching Ku80 [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21807880  (Couto et al. 2011)]. Ku80 has a C-terminal domain that binds DNA-PKcs together with the homolog of the DNA repair endonuclease Artemis
column8: that is essential for NHEJ [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16112620  (Block and Lees-Miller
column10: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16582628  (Hsu et al. 2006)]. Null mutations in either ''ku70'' or ''dnapkcs'' render recently germinated cells unusually sensitive to the DSB-inducing agent bleomycin. However
column11: these mutations have no effect on bleomycin sensitivity of populations of growing cells
column12: probably because DSBs can be repaired by the HR pathway in cells with two copies of each gene. Haploid cells emerge from spores in the G1 phase of the cell cycle where HR is inoperable; however
column13: growing cells are in G2 where HR can compensate for loss of NHEJ [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16243037  (Hudson et al. 2005)]. The DNA joining events that result in integration of plasmid sequences at random sites of double-strand cleavage during REMI mutagenesis appear to depend on the NHEJ pathway
column16: ''adprt1a'' and ''dclre1'' null mutants do not show the increase in plasmid integration seen in wild type cells transformed together with restriction enzymes [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21807880  (Couto et al. 2011)]
column17: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21536833  (Hsu et al. 2011)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column2: NHEJ is initated when Ku70/Ku80 heterodimers bind to DNA ends and recruit the catalytic subunit of DNA-dependent protein kinase (DNA-PKcs). Homologs of these components in Dictyostelium are encoded by ''ku70'' ([/gene/DDB_G0286069 ku70])
column3: ''ku80'' and ''dnapkcs'' ([/gene/DDB_G0281167 dnapkcs]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16243037  (Hudson et al. 2005)]. Both Ku70 and Ku80 are members of the family of ATP-dependent DNA helicases and are coordinately expressed during growth and early development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16112620  (Block and Lees-Miller
column5: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Poly ADP-ribose is generated by the polymerase Adprt1a ([/gene/DDB_G0278741 adprt1A]) at sites of DNA DSBs. Poly ADP-ribose polymers promote NHEJ by binding Ku70 at DSBs and attaching Ku80 [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21807880  (Couto et al. 2011)]. Ku80 has a C-terminal domain that binds DNA-PKcs together with the homolog of the DNA repair endonuclease Artemis
column6: Dclre1 ([/gene/DDB_G0277755 dclre1])
column7: that is essential for NHEJ [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16112620  (Block and Lees-Miller
column9: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16582628  (Hsu et al. 2006)]. Null mutations in either ''ku70'' or ''dnapkcs'' render recently germinated cells unusually sensitive to the DSB-inducing agent bleomycin. However
column10: these mutations have no effect on bleomycin sensitivity of populations of growing cells
column11: probably because DSBs can be repaired by the HR pathway in cells with two copies of each gene. Haploid cells emerge from spores in the G1 phase of the cell cycle where HR is inoperable; however
column12: growing cells are in G2 where HR can compensate for loss of NHEJ [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16243037  (Hudson et al. 2005)]. The DNA joining events that result in integration of plasmid sequences at random sites of double-strand cleavage during REMI mutagenesis appear to depend on the NHEJ pathway
column15: ''adprt1a'' and ''dclre1'' null mutants do not show the increase in plasmid integration seen in wild type cells transformed together with restriction enzymes [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21807880  (Couto et al. 2011)]
column16: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21536833  (Hsu et al. 2011)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0289653	Robert Dodson	NoxA
column3: and NoxC ([/gene/DDB_G0291117 noxC])
column4: are homologs of the heme-containing subunit of NADPH oxidase flavocytochromes that generate superoxide for defense and signaling. Each of them has 6 predicted transmembrane regions and uses 4 histidine moieties to bind 2 heme groups. Mutations that inactivate the ''nox'' genes in the genetic background of strain JH10 result in a developmental block at the tipped mound stage
column5: but have no effect on growth in association with bacteria. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950752  (Lardy et al. 2005)]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16367873  (Benghezal et al. 2006)]. A triple mutant in which ''noxA''
column8: and ''noxC'' are disrupted in the genetic background of strain AX2 develops normally
column9: but has defects in the defense response to bacteria. The Sentinel cells that normally provide innate immunity in slugs are unable to generate superoxide when all 3 of the ''nox'' genes are deleted. Reactive oxygen species (ROS) stimulate S cells to take up bacteria by phagocytosis and to release mitochondrial DNA nets that trap extracellular bacteria. ''noxA''/''noxB''/''noxC'' triple null mutants release very few DNA nets and fail to clear bacteria from the slugs. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26927887  (Zhang et al. 2016)]. ''noxA'' is expressed at high levels in vegetative cells and at lower levels during development. ''noxB'' and ''noxC'' are only expressed after 6 hrs of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950752  (Lardy et al. 2005)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0269024	Robert Dodson	''ate1'' encodes the highly conserved enzyme arginyltransferase which is responsible for the post-translational conjugation of arginine to the N-terminal aspartate or glutamate of a protein. Ate1 is localized to both the nucleus and cytosol
column2: and transiently relocates to sites of newly formed actin-rich protusions. ''ate1'' null cells lack focal actin adhesion sites at the substrate-attached surface
column3: and have defects in both cell-substrate adhesion and cell motility. Mass spectrometric analysis identified arginylation sites in actin and several actin-binding proteins
column4: suggesting a role for ''ate1'' in the regulation of cytoskeletal proteins involved in adhesion or migration. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30586322  (Batsios et al. 2018)].Basic annotations have been added to this gene

DDB_G0272004	Petra Fey	The ''p2xA'' gene is one of 5 ''Dictyostelium'' genes encoding putative P2X receptors. p2xA has been heterologously expressed in human HEK 293 cells and was shown to have ATP-gated cation channel activity. Mutation of conserved lysines (K67A
column2: K289A) or a conserved aspartate (D330A) to alanine rendered the molecule non-functional. This P2X receptor was also found to be sensitive to Cu2+ ions. Deletion of the ''p2xA'' gene in AX4 wild type cells led to extensive swelling of the cells when placed in water
column3:
indicating a defect in cellular water homeostasis. Addition to Cu2+ ions recapitulated the swelling phenotype. Expression of a p2xA-GFP construct localized p2xA to the contractile vacuolar membrane and rescued the defect in the null cells [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17625565 (Fountain et al. 2007)].
Using an apoaequorin expressing strain
column4: Ludlow ''et al.'' showed that ''Dictyostelium'' posseses P2X receptors that facilitate rapid Ca2+ influx in response to extracellular ATP and ADP. Deleting ''p2xA'' or [/gene/DDB_G0288061 p2xE] did not influence this behavior
column5: suggesting these genes are not involved. However
column6: this study proposes possible roles for [/gene/DDB_G0275293 p2xB]
column8:
or [/gene/DDB_G0288335 p2xD] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18486207 (Ludlow et al. 2008)].
Ludlow ''et al.'' also showed that P2xB and P2xE
column10: have ATP-gated channel activity when expressed in ''Xenopus'' oocytes. However
column11: Na+ inhibited this activity to various degrees in these P2x channels
column13: and NH4+ ions elicited a large response. Interestingly
column15: but not P2xE are permeable to Cl- ions. No such ATP-gated channel activity was found for P2xC and P2xD. All ''Dictyostelium'' P2x proteins localize to the contractile vacuolar membrane
column16: and not to the plasma membrane like P2x receptors from other organisms. The transmembrane loop region containing the agonist (ATP) binding site lies within the lumen of the vacuole. Also
column17: A quintuple ''p2xA/B/C/D/E'' null mutant in wild type AX2 shows a reduced response to the calmodulin inhibitor calmidazolium
column18: suggesting a role of the ''Dictyostelium'' proteins in the regulation of calcium-mediated signaling. The quintuple null mutant also shows a slight delay in its hypotonic response when placed in water
column20: single mutants in a AX2 background do not show any osmoregulatory defect. Taken together
column21:
this study suggests that it is still unclear which molecules are responsible for the extracellular purinergic response in ''Dictyostelium'' and it raises the possibility that the P2x receptors may play a role in the release of intracellular Ca 2+ stores in response to an ATP stimulus from within the contractile vacuole [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19833731 (Ludlow et al. 2009)].
The study by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22736763 Sivaramakrishnan and Fountain 2012] reported that the P2x receptor ATP binding site faces into the vacuole lumen and ATP translocation triggers P2x receptor-dependent release of calcium. Thus the P2xA receptor in ''Dictyostelium'' is a calcium release channel. In a later study they reported that two commonly used laboratory strains of ''Dictyostelium'' display different phenotypes in response to hypotonic stress.The magnitude of contractile vacuolar calcium
column22: released in response to ATP
column23: differs substantially between AX2 and AX4
column24: with the magnitude of release being significantly smaller in AX2 cells [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23221467  Sivaramakrishnan and Fountain 2013]. The results confirm those from [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19833731  Ludlow et al. 2009] that AX2 cells are not dependent on ''p2xA'' for normal volume regulation
column25:
and also substantiate findings from [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17625565 Fountain et al. 2007] that ''p2xA'' is required for normal osmoregulation in AX4 cells.
Activation of P2xA results in calcium efflux required for downregulation of Rab11a (gene [/gene/DDB_G0269238 rab11A]) activity and efficient vacuole fusion. Vacuole fusion and Rab11a downregulation require the activity of CnrF (gene [/gene/DDB_G0276119 cnrF])
column26: an EF-hand-containing Rab GAP found in a complex with Rab11a and P2xA. CnrF Rab GAP activity for Rab11a is enhanced by the presence of calcium and the EF-hand domain. These findings support that P2xA activation results in vacuolar calcium release
column27: which triggers activation of CnrF Rab GAP activity and subsequent downregulation of Rab11a to allow vacuole fusion [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24335649  (Parkinson et al. 2013)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0288877	Petra Fey	The armadillo repeats that characterize beta-catenin in metazoa are found in the protein encoded by the ''Dictyostelium'' gene ''aarA'' (aardvark). Beta-catenin plays two independent roles in metazoa
column2: as a component in epithelial cell-cell adhesion
column3: and as an intercellular signal transducer in the Wnt signaling pathway. In ''Dictyostelium'' AarA was found to be a component of actin-associated adherens junctions holding cells together around the top of the rising stalk tube. Mutants lacking AarA form weak fruiting bodies that collapse easily. They also express the prespore marker gene [/gene/DDB_G0267412 pspA] at reduced levels [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11130075  (Grimson et al. 2000)]. If beta-catenin is directly acting to regulate transcription
column4: it is doing so in a manner unrelated to the metazoan Wnt signaling pathway. No ortholog of the intercellular signal Wnt can be found in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome. Likewise
column5:
the nuclear proteins TCF/LEF that are targeted by beta-catenin in vertebrates are missing in ''Dictyostelium''.
Dickinson and colleagues showed that ''Dictyostelium'' contains a polarized epithelium around the apical tip of the developing fruiting body. The deletion of ''aarA'' resulted in the disruption of this polarized protein organization. Accumulation of cellulose and EcmA/B in the stalk tube is strongly reduced in the mutant. Cellulose synthase ([/gene/DDB_G0269124 dcsA]) and EcmA/B ([/gene/DDB_G0277853 ecmA]
column6: [/gene/DDB_G0269132 ecmB]) are mislocalized intracellularly in tip epithelial cells but localization
column8: is unchanged in stalk cells. This indicates that tip epithelial cells are the primary source of secreted cellulose and EcmA/B in the stalk tube. Aardvark was also shown to bind the ''Dictyostelium'' alpha-catenin ([/gene/DDB_G0285939 ctnnA]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21393547  Dickinson et al. 2011)]. Furthermore
column9: both catenins are essential for apical myosin localization ([/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA]) during epithelial tube morphogenesis by regulating cortexillin ([/gene/DDB_G0289483 ctxA]) and Ras-GTPase ([/gene/DDB_G0287585 rgaA]) distribution
column10: thus eliciting a signaling function of beta-catenin in ''Dictyostelium'' [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22902739  (Dickinson et al. 2012)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column11: 10-JUN-2015 PF; annotation contributions: PMID 22902739 Daniel Dickinson; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

DDB_G0282289	Robert Dodson	Disruption of the ''dhkD'' gene resulted in an unusual phenotype. Aggregation occurred without streaming and resulted in motile mounds
column2: a phenotype termed the pollywog stage. After a period of random migration
column3: the pollywogs attempted to form fingers but mostly generated aberrant structures with no tips. While prestalk and prespore cell differentiation occurred with normal timing
column4: proper patterning did not occur. The pollywog phenotype was dependent on a functional RegA
column5: suggesting that DhkD functions to ensure the proper cAMP distribution within mounds. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24086589  (Singleton et al. 2013)]Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0269114	Petra Fey	Nucleomorphin is a calmodulin binding protein. The numA1 isoform was identified in an expression library screen for calmodulin binding proteins. This protein contains nuclear localization signals (NLS)
column3: and a glu/asp rich repeat (DEED). A GFP-numA1 fusion protein localized to patches in the nucleoplasm. Cells expressing GFP-NumA1 lacking the acidic DEED repeat showed an increased number of nuclei
column4: which suggests numA1 regulates mitosis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11919178  (Myre & O'Day 2002)]. A longer isoform
column5: numA2
column6: contains an additional BRCT (Breast Cancer C-Terminal) domain found predominantly in proteins involved in cell cycle checkpoint functions responsive to DNA damage. While the shorter transcript is uniformly expressed throughout development
column7: the larger transcript is expressed at low levels during vegetative growth
column8: increasing by 4 h to remain high throughout development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15535983 (Myre & O'Day 2004a)]. A two-hybrid screen using numA1 as a bait identified [/gene/DDB_G0283153 cbpD1]
column11: and this interaction required presence of the DEED domain [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15325281 (Myre & O'Day 2004b)]. It has also been shown that the NLS
column13: is sufficient for nuclear translocation of numA1
column14:
and that the nuclear localization is crucial for its ability to regulate the nuclear number [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15896312 (Myre & O'Day 2005)].
In normal development
column15: numA1 is highly expressed in vegetative cells and expression decreases 80% over the first 4 hours starvation. Differentiation inducing factor 1 (DIF-1) completely blocked the starvation-induced decrease in numA1. Conversely
column16: treatment of vegetative cells with cAMP or ammonia
column17:
decreased numA1 expresssion. These results show that numA1 expression is regulated by developmental morphogens [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19000924 (O'Day et al. 2008)].
In 2011
column18: mumA1 has been found to localize to nucleoli and to a lesser degree to the nucleoplasm in interphase. During mitosis
column19: numA1 relocalizes to the centrosome and nuclear envelope. Nuclear or nucleolar localization signals ((NLS/NoLSs) have been mapped [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21327858 (Catalano & O'Day 2011)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0284465	Robert Dodson	The ''cudA'' gene was identified in a random mutagenesis screen as being essential for correct culmination[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9226443  (Fukuzawa et al. 1997)]. ''cudA'' was found to localize to the nucleus
column2: and to be expressed both in a cone of cells at the extreme slug tip and in prespore cells. cudA- cells exhibit several phenotypes: they are defective in the expression of certain prespore genes
column3:
including [/gene/DDB_G0277141 cotC]; both stalk and spore formation are impaired; and cudA- slugs continue to migrate under conditions in which normal slugs culminate. The latter defect is corrected if the ''cudA'' gene is expressed in cudA- cells under the control of a promoter that selectively directs expression to the anterior of the prestalk region. CudA directly regulates ''cotC'' prespore gene expression by binding to a site in the ''cotC'' promoter. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18701541 Yamada et al. 2008]).
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10821768 (Fukuzawa and Williams 2000)] demonstrated that STATa ([/gene/DDB_G0281381 dstA])
column4: activates ''cudA'' expression in tip-organizer cells of the migrating slug. CudA directly activates [/gene/DDB_G0288331 expl7] gene expression there
column5: suggesting that ''cudA'' plays a transcriptional role in tip-organizer cell differentiation. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19757394  (Wang et al. 2010)]. For pstA-specific genes
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27125566  (Saga et al. 2016)] demonstrate two distinct signaling pathways downstream of STATa: CudA-dependent and CudA-independent. In addition to ''expl7''

DDB_G0291231	Robert Dodson	MHCK A ([/gene/DDB_G0291231 mhkA]) was the first myosin heavy chain kinase identified
column2: purified as a 130 kDa protein. It was found to phophorylate myosin II on the heavy chain (MHC
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA]) driving myosin filament disassembly [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3027076  (Cote & Bukiejko 1987)]. In this study MHCK A was found to phosphorylate threonine residues
column4: later these threonine residues were identified to be at positions 1823
column6: and 2029 in the tail region of myosin II [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2839474  (Vaillancourt et al. 1988)]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2387408  (Luck-Vielmetter et al. 1999)]. It was shown that MHCK A activity is activated by autophosphorylation
column8: and that the presence of myosin II increased the rate of autophosphorylation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2176841  (Medley et al. 1990)]. Furthermore it was shown that MHCK A has a high preference for threonine; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18381083  Luo et al. 2001]
column9:
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18381083 Crawley & Cote et al. 2008])) and neighboring peptide residues important for substrate specificity have been determined ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18381083 Crawley & Cote et al. 2008]).
In 1995
column10: Futey ''et al.'' cloned the ''mhkA'' gene encoding MHCK A and found that no part of the sequence displayed significant similarity to the catalytic domain of conventional eukaryotic protein kinases. However
column11: both native and recombinant MHCK A displayed bona fide kinase activity. In the 1
column12:
146 amino acid sequence they identified an N-terminal coiled-coil domain followed by a then uncharacterized central domain; the roughly 290 C-terminal amino acids were found to contain several G-protein beta WD-40 repeats [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7822274 (Futey et al. 1995)]. The WD40 repeat domain has been shown to directly bind myosin II and to facilitate myosin phosphorylation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11106661 (Steimle et al. 2001) ]. The central domain was later identified as the unconventional Alpha kinase domain found in all ''Dictyostelium'' myosin heavy chain kinases and in metazoan elongation factor 2 (eEF-2) kinases (reviewed in [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15050379 Drennan & Ryazanov 2004)].
Crosslinking [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7822274 (Futey et al. 1995)] and in vivo truncation studies [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9201999 (Kolman & Egelhoff 1997)] demonstrated that the N-terminal coiled-coil domain is responsible for protein homooligomerization
column13: confirming earlier observations that the 130 kDa protein eluted from gel filtration columns with a molecular mass greater than 700 kDa [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3027076  (Cote & Bukiejko 1987)]. Other studies showed that the coiled-coil region is responsible for direct actin filament binding in order to localize the enzyme to anterior F-actin-rich structures [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11959103  (Steimle et al. 2002)]. It has also been shown that the coiled-coil domain alone binds to F-actin and that this interaction increases the kinase activity 40-fold
column14: suggesting that MHCK A recruitement to F-actin rich sites leading to its activation may represent a mechanism for localized disassembly of myosin [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15545285  (Egelhoff et al. 2004)]. Furthermore
column15:
the coiled-coil domain represents a novel actin binding domain that is responsible for actin filament bundle formation and actin crosslink formation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16372899 (Russ et al. 2006)].
Deletion of the ''mhkA'' gene led to a strong decrease in MHC phosphorylation resulting in myosin II overassembly. However
column16: defects in the null mutant were milder than defects in cells that overexpressed ''mhkA''; the overexpressing cells showed an increase in MHC phosphorylation and a decrease in myosin II assembly. In addition
column17: these cells displayed reduced growth in suspension
column18: a cytokinesis defect when grown in suspension
column19: and an arrest of development at the mound stage [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8567716  (Kolman et al. 1996)]. These results are consistent with those in earlier studies; here cells that contained myosin that is nonphosphorylatable on MHCK A target sites (3XALA cells)
column20: or which is constantly pseudophosphorylated through introduction of aspartate residues
column21: (3XASP cells) were investigated [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7691416  (Egelhoff et al. 1993)]. However
column22: the amount of overassembled myosin was significantly lower in mhkA-null cells than in 3XALA cells
column23: suggesting other MHCKs participate. These results indicate that partial myosin overassembly is not highly deleterious
column24: but that hyperphosphorylation
column25: which inhibits myosin assembly
column26:
significantly reduces myosin II function in vivo [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8567716 (Kolman et al. 1996)].
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22899719 (Wessels et al. 2012)] found that MhckA and MhckC were essential for chemotaxis in a spatial gradient of Ca(2+)
column28: and reorientation in the front of waves of cAMP during natural aggregation. The phenotypes of mhckA- and mhckC- were highly similar to that of the Ca(2+) channel/receptor mutant iplA- demonstrating that IplA
column29: MhckA and MhckC play a selective role in Ca(2+) chemotaxis
column30:
but not cAMP and suggesting that Ca(2+) chemotaxis plays a role in the orientation of cells in the front of cAMP waves during natural aggregation.
''Dictyostelium'' has 4 very related myosin heavy chain kinases (MHCK A-D). Three of those (''mhkA''
column32: [/gene/DDB_G0290687 mhkC]) have been cloned and characterized. The fourth
column35: is very similar to the other MHCKs in sequence and domain structure
column36: making it likely to function as a MHCK (see review [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12952069  De la Roche et al. 2002)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0284839	Robert Dodson	Deletion of the ''ndrC'' gene [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24986648  (Mueller-Taubenberger et al. 2014)] resulted in a severe defect in cytokinesis and an aberrant numbers of centrosomes. NdrC was found to be localized to the centrosome
column2: and pull-down assays revealed that NdrC bound to RasB and RasG. In addition
column3: in ndrC- cells
column4: the levels of activated RasB and RasG are up-regulated
column5: suggesting a functional connection between RasB
column6: RasG
column7:
and NdrC.
The AGC family of serine/threonine protein kinases derives its name from the founding members: PKA (protein kinase A/cAMP-dependentprotein kinase)
column9: and PKC (protein kinase C). Other subfamilies exist within the AGC group
column13: and RSK (ribosomal S6kinase).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0280961	Robert Dodson	The first member of a two-component system
column3: functions in a signal transduction pathway regulating the terminal differentiation of prespore cells. DhkA was shown to be a transmembrane receptor for the signaling peptide SDF-2 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8670894  Wang et al. 1996)] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10373524  Wang et al. 1999)]. DhkA autophosphorylates a histidine residue
column4: and then transfers the phosphate to an aspartate in the carboxy terminal region from where it is relayed to a histidine in the small H2 protein RdeA ([/gene/DDB_G0282923 rdeA]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9582274  Chang et al. 1998)]. The phosphate on RdeA is in equilibrium with phosphate on an aspartate in the response regulator region of the cAMP phosphodiesterase RegA ([/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10488068  Thomason et al. 1999)]. Phosphorylation of RegA increases its activity which reduces the internal level of cAMP. When SDF-2 binds to the external CHASE domain of DhkA
column5: it converts the protein kinase to a protein phosphatase which reduces the activity of RegA and allows cAMP levels to increase ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15897458  Anjard et al. 2005)]. High levels of cAMP activate PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column6: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) which induces rapid sporulation in culminants.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column5:
a component of the ESCRT-I complex. Tom1participates in a minimal ESCRT-0 complex that could be recruited to endosomal membranes by its direct interaction with phospholipids and the support of Eps15. The authors propose that Tom1 participates in an ancestral ESCRT-0 complex implicated in the sorting of ubiquitinated proteins into multivesicular bodies.

column2: but the defects were much weaker. To test for redundant function

DDB_G0285995	Robert Dodson	The major extracellular cAMP phosphodiesterase is encoded by ''pdsA'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3023365 Lacombe et al. 1986)]. A signal sequence for secretion is cleaved from the N-terminus along with 49 amino acids. Transcription of ''pdsA'' is initiated at promotors 1.9 kb and 3 kb upstream of the translational start site during growth and early development
column2: respectively ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2157967 Faure et al. 1990)]. After 10 hours of development
column3: ''pdsA'' is transcribed only in prestalk cells starting from a third promotor that is positioned close to the coding sequence. The phosphodiesterase secreted by prestalk cells is necessary for slug and fruiting body formation but not for aggregation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7851634 Wu et al. 1995)]. Null mutations in ''pdsA'' result in non-cell autonomous defects in aggregation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9405107 Sucgang et al. 1997)]
column4: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19477920 Garcia et al. 2009)]. PdsA is part of the circuit that generates 6 minute oscillations in cAMP during aggregation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9843585 Laub et al. 1998)]
column5: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15131307 Maeda et al. 2004)]. It acts in the extracellular environment to reduce cAMP in the back of the wave and resets the oscillator ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23473502 Masaki et al. 2013)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0286121	Robert Dodson	TagC is a composite protein in which a serine protease is attached to an ABC transporter ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7744252 Shaulsky et al. 1995)]. It processes acyl coA-binding protein (AcbA) [/gene/DDB_G0270658 acbA] to generate the 34 amino acid peptide signal Spore Differentiation Factor 2 (SDF-2) that induces rapid sporulation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9473320 Anjard et al. 1998)]
column3: 2005)]. The protease domain of TagC is exposed to the external environment when gamma-Aminobutyric acid (GABA) signals through the surface G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR)
column4: GrlE ([/gene/DDB_G0291356 grlE]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16672332 Anjard et al. 2006)]. Since secretion of AcbA is also induced by GABA
column5: the two events are coordinated. Expression of ''tagC'' starts at 4 hours of development and is restricted to prestalk cells in slugs. Development of ''tagC'' null mutants is blocked at the tipped aggregate stage and neither spores nor stalk cells are made. The mutant phenotype is non-cell autonomous as shown by rescue of spore and stalk formation in the mutant cells by co-developing wild type cells. The wild type cells would be expected to generate SDF-2 that could signal nearby ''tagC'' null mutant cells. Tandem duplications on chromosome 4 generated ([/gene/DDB_G0286119 tagB])
column6: ''tagC''
column7: and ([/gene/DDB_G0286123 tagD]) which all encode membrane-embedded proteases ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 Anjard and Loomis
column8: 2002)]. The amino acid sequences of TagB and TagC are highly similar but they process different proteins into different signals.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0286119	Robert Dodson	The ''tagB'' gene was recovered from a REMI mutant that was blocked at the tipped aggregate stage ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7744252 Shaulsky et al. 1995)]. TagB is a composite protein with an amino-terminal serine protease section and a carboxy-terminal ABC transporter section. TagB processes the secreted precursor of Spore Differentiation Factor 1 (SDF-1) to generate the active phosphopeptide signal that prepares prespore and prestalk cells for terminal differentiation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21602484 Anjard et al. 2011)]. Expression of ''tagB'' starts at 4 hours of development and is restricted to prestalk cells in slugs. Development of ''tagB'' null mutants is blocked at the tipped aggregate stage and neither spores nor stalk cells are made. The mutant phenotype is non-cell autonomous as shown by rescue of spore and stalk formation in the mutant cells by co-developing wild type cells. The wild type cells would be expected to generate SDF-1 in the extracellular space that could signal nearby ''tagB'' null mutant cells. Tandem duplications on chromosome 4 generated ''tagB''
column3: and ([/gene/DDB_G0286123 tagD]) which all encode membrane-embedded proteases ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 Anjard and Loomis
column4: 2002)]. The amino acid sequences of TagB and TagC are highly similar but they process different proteins into different signals.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0273737	Petra Fey	Members of the casein kinase I (CK1) family of serine/threonine kinases have been implicated in many cellular processes. Casein kinases have been shown to phosphorylate the 14-3-3 ([/gene/DDB_G0269138 fttB]) protein in mammals
column2: play a role in Wnt signaling in ''Xenopus laevis'' and ''Caenorhabditis elegans''
column3: and maintain circadian rhythms in ''Drosophila melanogaster''. Additionally
column4:
CK1 plays a role in DNA repair in ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' and ''Schizosaccharomyces pombe'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10880352 Moreno-Bueno et al. 2000]).
Two casein kinase I family members have been identified in ''Dictyostelium discoideum''
column5: ''cak1'' and [/gene/DDB_G0292354 DDB_G0292354]. Cak1 is highly similar to CK1s in yeast and in metazoans. DDB0216336 is a putative casein kinase I that is highly similar to the CK1 subfamily tau-tubulin kinase (TTBK) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12471243 Manninget al. 2002]). The Cak1 protein has been shown to phosphorylate casein when it is expressed in ''E. coli'' cells
column6: and localizes to both the cytoplasm and the nucleus in immunofluorescence assays. Null mutations and overexpression of a dominant-negative form of Cak1 fail to produce viable cells
column7: indicating that this protein may be essential for growth. Overexpression of wild-type Cak1 results in decreased sensitivity to the DNA-damaging agent hydroxyurea; this suggests a role for Cak1 in DNA repair ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10880352 Moreno-Bueno et al. 2000]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0273725	Petra Fey	Dictyostelium Snf12 is an ortholog of yeast SNF12 and of human BAF60a. Both Dictyostelium Snf12 and human BAF60a possess a SWIB domain and a conserved COG domain. Snf12 localizes predominantly to the nucleoplasm and redistributes to the cytoplasm during mitosis. Under stress by addition of the antibiotic actinomycin D
column2: Snf12 relocalizes to the nucleoli where it is also visible in nucleolar regions atypically protruding from the nucleus. Snf12 contains three putative nuclear localization signals (NLSs)
column3: of which NLS-3 has been shown to be necessary and sufficient for nuclear localization [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22623154 (Catalano & O'Day 2012)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0283615	Petra Fey	''rpkA'' is a member of a characterized class of G protein-coupled receptors found in ''Dictyostelium'' and in the plant pathogen ''Phytophthora'' and that contain a phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate 5-kinase (PIP5K) domain at the carboxyl terminus of the protein ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16876997 Bakthavatsalam et al. 2006]). In ''Dictyostelium''
column2:
''rpkA'' is constitutively expressed and localizes to the endosome.
Null mutants in ''rpkA'' fail to aggregate at low cell density due to their inability to respond to cAMP and CMF (conditioned medium factor). The G protein domain of the protein is sufficient to rescue the developmental defects of ''rpkA''-. No role for the PIP5K domain in development has been found
column3: but this domain is required for proper localization of the protein. Double mutants in ''rpkA'' and [/gene/DDB_G0283349 gpaA] (G alpha 1) can bypass the developmental defect of ''rpkA'' nulls
column4:
indicating that RpkA is an effector of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17481898 Bakthavatsalam et al. 2007]).
RpkA is also involved in phagocytosis and in the response to infectious bacteria. The protein localizes to late phagosomes
column5: and colocalizes with and binds [/gene/DDB_G0287127 vatA] and [/gene/DDB_G0291858 vatM]. The PIPK domain binds predominantly monophosphorylated phosphoinositides and also phosphatidylserine and loss of RpkA leads to reduced levels of phosphoinositides ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22073313 Riyahi et al. 2011]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated
