DDB_G0290079	Robert Dodson	A branched heteropolysaccharide
column2: which consists of galactose and N-acetylgalactosamine
column3: is a primary constituent of the Dictyostelium spore coat. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18996984  West et al. 2009] found that disruption of either ''pgtB'' or ''pgtC'' reduced synthase-like activity and blocked heteropolysaccharide formation. Spore coats from an ''pgtB'' ''pgtC'' double null mutant expressed reduced levels of crystalline cellulose
column4: and also contained elevated levels of selected coat proteins. Mutant spores were unusually susceptible to hypertonic collapse and damage by detergent or hypertonic stress. These results suggest that the heteropolysaccharide is essential for spore integrity
column5: which can be explained by a role in the formation of crystalline cellulose and regulation of the protein content of the coat.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0268632	Petra Fey	The ''abpA'' gene encodes alpha-actinin
column2: a 95 kD protein originally isolated from the cell cortex. It forms a dimer
column3: crosslinks actin filaments into lateral arrays
column4: and increases the actin-stimulated Mg ATPase of myosin. Both activities are regulated by Ca2+ [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6746725  (Condeelis et al. 1984)]. The alpha-actinin molecule carries two characteristic EF-hand structures. The calcium-binding loops form the structural basis for the calcium sensitivity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3622778  (Noegel et al. 1987)]. It was shown that EF hand I has a low affinity for Ca2+ and EF hand II a high affinity
column5: implying a regulatory function of EF hand I in the inhibition of F-actin cross-linking activity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8486739  (Witke et al. 1993)]. This was confirmed when the viscoelastic properties of F-actin solutions in the presence of mutated EF hand structures was tested
column6:
and it was concluded that the first EF hand of alpha-actinin is crucial for its crosslinking function [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8561496 (Janssen et al. 1996)].
The phenotype of an alpha-actinin mutant
column8: which retained only trace amounts of alpha-actinin
column9: appeared to be normal [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3956480  (Wallraff et al. 1986)]. The lack of alpha-actinin was shown to only slightly affect cell substrate adhesion [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10411959  (Weber 1996)]
column11: and development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10704840  (Ponte et al. 2000)]. A redundancy in the microfilament system was suggested when two cytoskeletal genes
column13: were disrupted. The loss of both proteins severely affected growth and resistance to osmotic stress. It also resulted in reduced motility and phagocytosis rates
column14: and heavily impaired development. These changes were reversed by expressing either ''abpA'' or ''abpC''
column15: showing the defects to be due to the absence of the two F-actin cross-linking proteins [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1732064  (Witke et al. 1992)]
column16: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8937986  (Rivero et al. 1996)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0268168	Robert Dodson	Gene has been comprehensively annotated
DDB_G0290551	Petra Fey	The ''rblA'' gene is the Dictyostelium ortholog of the conserved retinoblastoma susceptibility gene Rb. ''rblA'' overexpression during growth leads to G1 arrest
column2: but as growing ''Dictyostelium'' are overwhelmingly in G2 phase
column3: ''rblA'' does not seem to be important in the normal cell cycle. ''rblA'' is expressed predominantly in pre spore cells and the null mutant shows a preference for the stalk pathway during development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16495312 (MacWilliams et al. 2006)]. Furthermore
column4:
it has been suggested that [/gene/DDB_G0285069 btg] genetically interacts with ''rblA'' in cell fate commitment during development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20300194 (Conte et al. 2010)].
Using microarray analysis and mRNA-Seq transcriptional profiling
column5:
it has been shown that rblA represses genes whose products are involved in S phase and mitosis. ''rblA'' also activates a set of genes unique to Dictyostelids that function in terminal differentiation during development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22768168 (Strasser et al. 2012)].
Bakthavatsalam and colleagues showed that RblA is necessary for the autocrine proliferation-inhibiting factor AprA ([/gene/DDB_G0281663 aprA]) to inhibit cell proliferation. In addition
column6: RblA is required for AprA-induced chemorepulsion
column8: Rb is necessary for a pathway mediating the effects of a chalone [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24390142 (Bakthavatsalam et al. 2014)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0291714	Robert Dodson	The ABC superfamily of genes is one of the largest in the genomes of both bacteria and eukaryotes. The proteins encoded by these genes all carry a characteristic 200- to 250-amino-acid ATP-binding cassette that gives them their family name ATPase activity
column2: coupled to transmembrane movement of substances. In bacteria they are mostly involved in nutrient import
column3: while in eukaryotes many are involved in export. Seven different families (A to G) have been defined in eukaryotes based on sequence homology
column4: domain topology
column5: and function. ''Dictyostelium'' has 71 ABC transporters (including one on the chromosome 2 duplication) and 11 ABCB family members: [/gene/DDB_G0293416 abcB1]
column6: [/gene/DDB_G0293438 abcB2]
column15: and [/gene/DDB_G0286123 tagD]. The B family includes three main subtypes: full transporters involved in multiple drug resistance (MDR)
column17:
and half-transporters involved in peptide transport [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12456012 (Anjard and Loomis 2002)].
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25448698 Miranda et al. 2014] show pharmacologically and genetically that ABC transporters mediate cAMP export. They identified several candidates and further characterized one
column19: in detail. RNAi-mediated knockdown of abcB3 results in delayed development and decreased extracellular cAMP levels. In addition
column20: ectopic expression of ''abcB3'' is sufficient to increase cAMP export in mammalian cells
column21: suggesting that AbcB3 is a component of the cAMP export mechanism in D. discoideum development. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0271676	Robert Dodson	The role of Nwk/Bzz1p-like protein (NLP) and Syndapin-like protein (SLP)
column2: in the regulation of the formation and trafficking of WASP-vesicles during chemotaxis was investigated by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19409937  Lee et al. 2009]. Deletion mutants of either ''nlp'' or ''slp'' did not cause significant defects
column3: but deletion of both genes causes the loss of polararized F-actin organization and significant defects in chemotaxis. WASP and NLP are colocalized on vesicles and interactions between the two are required for vesicle formation from Golgi. Microtubules are required for polarized trafficking of these vesicles as vesicles showing high directed mobility are absent in cells treated with nocodazole. Our results suggest that interaction of WASP with NLP/SLP is required for the formation and trafficking of vesicles from Golgi to the membrane
column4: which might play a central role in the establishment of cell polarity during chemotaxis. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column2: in the regulation of the formation and trafficking of WASP-vesicles during chemotaxis was investigated by [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19409937  Lee et al. 2009]. Deletion mutants of either ''nlp'' or ''slp'' did not cause significant defects
column3: but deletion of both genes causes the loss of polararized F-actin organization and significant defects in chemotaxis. WASP and NLP are colocalized on vesicles and interactions between the two are required for vesicle formation from Golgi. Microtubules are required for polarized trafficking of these vesicles as vesicles showing high directed mobility are absent in cells treated with nocodazole. Our results suggest that interaction of WASP with NLP/SLP is required for the formation and trafficking of vesicles from Golgi to the membrane

column1: DDB_G0272002	Robert Dodson	The ''egeA'' gene was identified during a REMI screen for mutants defective in early development. EgeA was found to be a cytosolic
column2: C2 domain-containing protein. ''egeA'' mRNA is expressed in vegetative and early development cells
column3: with expression reaching a maximum at the 2 hr. developmental stage. ''egeA'' null cells fail to form aggregates and do not enter development. Further
column4: the ''egeA'' null mutant expresses pre-starvation genes
column5: but fails to express early developmental genes required for aggregation
column6: such as cAR1 and GP80. EgeA over expressing cells display a similar phenotype to ''egaA'' null cells
column7: suggesting that an optimal level of Ege A is required for proper function. These results suggest that ''egeA'' is a novel cytosolic protein required for the induction of GPCR-mediated early gene expression [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12142016  (Zhang et al. 2002)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0278781	Robert Dodson	''D. discoideum'' Pah is the only aromatic amino acid hydroxylase in this organism and has phenylalanine 4-monooxygenase activity. Gel filtration showed this enzyme to form a tetramer. As the most efficient cofactor this enzyme requires DH<sub>4</sub> (''D-threo''-BH<sub>4</sub>)
column3: which is the major cofactor of metazoan PAH enzymes tetrahydrobiopterin binding. However
column4: ''Dictyostelium'' Pah cannot be activated by L-Phe like its metazoan counterparts. The low affinity for the substrate and the overall lower activity than human PAH may provide a constitutive level of activity in ''D. discoideum''
column5: pointing to an anabolic function of Pah in lower eukaryotes and bacteria. A more strict allosteric regulation of the enzyme by L-Phe seems to be needed in higher eurkaryotes. By determining the structure of ''D. discoideum'' Pah
column6: high similarity to human PAH in the catalytic domain was found. However
column7:
differing residues could be identified in the regulatory domain that might be important for cofactor selection and L-Phe binding ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18835579 Siltberg-Liberles et. al 2008)].
In vivo studies to clarify the roles of L-erythro-tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4) and its stereoisomer D-threo-BH4 (DH4) in ''D. discoideum'' suggested that BH4 is the preferred cofactor for Pah
column8: and that DH<sub>4</sub> functions mainly as an antioxidant ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21871890 Kim et. al 2011)]. In a subsequent publication
column9: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23017206 Kim et. al 2012] studied the regulatory function of Pah by characterizing the oligomeric status and kinetic parameters of both full-length and partial Pah constructs consisting of the regulatory
column11: or both domains. Their results suggest that phenylalanine activates Pah
column12: which is functional in vivo as a tetramer. In addition
column13: kinetic studies suggest that the regulatory domain of dicPAH may play a role different from that of the domain in mammalian PAH.Gene has been comprehensively annotated 19-FEB-2013 RD

DDB_G0284171	Robert Dodson	 The CHD (chromodomain-helicase-DNA binding) protein family is one of the major ATP-dependent
column2: chromatin remodeling factors that regulate nucleosome positioning and access of transcription factors and RNA polymerase to the eukaryotic genome. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24301467  Platt et al. 2013] identified three CHD orthologs (ChdA
column3: ChdB and ChdC) in ''Dictyostelium discoideum'' which are expressed throughout development
column4: but with unique patterns. ChdA shows the strongest similarity to human CHD subfamily I
column5: and ''chdA'' has low relative expression during aggregation and early development
column6: but increased abundance during terminal differentiation. ''chdA'' null cells exhibited a significant delay at the onset of culmination and displayed reduced chemotaxis to cAMP. Genome-wide (RNA-seq) transcriptome profiling for each CHD null strain revealed that the different CHDs regulate distinct gene sets during both growth and development. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0286663	Robert Dodson	Monoclonal antibodies were used to recognize a family of secreted proteins in the extracellular matrix (ECM) deposited on the substratum by migrating slugs ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7729573 Ti et al. 1995)]. One of them
column3: was shown to be a dimer of the 30 kDa product of the ''ecmC'' gene that associates with cellulose in the sheath. mRNA of ''ecmC'' first starts to accumulate at16 hours and peaks at 22 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. EcmC is unlikely to be essential for the formation of sheath at the mound stage because it is not expressed early enough
column4: but it could play an important role in the sheath at later stages of development. ''ecmC'' is a prestalk-specific gene.Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column5: 11-JUL-2016 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

column1: DDB_G0286647	Robert Dodson	''ecmD'' encodes a protein
column3: that has almost exactly the same size and amino acid sequence as EcmC ([/gene/DDB_G0286663 ecmC]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7729573 Ti et al. 1995)]
column4: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11488929 Wang et al. 2001)]. Both of these proteins associate with cellulose in the extracellular matrix (ECM) deposited on the substratum by migrating slugs. However
column5: ''ecmD'' mRNA starts to accumulate at 11 hours of development
column6: 5 hours earlier than ''ecmC'' mRNA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Therefore
column7: it could be an essential component of the sheath formed at the mound stage. ''ecmD'' is a prestalk-specific gene.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0292224	Robert Dodson	''ecmG'' encodes a protein
column3: with a similar size and amino acid sequence as EcmH ([/gene/DDB_G0292220 ecmH]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11488929 Wang et al. 2001)]. Both of these proteins associate with cellulose in the extracellular matrix (ECM) deposited on the substratum by migrating slugs. However
column4: ''ecmG'' mRNA starts to accumulate at 11 hours of development
column5: 5 hours earlier than ''ecmH'' mRNA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)].Therefore
column6: it could be an essential component of the sheath formed at the mound stage. ''ecmG'' is a prestalk-specific gene that is dependent on the transcription factor STATa for expression ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15309638 Shimada et al. 2004)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0272861	Robert Dodson	''cosA'' was identified by a genetic screen in ''D. discoideum'' for chemotaxis-defective mutants. Its gene product 'costars' belongs to the costars family
column2: and has sequence similarity to the C-terminal region of the mammalian protein striated muscle activator of Rho signaling (STARS). ''cosA'' expression has been shown to be developmental regulated

column1: DDB_G0288511	Petra Fey	The ''sadA'' gene has been identified by its disruption in a substrate adhesion-deficient REMI mutant. SadA- cells grow in plastic dishes without attaching to the substrate. The sadA- mutant also shows slightly impaired cytokinesis
column3: and a phagocytosis defect. Deletion of the sadA gene by homologous recombination recreated the original mutant phenotype. Expression of sadA-GFP in sadA-null cells restored the wild-type phenotype. SadA-GFP localized to the cell surface
column4: appropriate for an adhesion molecule. SadA contains nine putative transmembrane domains and three conserved EGF-like repeats in a predicted extracellular domain. EGF repeats are found in proteins known to be involved in adhesion
column5: such as tenascins and integrins
column6:
suggesting that sadA is the first substrate adhesion receptor to be identified in Dictyostelium [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12499361 (Fey et al. 2002)].
Kowal and Chisholm showed that the cytoplasmic tail of the SadA protein has an important function in cell-substrate adhesion. A SadA tailless mutant was unable to rescue the sadA adhesion deficiency and overexpression of the SadA tail domain reduced adhesion in wild-type cells. Mutation analysis revealed that the phosphorylation status of serine residues in the tail region plays a role in adhesion. In fractionation assays SadA was found in the insoluble fraction and was also identified to interact with the actin bundling protein Cortexillin I ([/gene/DDB_G0289483 ctxA]). This might suggest that phosphorylation/dephosphorylation regulates adhesion through the binding of SadA to Cortexillin I [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21441344 (Kowal and Chisholm 2011)].
SadA also plays a role in cell adhesion by controlling the levels of [/gene/DDB_G0287363 sibA] adhesion molecules at the cell surface by stabilizing the intracellular SibA protein and possibly by assisting intracellular transport to the surface[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22219373 (Froquet et al. 2012)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column7: 27-SEP-2012 PF; annotation contributions: PMID 22219373 Pierre Cosson.

column1: DDB_G0285939	Petra Fey	The ''Dictyostelium'' alpha-catenin was first identified in a screen for proteins involved in adhesion during cytokinesis and described as a vinculin (''vinA'') with which it shares considerable similarities. It was found to colocalize with [/gene/DDB_G0274109 paxB] in focal adhesion-like complexes. Mutant analysis showed that its involvement in adhesion dependent cytokinesis
column2: or cytokinesis B. Myosin II is required for the contractile ring-dependent cytokinesis (cytokinesis A). A double mutant with mhcA disrupted adhesion on solid substrate completely
column3:
as both cytokinesis A were B are disrupted [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19065153 (Nagasaki et al. 2009)].
Dickinson and colleagues analyzed the structural similarity of the ''Dictyostelium'' protein with vinculins and alpha-catenins and found that it represents one of the earliest members before the branching of vinculins and alpha-catenins. everal experimental results were convincing that this protein is the ''Dictyostelium'' alpha-catenin homolog and the gene was named ''ctnnA''. CtnnA binds AarA
column4: the ''Dictyostelium'' beta-catenin ([/gene/DDB_G0288877 aarA])
column5: as well as the human beta-catenin. Depletion of ''ctnnA'' through RNAi resulted in a disruption of the polarized tip epithelium organization during development. Cellulose synthase ([/gene/DDB_G0269124 dcsA]) and EcmA/B ([/gene/DDB_G0277853 ecmA]
column6: [/gene/DDB_G0269132 ecmB]) are mislocalized intracellularly in tip epithelial cells but localization
column8: is unchanged in stalk cells. This indicates that tip epithelial cells are the primary source of secreted cellulose and EcmA/B in the stalk tube [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21393547  Dickinson et al. 2011)]. Furthermore
column9: both catenins are essential for apical myosin localization ([/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA]) during epithelial tube morphogenesis by regulating cortexillin ([/gene/DDB_G0289483 ctxA]) and Ras-GTPase ([/gene/DDB_G0287585 rgaA]) distribution
column10: thus eliciting a signaling function of alpha-catenin in ''Dictyostelium'' [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22902739  (Dickinson et al. 2012)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0287295	Petra Fey	ForC is a formin that lacks a typical FH1 domain but contains FH2 and FH3 domains; it also contains an N-terminal GBD domain. ForC null mutants were able to aggregate but unable to form slugs or develop into full fruiting bodies. Depending on the substratum

DDB_G0288179	Petra Fey	A small family of highly related cell-surface receptors is responsible for the responses to cAMP at different stages of development in ''Dictyostelium''. The members are all 7 transmembrane G protein-coupled proteins but show different affinities to cAMP as well as different cell type specificities. ''carB'' encodes the CAR2 receptor that is expressed briefly in prestalk cells following aggregation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2049880  (Saxe et al.
column3: 1993)]. Null mutations in ''carB'' result in the inability of mound cells to form a tip or progress further in morphogenesis. It appears that CAR2 is required for sorting of prestalk cells in mounds. While prestalk specific genes are expressed normally in null mutants
column4: the prespore gene pspB that encodes SP85 is expressed at >10 fold higher levels in carB- mutants than in wild type cells [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8436297  (Saxe et al.
column5: 1993)]. Mutations in ''[/gene/DDB_G0285253 scrA]''
column6: which encodes SCAR
column7: were selected that suppress the block to morphogenesis resulting from loss of CAR2 [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9732292  (Bear et al.
column8: 1998)]. It appears that CAR2 signaling normally inhibits SCAR to help regulate cell movement. CAR2 has also been implicated in the regulation of the prestalk pathway by facilitating the DIF induction of prestalk genes [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9742091  (Verkerke-Van Wijk et al.
column9: 1998)]. Comprehensive annotations have been added to this gene

column1: DDB_G0277845	Robert Dodson	''dhkB'' is involved in the cytokinin signal transduction pathway regulating spore germination. ''dhkB'' encodes a histidine kinase with several potential transmembrane domains but no extracellular loops of more than 10 amino acids. Spores from ''dhkB'' null cells germinate precociously
column2: a phenotype that is suppressed by ectopic activation of or expression of protein kinase A (PKA) ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9576830 Zinda and Singleton 1998)]. Spores lacking DhkB germinate precociously because they do not respond to the cytokinin germination inhibitor
column4: discadenine
column5: by an increase in internal cAMP. Cytokinins accelerate sporulation in wild type cells
column6: but not in dhkB null mutants ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18216168 Anjard and Loomis 2008)]. The same phenotype is observed in mutants lacking the late adenylyl cyclase AcrA ([/gene/DDB_G0267376 acrA])
column7: that can function as part of a two-component system by accepting a phosphate in its response regulator region. The response to cytokinins is independent of the sole H2 protein of Dictyostelium
column9: and so does not use the standard phosphorelay pathway. It is possible that cytokinins stimulate direct phosphorelay between DhkB and AcrA which results in an increase in the level of cAMP. Pharmaceutical stimulation of cAMP and PKA activity accelerates sporulation in both dhkB- and acrA- mutants. The cytokinin receptor does not appear to be either DhkB or AcrA since culmination-stage mutants lacking these products bind radiolabelled cytokinin just as well as wild type cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18216168 Anjard and Loomis 2008)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0289073	Robert Dodson	The cell surface glycoprotein CsaA mediates cell-cell adhesion via homophilic binding. ''csaA'' encodes the glycoprotein gp80 that is responsible for Contact Sites A ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16453689 Noegel et al. 1986)]
column2: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16593709 Wong and Siu et al. 1986)]. It is expressed after 6 hours of development when the cells begin to aggregate. At this time
column3: the cells become mutually adhesive even in the presence of 10 mM EDTA. Antibodies specific to gp80 are able to block this EDTA resistant adhesion ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5106016 Beug et al. 1971)]
column4: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7328669 Murray et al. 1981)]
column5: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3934167 Siu et al. 1985)]. gp80 is stabilized by addition of N-acetylglucosamine to a threonine in a reaction catalyzed by ModB
column6: the product of ([/gene/DDB_G0291241 gnt2]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6717432 Murray et al. 1984)]
column8: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9092834 Jung et al. 1997)]. gp80 is also phosphorylated ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6178632 Schmidt and Loomis et al. 1982)]
column9: and held to the surface membrane by a covalently attached glycosylphosphatidyl-inositol lipid (GPI-anchor) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8081259 Klein et al. 1994)]
column10: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8294503 Barth et al. 1994)]. Homophilic interactions at the octapeptide YKLNVNDS found near the N-terminus of gp80 are responsible for end-to end adhesion of adjacent cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3320049 Siu et al. 1987)]
column11: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2582489 Kamboj et al. 1989)]. Disruption of csaA results in loss of EDTA-stable adhesion but does not noticeably affect aggregation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2515990 Harloff et al. 1989)]. Cells overexpressing csaA formed big slugs that gave rise to unusually large fruiting bodies ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1966011 Kamboj et al. 1990)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0292206	Robert Dodson	''manA'' encodes the lysosomal acid hydrolase alpha-mannosidase ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5464526 Loomis et al. 1970)]. The specific activity increases more than a thousand fold during development. Since alpha-mannosidase can be efficiently assayed along with other developmentally regulated acid hydrolases in wild type and mutant strains
column2: it has been used to establish an early dependent sequence of developmental events in Dictyostelium ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1033094 Loomis et al. 1976)]. The ''manA'' locus was the first genetic marker for chromosome 6 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1033886 Free et al. 1976)]. No phenotypic difference from wild type was observed in ''manA'' null cells. The mRNA is very low in cells growing on bacteria and rises to a peak at 8 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2038336 Schatzle et al. 1991)] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20236529 Parikh et al. 2010)]. Expression is dependent on a secreted quorum sensing signal
column3: indicating that this is one of the prestarvation response genes ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2038336 Schatzle et al. 1991)]. The response of ManA to PSF is not mediated by cAMP binding to CAR1 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8366107 Schatzle et al. 1993)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column3: which also appears to have no bcl-2 family members
column4: autophagic cell death and necrotic cell death are independent of caspases and bcl-2 proteins ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17889831 Lam et al.
column5:
2007]).
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23938384 Saheb et al.

DDB_G0292220	Robert Dodson	''ecmH'' encodes a 14 kDa protein that contains a cellulose-binding domain. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15309638 Shimada et al. 2004)]. There are 14 other proteins in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome that carry a cellulose-binding domain. Genes encoding 4 of the small cellulose-binding proteins are tightly clustered on chromosome 6 and another 4 are clustered on chromosome 1. mRNA from ''ecmH'' is not found in growing cells or during aggregation; however it accumulates more than 50 fold in prestalk cells between 16 and 22 hrs of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Expression of ecmH as well as the other family members on chromosome 6 ([/gene/DDB_G0291291 ecmF]
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0292222 ecmI]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0292218 st15]) is regulated by the transcription factor STATa ([/gene/DDB_G0281381 dstA]). ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15309638 Shimada et al. 2004)]. Since the slug sheath is made for several hours before ''ecmH'' is expressed
column5: it is unlikely that EcmH is an essential sheath component
column6: and more likely that it is involved in culmination.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0293524	Robert Dodson	''Dictyostelium'' [/gene/DDB_G0293524 ppk1] is highly similar to bacterial PPK
column2: which exhibits polyphosphate kinase activity inresponse to stress and starvation. PPK synthesizes long chains of polyphosphate (poly P)
column3: however
column4: the ''ppk1-''mutant retains a low level of polyphospate kinase activity. The remaining kinase activity (DdPKK2 activity) is attributed
column5: interestingly
column6: to three proteins identified using mass spectrometry: [/gene/DDB_G0288937 arpA]
column8:
and[/gene/DDB_G0289511 act28]. Inhibition of these three actin-related proteins with reagents affecting actinpolymerization (such as phalloidin) concomitantly inhibits poly P formation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15496465 Gmez-Garca and Kornberg 2004]).
Disruption of the ''ppk1'' gene results in low levels of poly P and a growth defect attributed to a phagocytosis defect. In addition
column9:
the ''ppk1'' mutant exhibits delayed culmination and a significantly reduced number of spore cells. In addition to its functions in development and phagocytosis ppk1 plays a role in the late stages of cytokinesis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15701689 Zhang et al. 2005]).
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26755590 Livermore et al. 2016] also generated a ''ppk1'' null mutant and confirmed that ''ppk1'' is the sole enzyme responsible for polyP synthesis in ''Dictyostelium''. Their investigations revealed that polyP regulates basic metabolism
column12: they discovered a massive increase in the level of polyP during developmental progression which is linked to the accumulation of inositol pyrophosphates. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0289075	Robert Dodson	''spiA'' encodes a 31 kDa protein that is added to the inner face of spore coats to keep spores viable ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2010032 Richardson et al. 1991)]
column3: 1992)]. Transcription starts very late in development as the cells are beginning to culminate (T=18 hrs). Expression is dependent on the MADS-box transcription factor SrfA ([/gene/DDB_G0281387 srfA]) and the GATA-binding transcription factor StkA ([/gene/DDB_G0277147 stkA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9729488 Escalante and Sastre
column5: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15075287 Escalante et al. 2004)]
column6: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2010032 Richardson et al. 1991)]. Transcription starts in the rising culminant at the interface of prestalk and prespore cells and then spreads down through the underlying prespore cells in the sorus ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7607079 Richardson et al. 1994)]. This spatial pattern of expression is the result of stimulation of PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column7: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) activity by diffusible signals generated by prestalk cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7937993 Mann et al. 1994)]

column1: DDB_G0276939	Robert Dodson	''pspB'' encodes the spore coat protein SP85 that binds cellulose in the middle of the trilaminar surface layer ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2731733 Smith et al. 1989)]
column3: 1994)]. The protein carries ''modB'' ([/gene/DDB_G0291241 gnt2])-dependent O-linked carbohydrate post-translational modifications that are recognized by the monoclonal antibody MUD50 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7693675 Watson et al. 1993)].There is a signal sequence at the N-terminus that directs transport across membranes. ''pspB'' mRNA is prespore-specific and starts to accumulate at 10 hrs. of development. The transcription factor GBF ([/gene/DDB_G0288755 gbfA]) binds to a CA-rich element upstream of ''pspB'' that is also found in the regulatory regions of several other genes encoding prespore specific proteins ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8050366 Powell-Coffman and Firtel
column4: 1994)]. Transcription of ''pspB'' is prespore-specific and coordinated with that of ''cotA''
column5: ([/gene/DDB_G0276941 cotA]) ''cotB''
column6: ([/gene/DDB_G0276761 cotB]) and ''cotC'' ([/gene/DDB_G0277141 cotC]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. ''pspB'' mRNA accumulates to much higher levels in cells lacking the cAMP receptor CAR2 ([/gene/DDB_G0288179 carB]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8436297 Saxe et al. 1993)]. SP85 is stored in prespore vesicles in a complex with 5 other proteins including SP96 ([/gene/DDB_G0276941 cotA]) and is released during sporulation such that it can associate with another cellulose binding protein
column8: ([/gene/DDB_G0277903 cotE]) to form the middle layer of the spore coat ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7844172 Watson et al. 1994)]
column10: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9692967 Zhang et al. 1998)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

It is transcribed during aggregation about 2 hours before the genes encoding the major spore coat proteins ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2550894 Early and Williams

column1: DDB_G0281561	Robert Dodson	Disruption of ''tipA'' by REMI mutagenesis resulted in cells that aggregated normally but were blocked at the mound ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9169048 Stege et al. 1997)]. The gene encodes a prestalk enriched protein that has a conserved PP 2C domain also found in protein phosphatases but is otherwise unrelated to previously characterized proteins. Prestalk cells differentiate in tipA- aggregates but fail to sort out to form an apical tip. They remain as small clumps scattered throughout the mounds. TipA appears to be responsible for cell autonomous sorting of the initial cell types.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0276333	Robert Dodson	''tipB'' encodes a 41 kDa protein that functions together with TipA ([/gene/DDB_G0281561 tipA]) at the mound stage in the sorting of prestalk cells to the tip ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10402673 Stege et al. 1999)]. Its amino acid sequence does not show significant similarity to that of other known proteins. Mutant strains lacking TipA or TipB
column3: form mounds with multiple tips that fail to transform into slugs. The phenotype of ''tipB'' null cells is significantly improved by overexpression of wild type ''tipA'' indicating that these two genes may have overlapping functions.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0289875	Robert Dodson	The increased rate of polysaccharide synthesis during culmination is dependent on uridine diphosphate glucose pyrophosphorylase (UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase) activity to generate the needed substrate
column2: UDP-glucose. Biochemical assays found a 10 fold increase in pyrophosphorylase activity between 10 and 20 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6067273 Ashworth and Sussman
column3: 1967)]. Mutant strains lacking this enzyme activity develop well until culmination but then arrest as gnarled fingers ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/944665 Dimond et al. 1976)]. Characterization of cDNA and genomic clones of ''uppA'' showed that it encodes UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2991046 Fishel et al. 1985)]
column4: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3035502 Ragheb et al. 1987)]. However
column5: most of the UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase activity during development is produced by the related gene ''ugpB'' ([/gene/DDB_G0277879 ugpB]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12060658 Bishop et al. 2002)]. mRNAs from ''uppA'' and ''ugpB'' accumulate coordinately between 6 and 18 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column6: 24-MAY-2016 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

column1: DDB_G0277879	Robert Dodson	''ugpB'' is responsible for most of the uridine diphosphate glucose pyrophosphorylase activity (UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase) during development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12060658 Bishop et al. 2002)]. Biochemical assays found a 10 fold increase in UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase activity between 10 and 20 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6067273 Ashworth and Sussman
column2: 1967)]. Mutant strains lacking this enzyme activity develop well until culmination but then arrest as gnarled fingers with reduced levels of polysaccharides ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/944665 Dimond et al. 1976)]. Disruption of ''ugpB'' results in reduced levels of glycogen and development ending with small
column3: gnarled fruiting bodies ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12060658 Bishop et al. 2002)]. There is a second gene encoding UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase
column4: ''uppA'' ([/gene/DDB_G0289875 uppA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3035502 Ragheb et al.1987)]. Disruption of ''uppA'' results in cells that develop normally and have only slightly reduced UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase activity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12060658 Bishop et al. 2002)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0281563 Robert Dodson Members of the Myb family of transcription factors are typically composed of two or three imperfect repeats each of about 50 amino acids. These repeats fold into a variant of the helix-turn-helix motif have DNA binding activity. The Myb motif has been well conserved during evolution (see [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10331990 Guo et al. 1999] and references therein).
''mybC'' was isolated as a REMI mutant that is unable to culminate. This defect is non-cell autonomous and can be rescued by overexpression of [/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]. However even when their defect is bypassed
column2: ''mybC'' null slugs and culminants produce little if any of the intercellular signalling peptides SDF-1 and SDF-2 that are believed to be released by prestalk cells at culmination. In ''mybC'' null cells
column3: several culmination genes are expressed at reduced levels: [/gene/DDB_G0269132 ecmB]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0289075 spiA]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0276941 cotA]
column6: and [/gene/DDB_G0276761 cotB]. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10331990 Guo et al. 1999]). ''mybC'' is downregulated in a STATa ([/gene/DDB_G0281381 dstA]) null mutant. In addition
column8: as well as additional prestalk genes
column9: such as ([/gene/DDB_G0291291 ecmF]) are downregulated in ''mybC'' null mutants
column10:
suggesting that ''mybC'' may work in conjunction with STATa to regulate the expression of prestalk-specific genes. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27125566 (Saga et al. 2016)]).
MybC was found in the nucleus of prestalk cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10331990 Guo et al. 1999]) using a beta-galactosidase gene driven by 1.85 kb of upstream sequence and the first 16 amino acids of mybC. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11553701 Iranfar et al. (2001)] found this gene overexpressed in prespore cells by Northern blot. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0277175	Robert Dodson	Formin G localizes to endocytic cups. Inactivation of the ''forG'' gene results in severely impaired macropinocytosis and phagocytosis
column2: and a reduced F-actin content at the base of phagocytic cups. ForG has weak actin filament nucleation activity
column3: but acts as an actin filament elongator that contributes to the generation of a functional F-actin network during endocytosis. In addition
column4: ''forG'' is directly regulated by the Ras GTPases [/gene/DDB_G0292998 rasB] and [/gene/DDB_G0293434 rasG] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27821733  (Junemann et al. 2016)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0282923	Robert Dodson	Genetic complementation studies were used to assign a series of rapid developing mutants of Dictyostelium to one or another of 3 rde loci. Those carrying mutations in ''rdeA'' were found to have high levels of cAMP ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6298035 Abe et al. 1983)]. Sequence comparisons and phenotypic characterizations showed that RdeA is a component of phosphorelay pathways controlling internal cAMP phosphodiesterase activity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9582274 Chang et al. 1998)]. A histidine moeity in the 28 kDa RdeA protein accepts a phosphate from an aspartate in histidine kinases
column2: and relays it to an aspartate in the response regulator region of the cAMP phosophodiesterase RegA ([/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10488068 Thomason et al. 1999)]. RdeA also facilitates dephosphorylation of RegA when DhkA ([/gene/DDB_G0280961 dhkA]) is converted to a phosphatase after it has bound SDF-2 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10373524 Wang et al. 1999)]. The signaling molecule differentiation-inducing factor 2 (DIF-2) modulates chemotaxis to cAMP via the DhkC ([/gene/DDB_G0274191 dhkC])-RegA-RdeA signaling pathway. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26919666 Kuwayama and Kubohara 2016)]Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0273065	Robert Dodson	Papers from the early '80's suggested that there are two genes

column1: DDB_G0291342	Robert Dodson	TacA is a homolog of the budding yeast ''S. cerevisiae'' zinc finger transcription factor
column2: Crz1. TacA is translocated from the cytosol to the nucleus after dephosphorylation by the calcium-activated protein phosphatase calcineurin ([/gene/DDB_G0276883 canA]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22944283  (Thewes et al. 2012)]. TacA translocates to the nucleus of ''D. discoideum'' within 3 minutes after addition of 100 mM CaCl2. The effect of calcium on TacA can be blocked by inhibition of calcineurin with 50 mM gossypol. Cells with reduced TacA as the result of expression of tacA-RNAi are delayed in aggregation and form very small fruiting bodies. Expression of prestalk genes ([/gene/DDB_G0277853 ecmA]) and ([/gene/DDB_G0269132 ecmB])
column3: prespore gene ([/gene/DDB_G0267412 pspA])
column4: and calcium up-regulated genes ([/gene/DDB_G0289283 cupC]) and ([/gene/DDB_G0277861 patA]) showed no clear effect of reduction of TacA in the mutant strain [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22944283  (Thewes et al. 2012)]. It is likely that the major roles of TacA occur during early development.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0279409	Robert Dodson	CbfA is a nuclear DNA binding protein that represses genes during growth including ([/gene/DDB_G0271870 agnC]) and induces genes during developement including ([/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8898890  (Geier et al. 1996)]
column3: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23355006  (Schmith et al. 2013)]. ''agnC'' encodes an Argonaute type protein that is a subunit of the RNA-induced silencing complex RISC. Cells transformed with a construct in which ''agnC'' is driven by act15 have high levels of Argonaute C that block accumulation of RNA from members of the TRE5-A family of repetitive elements [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26339297  (Schmith et al. 2015)]. Likewise
column4: cells with only 5% of wild type CbfA activity as the result of a partially suppressed mutation in cbfA do not efficiently transpose TRE5-A because the high levels of Argonaute C reduce RNA of the repetitive element. These cells fail to develop as the result of lack of induction of ''acaA''
column5: the gene encoding the adenylyl cyclase activity necessary for the generation of the chemoattractant cAMP [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15470262  (Winckler et al. 2004)]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16607013  (Siol et al. 2006)]. This developmental block can be bypassed by pulses of cAMP that advance the mutant cells to the aggregation stage where they can sustain expression of ''acaA'' and other genes necesssary for cAMP relay by positive feedback. CbfA (C-Binding Factor) was discovered among proteins that bind to the C-module at the 3' end of TRE5-A which controls synthesis of minus-strand (antisense) RNA [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8898890  (Geier et al. 1996)]. The C-terminal domain of CbfA binds to high dA/dT stretches in the C-module ''in vitro'' but does not regulate C-module promoter activity ''in vivo'' [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10491202  (Horn et al. 1999)]
column8: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21076008  (Bilzer et al. 2010)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0271684	Robert Dodson	''grlA'' encodes a member of the evolutionarily conserved family of seven transmembrane receptors that are coupled to G-proteins ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16735079 Prabu and Eichinger 2006)]. GrlA is similar to metazoan gamma aminobutyric acid (GABA) B-type receptors with 7 transmembrane domains and a large extracellular domain. Inactivation of the ''grlA'' gene leads to a delay in development at the post aggregation stage and a reduced number of spores ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17950724 Prabu et al. 2007)]. When steroids such as hydrocortisone bind to GrlA during culmination
column2: GABA is rapidly released to trigger production of the 34 amino acid peptide signal
column3: spore differentiation factor 2 (SDF-2). GrlA uses the trimeric G-protein containing the Galpha4 subunit encoded by gpaD ([/gene/DDB_G0285425 gpaD]). Drugs that inhibit the steroid biosynthetic pathway block the production of SDF-2 and reduce spore viability ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19176583 Anjard et al. 2009)]. Likewise
column4: grlA null and gpaD null mutants fail to release SDF-2 in response to hydrocortisone but respond normally to GABA.Gene has been comprehensively annotated
column5: 05-FEB-2017 RD; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

column1: DDB_G0289389	Robert Dodson	The ''dtfA'' gene was identified by screening a bank of REMI mutants for clones that could not form tipped mounds during development. The ''dftA'' protein DFTA lacks extensive sequence homology to other proteins
column2: but contains four short motifs which show partial homology to repeats found in mammalian mucins. DFTA was found to localize to the cell surface. dftA null cells have a complex phenotype
column3: including defects in development
column4: cytokinesis
column5: prestalk cell sorting
column6: and cell-cell adhesion. These results suggest that ''dtfA'' may form part of a cell-cell adhesion system that is needed both for optimal aggregation and efficient cell sorting during development. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9693138  (Ginger et al. 1998)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column13: and TTRAY2. This ancient adaptor complex (AP) was identified in organisms such as Dictyostelids and land plants

DDB_G0277143	Robert Dodson	Signal transduction from surface receptors is often mediated by heterotrimeric G proteins that dissociate into alpha and beta/gamma subunits when GTP replaces bound GDP on the Galpha subunit. ''gpbA'' encodes the evolutionarily conserved beta subunit which dimerizes with the gamma subunit in the presence of the phosducin-like protein PhLP1 ([/gene/DDB_G0292850 phlp1]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3151181  (Pupillo et al. 1988)]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16135826  (Knol et al. 2005)]. Mutant cells lacking Gbeta grow well axenically but are defective in phagocytosis of bacteria [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8099335  (Lilly et al. 1993)]
column3: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9647646  (Peracino et al. 1998)]. ''gpbA'' mutant cells have reduced levels of the cAMP receptor CAR1 ([/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0273533 carA-2]) and so do not respond to the chemoattractant cAMP. Consequently

column3: ([/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]). A feedback loop in which PKA activity inhibits ERK2 inhibition of RegA leads to an increase in cAMP phosphodiesterase activity that reduces the concentration of cAMP. As a result of this circuit and the activation of adenylyl cyclase when cAMP binds to CAR1

column1: DDB_G0293526	Robert Dodson	''racC'' encodes a guanine nucleotide-binding protein (G protein) of the Rho family of small GTPases. G proteins are key components of signal transduction networks in which they function as molecular signaling switches
column2: binding to GDP in the off state while binding GTP in the on state. Guanine nucleotide-exchange factors (GEFs) promote the exchange of GDP for GTP on Ras GTPases thus activating them
column3: while GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs) inactivate Ras GTPases by binding to them and promoting their intrinsic GTPase activity to hydrolyze bound GTP to GDP. GxcT ([/gene/DDB_G0269610 gxcT]) binds RacC and is a likely GEF for RacC ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24248334 Wang et al. 2013]). The armadillo-like protein Darlin ([/gene/DDB_G0288771 darA]) binds RacC
column4: but GEF activity has not been demonstrated ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9802899 Vithalani et al. 1998]). Additional possible GEFs for RacC include DockD ([/gene/DDB_G0284725 docD]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19037099 Para et al. 2009])
column5: ZizB ([/gene/DDB_G0293084 zizB])
column6: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22366457 Pakes et al. 2012])
column7: gxcDD ([/gene/DDB_G0279733 gxcDD]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17584488 Mondal et al. 2007]) and GxcC ([/gene/DDB_G0284845 gxcC]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23363311 Plak et al. 2013]). DRG ([/gene/DDB_G0291978 xacA]) contains both GAP and GEF domains
column8: and DRG displays weak GAP activity for RacC ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9188459 Ludbrook et al. 1997]). Other possible GAPs for RacC include GAPA ([/gene/DDB_G0269140 gapA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21085675 Mondal et al. 2010]) and DGAP1 ([/gene/DDB_G0287585 rgaA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22302991 Filic et al. 2012])
column9:
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26940518 Rivero et al. 2016]).
RacC has multiple binding partners that may function as downstream effectors. These include: the myosin heavy chain kinase PakB ([/gene/DDB_G0276459 pakB]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15509655 de la Roche et al. 2005])
column11: coronin A ([/gene/DDB_G0267382 corA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24347642 Swaminathan et al. 2013])
column12:
WASP ([/gene/DDB_G0293834 wasA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16968699 Han et al. 2006]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31786060 Amato et al. 2019)] and WASP-B ([/gene/DDB_G0272811 wasB]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23791739 (Chung et al. 2013)]. RacC also binds to the Rho GDP-dissociation inhibitor RhoGDI1 ([/gene/DDB_G0291077 rdiA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12163018 Imai et al. 2002]).
''racC'' plays an important role in signaling networks that regulate F-actin assembly during ''Dictyostelium'' chemotaxis and other processes that depend on the organization of the actin cytoskeleton. ''racC'' is expressed during growth
column13: but ''racC'' mRNA levels decrease significantly during aggregation before again increasing late during development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8294042 Bush et al. 1993]). ''racC'' overexpression results in aberrant F-actin organization with cells displaying unusual dorsal and peripheral F-actin rich surface blebs. Overexpression of ''racC'' also results in increased rates of phagocytosis
column14: but a decrease in macropinocytosis and exocytosis rates ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9763450 Seastone et al. 1998]). ''racC'' is activated at the leading edge of chemotaxing cells where it binds and activates WASP. ''racC'' null mutants have defects in both chemotaxis and cytokinesis
column15: and in addition display decreased levels of F-actin polymerization and reduced PI3K ([/gene/DDB_G0278727 pikA]
column16: [/gene/DDB_G0283081 pikB]) activation and translocation to the membrane in response to cAMP stimulation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16968699 Han et al. 2006]). RasC is aberrantly localized in ''wasB'' null cells
column17: and these mutants also have higher levels of activated RacC
column18: suggesting that WASP-B plays a role in the regulation of actin polymerization by modulating the activity and localization of RacC ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23791739 Chung et al. 2013]). ''racC'' null cells also have a streaming defect
column19: forming smaller and more fragmented streams. The adenylate cyclase ACA ([/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA])
column20: which is normally enriched in the uropod at the back of chemotactically migrating cells
column21: is mainly associated with intracellular vesicular structures in ''racC'' null cells
column22: revealing an important role for RacC in the regulation of ACA localization ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26315268 Wang et al. 2015]). The cell proliferation repressor AprA ([/gene/DDB_G0281663 aprA]) requires RacC to induce chemo-repulsion revealing that ''racC'' also plays a role in chemo-repulsion signal transduction pathways ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30462573 Rijal et al. 2018]). Activated Rac1A ([/gene/DDB_G0277869 rac1A]) and RacC both regulate
column24: WASP. WASP interacts with activated Rac genes via its CRIB motif
column25: and this interaction is required for WASP to generate pseudopods in the absence of SCAR/WAVE ([/gene/DDB_G0285253 scrA]). However
column26: this interaction also provides a means for WASP to remove activated Racs from the membrane via endocytosis. Thus
column27: WASP contributes to front-rear cell polarity by controlling localization and cellular levels of activated Rac. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31786060  (Amato et al. 2019)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0288375	Robert Dodson	The 47 kDa protein encoded by ''lis1'' is a close homolog of mammalian LIS1 which is associated with lissencephaly. ''lis1'' consists of an N-terminal LIS1-homology domain and seven WD40 repreats. Like LIS1
column2: it is found at the tips of microtubules where it asssociates with the XMAP215 family member DdCP224 ([/gene/DDB_G0268616 cepJ]) and dynein ([/gene/DDB_G0276355 dhcA]) to form cortical attachments. Partial loss of Lis1 function resulting from a hypomorphic point mutation leads to collapse of radial interphase microtubule arrays into bundles that whorl around the nucleus. Lis1 is also found directly assocated with the centrosome which it helps localize near the nucleus. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15800059  (Rehberg et al. 2005)]. LIS1 may also affect actin dynamics through interactions with Rac1A ([/gene/DDB_G0277869 rac1A]) and doublecortin ([/gene/DDB_G0277115 dcx]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21034843  (Meyer et al. 2010)]. LIS1 over-expression mutants have a defect in the formation of the phagocytic cup and a reduced migration velocity
column3: further suggesting that LIS1 is involved in the regulation of actin dynamics [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32524725  (Chhatre et al. 2020)]. About 100 different proteins contribute to centrosomal functions including the products of ([/gene/DDB_G0271738 tubC])
column4: ([/gene/DDB_G0285849 spc97])
column5: ([/gene/DDB_G0283909 spc98])
column6: ([/gene/DDB_G0288427 cenA])
column10: ([/gene/DDB_G0268616 cepJ]) and ([/gene/DDB_G0278809 cepG]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15548420  (Graf et al. 2004)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0272192	Petra Fey	The neuronal ceroid lipofuscinoses (NCLs)
column3: belong to a group of neurological disorders causing blindness
column4: seizures
column5: loss of motor function and cognitive ability
column6: and premature death. ''Dictyostelium'' Mfsd8 is a homolog of human MFSD8 (CLN7)
column7: identified as one of the mutated genes in the disease. Conserved key residues
column8: protein domains and a structural model greatly overlap between both
column9:
the human and and ''Dictyostelium'' protein. Mfsd8 proteins contain multiple transmembrane domains.
GFP-fusions show that Mfsd8 localizes to endsomal compartments and acidic vesicles
column10: including late endosomes. Mass spectrometry has been used to reveal the Mfsd8 interactive. Among the interacting proteins cathepsin D has been independently verified ([/gene/DDB_G0279411 ctsD]). Other interacting candidates are [/gene/DDB_G0285793 cadA] or [/gene/DDB_G0281605 cfaD]. The three proteins also interact with Cln5 ([/gene/DDB_G0275299 cln5]) suggesting a NCL protein network. The ''mfsd8'' null mutant is involved in protein secretion. During starvation
column11: intracellular levels of CtsD and Cln5 are reduced compared to wild-type. Because expression levels are not affected by the mutation
column12: conditioned starvation buffer has been tested for the proteins and elevated levels found. Thus Mfsd8 negatively regulates secretion of CtsD and Cln5 during starvation )[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32087303 Huber et al. 2020]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0283907	Robert Dodson	''pkaC'' encodes the catalytic subunit of the cAMP dependent protein kinase PKA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1332055 Mann et al. 1992 ]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8373760 Anjard et al. 1993)]. In the absence of cAMP
column3: PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) exists as an inactive complex of the catalytic and regulatory subunits. cAMP binds cooperatively to two sites on PkaR which leads to the release of active PkaC. This protein kinase plays multiple roles throughout development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1728597 Harwood et al. 1992]
column5: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9126295 Mann et al. 1997]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9729606 Loomis et al. 1998]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25872182 Loomis et al. 2015]). During normal development on a moist surface
column8: mRNA from ''pkaC'' increases smoothly from an initially low level to reach a peak at 20 hours ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420 Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. When cells are developed in suspension with addition of 50 nM cAMP every 6 minutes
column9: the level of ''pkaC'' mRNA stays low throughout development. Very few other genes are repressed by cAMP pulses. The regulatory subunit can reassociate with the catalytic subunit and inhibit it when the phosphodiesterase RegA ([/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA]) hydrolyses cAMP bound to PkaR ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9435289 Shaulsky et al. 1998]
column10: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20923972 Moorthy et al. 2011)]. As part of the circuit that generates 6 minute oscillations in cAMP during aggregation
column11: PKA activity blocks ERK2 ([/gene/DDB_G0283903 erkB]) inhibition of RegA as well as CRAC ([/gene/DDB_G0285161 dagA]) activation of ACA ([/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA]) resulting in rapid decrease in the internal concentration of cAMP and a drop in PKA activity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9020088 Aubry et al. 1997]
column13: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15131307 Maeda et al. 2004]). PKA plays a role in gradient sensing and chemotaxis to cAMP by regulating the Ras ([/gene/DDB_G0281385 rasC]
column15: Rap1 ([/gene/DDB_G0291237 rapA]) and TORC2 ([/gene/DDB_G0281569 tor]) signaling pathways in response to cAMP. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28302905 Scavello et al. 2017)]. PKA is also part of the signal transduction pathway by which Prestarvation Factor (PSF) stimulates expression of ''carA'' ([/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1]
column16: [/gene/DDB_G0273533 carA-2]) and ''acaA'' at the initiation of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9584128 Souza et al. 1998)]. PSF activates the protein kinase YakA ([/gene/DDB_G0283605 yakA]) such that it inhibits PufA ([/gene/DDB_G0279735 pufA]) which is the translational inhibitor of ''pkaC'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10375515 Souza et al. 1999)]. PkaC increases relative to PkaR resulting in constitutive protein kinase activity. PKA also controls gene expression during culmination by regulating the transcription factor SrfA ([/gene/DDB_G0281387 srfA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12204259 Escalante et al. 2002)]. The peptide signal that prepares prespore and prestalk cells for terminal differentiation
column18:
is phosphorylated by PKA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9373946 Anjard et al. 1997)].
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28057864 (Chen et al. 2017)] demonstrated a role for PKA in stalk cell differentiation. Their investigation into the c-di-GMP signal transduction pathway showed that the stalk-inducing signal cyclic diguanylate (c-di-cGMP) produced by diguanylate cyclase ([/gene/DDB_G0283453 dgcA]) activates cAMP synthesis by adenylate cyclase A (ACA) which is specifically expressed at the apical tip. cAMP then activates PKA which then triggers stalk differentiation. PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column19: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) also mediates the response of several xenobiotic compounds
column22: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16759735  (Boeckeler et al. 2006)] and curcumin [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29135990  (Swatson et al. 2017)]. Results presented in ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29440238 Williams et al. 2018)] argue that macropinocytosis is downregulated in early development because of PKA activation. PkaC is involved in the signal transduction pathway responsible for AprA-dependent ([/gene/DDB_G0281663 aprA]) chemorepulsion. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30462573 Rijal et al. 2018]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

Cells lacking Vmp1 have elevated and aberrant PtdIns3P signaling on the ER

column1: DDB_G0280849	Robert Dodson	''dicA'' encodes the highly conserved dynein intermediate chain that associates with dynein heavy chains ([/gene/DDB_G0276355 dhcA]) to make the motor complexes which function in retrograd transport of cargos along microtubules [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1469051  (Koonce et al. 1992)]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7866389  (Koonce et al. 1994)]. An N-terminal region of DicA binds the dynactin complex that allows dynein to move organelles long distances along microtubules. A C-terminal region of DicA binds dynein heavy chain. Expression of truncated versions of ''dicA'' missing either the N-terminal region or the C-terminal region results in mislocalization of the Golgi
column3: collapse of microtubules into large bundles
column4: and alterations in centrosome separation resulting in defective mitosis. It appears that dynactin-mediated dynein function is required for organization of interphase microtubule network as well as centrosome replication and separation. As expected
column5: dynein intermediate chain is essential for viability of ''Dictyostelium'' [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10601339  (Ma et al. 1999)]. Dynein motors cluster into microdomains on phagosomal membranes
column6: resulting in rapid directed transport of the phagosome toward microtubule minus ends
column7: likely promoting phagolysosome fusion and pathogen degradation. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26853472  (Rai et al. 2016)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0276355	Robert Dodson	''dhcA'' encodes the highly conserved dynein heavy chain that together with the dynein intermediate chain ([/gene/DDB_G0280849 dicA]) makes motor complexes that move cargo along microtubules [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1469051  (Koonce et al. 1992)]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7866389  (Koonce et al. 1994)]. The heavy chain has a stem at the N-terminal that binds cargo
column3: followed by the motor domain
column4: 4 ATP binding sites and a long stalk ending in a microtubule binding site [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22398446  (Kon et al. 2012)]. Dimers walk along microtubules towards the minus-ends by coupling large structural changes to ATP [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17548361  (Mogami et al. 2007)]
column5: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19203583  (Roberts et al. 2009)]. Endosomes are transported along microtubules with frequent reversals in direction due to a tug-of-war between dynein pulling to the minus-end and kinesin ([/gene/DDB_G0290963 kif1]) pulling to the plus-end [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19864630  (Soppina et al. 2009)]. Dynein heavy chains are essential for viability of ''Dictyostelium'' [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9453714  (Koonce and Knecht
column6: 1998)]. ''In vitro'' assays of mutant forms of dynein heavy chain showed that the first ATP-binding/hydrolysis site is essential for the motor activities. Mutations in the second and fourth binding sites reduced microtubule-activated ATPase activity but had no effect on binding affinity. Mutations in the third binding site resulted in 20-fold slower sliding velocity on microtubules [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15366936  (Kon et al. 2004)]. Overexpression of a truncated 380 kDa form lacking the amino terminal region involved in dimerization results in collapse of the interphase radial microtubule array [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8816999  (Koonce and Samso
column7: 1996)]. Dynein is also found associated with centrosomes [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15186508  (Hestermann et al. 2004)]. Dynein motors cluster into microdomains on phagosomal membranes
column8: resulting in rapid directed transport of the phagosome toward microtubule minus ends
column9: likely promoting phagolysosome fusion and pathogen degradation. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26853472  (Rai et al. 2016)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0285849	Robert Dodson	Spc97 and Spc98 ([/gene/DDB_G0283909 spc98])
column2: form a complex with gamma-tubulin ([/gene/DDB_G0271738 tubC]) that initiates microtubule polymerization in the spindle pole body of yeast. The ''Dictyostelium'' homologs are encoded by ''spc97'' and ''spc98''
column3: respectively. Throughout the cell cycle they are found in the centrosome which functions as the main microtubule-organizing center (MTOC) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12018385  (Daunderer and Graf
column4: 2002)]. Under high salt conditions Spc98 co-immunoprecipitates with gamma-tubulin but Spc97 fails to co-immunoprecipitate. In other organisms all 3 proteins are strongly held in a complex. In contrast to mammalian cells
column5: there is no dramatic increase in microtubule nucleation during mitosis of ''Dictyostelium''. At prometaphase the gamma-tubulin/Spc98 complex rapidly redistributes from the centrosomal corona to the inner surfaces of the two outer layers of the centrosome allowing the microtubule spindle to drive the two spindle poles apart [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9880333  (Ueda et al. 1999)]

column1: DDB_G0287773	Robert Dodson	The glycine cleavage system complex consists of four proteins that function to catalyze the net reaction glycine + THFA <=> NH<sub>3</sub> + CO<sub>2</sub> + 5

column8: [/gene/DDB_G0287795 gcvH4] and [/gene/DDB_G0287861 gcvH5]) whereas other species contain only one H-protein. The final component of the glycine cleavage system is ([/gene/DDB_G0291648 lpd]) a dihydrolipoyl dehydrogenase that is a member of several other dehydrogenase complexes
column9:
including the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1993704 Kume et al. 1991]).
A genetic screen of an insertional mutant library identified ''gcvH1'' as having reduced sensitivity to cannabidiol (CBD). The protein GCVH1 localizes to the mitochondrion. A ''gcvH1'' null mutant showed elevated glycine levels and increased tetrahydrofolate levels
column10: supporting a role for ''gcvH1'' in the glycine cleavage system. Treatment of wild-type cells with CBD significantly lowered methionine levels
column11: but this effect was lost in ''gcvH1'' null cells
column12: suggesting a mechanism of CBD action through inhibition of methionine production and regulation of one carbon metabolism. A form of cannabidiol (CBD) has demonstrated seizure control activity in patients with Dravet syndrome. Induction of seizure-like activity also elevates rat neuronal methionine levels
column13: and acute CBD treatment attenuates this effect. Thus these combined results from ''Dictyostelium'' and mammalian cells suggest a novel mechanism for CBD in regulating methionine levels
column14: and identify altered one-carbon metabolism in Dravet syndrome and seizure activity. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31693171 Perry et al. 2019]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

DDB_G0284331	Robert Dodson	The major intracellular cAMP phosphodiesterase is encoded by ''regA'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8986798 Shaulsky et al. 1996)]. RegA associates with PkaR ([/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) and catalyzes the hydrolysis of bound cAMP ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9435289 Shaulsky et al. 1998)]. The catalytic subunit of PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]) then displaces RegA and reforms the inactive PKA complex ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20923972 Moorthy et al. 2011)]. RegA carries a response regulator domain at the N-terminus that accepts phosphate from the H2 relay protein RdeA ([/gene/DDB_G0282923 rdeA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9582274 Chang et al. 1998]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10488068  Thomason et al. 1999)]. Phosphorylation of the response regulator domain of RegA allosterically activates the catalytic domain found near the carboxy-terminus ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22326871 Moorthy et al. 2012)]. Multiple histidine kinases relay phosphate to RdeA and can thereby modulate cAMP levels by controlling the phosphodiesterase activity. DhkA ([/gene/DDB_G0280961 dhkA]) is a receptor histidine kinase that acts in a two-component system with RegA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8670894 Wang et al. 1996]
column3: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10373524 Wang et al. 1999)]. When DhkA binds its peptide ligand
column4: SDF-2
column5: it acts as a phosphatase to remove phosphate from RdeA which can then dephosphorylate RegA and reduce its activity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9191038 Loomis et al. 1997]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9582277 Thomason et al. 1998)]. RegA is part of the circuit that generates 6 minute oscillations in cAMP during aggregation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9843585 Laub et al. 1998]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15131307 Maeda et al. 2004)]. When external cAMP binds to the CAR1 ([/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1])
column9: ERK2 ([/gene/DDB_G0283903 erkB]) is activated and then associates with and inhibits RegA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31730032 Adhikari et al. 2019)]. cAMP can then rapidly build up until it activates the cAMP dependent protein kinase PKA which blocks ERK2 inhibition of RegA; the resulting RegA activity drives the concentration of cAMP back down. Cells in which ''regA'' is disrupted develop precociously much like cells in which ''pkaR'' is disrupted ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9435289 Shaulsky et al. 1998)]. These mutant cells are also impaired in chemotaxis as the result of being unable to suppress lateral pseudopods in the front of natural cAMP waves ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10930471 Wessels et al. 2000)]. The signaling molecule differentiation-inducing factor 2 (DIF-2) modulates chemotaxis to cAMP via the DhkC ([/gene/DDB_G0274191 dhkC])-RegA-RdeA signaling pathway. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26919666 Kuwayama and Kubohara 2016)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1:
DDB_G0273805 Robert Dodson ''ndkC'' encodes the cytosolic form of nucleoside diphosphate (NDP) kinase (EC 2.7.4.6). The related [/gene/DDB_G0279911 ndkM] gene encodes a mitochondrial NDP kinase ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8244981 Troll et al. 1993]). This enzyme is responsible for the phosphorylation of nucleoside or deoxynucleoside diphosphates into the corresponding triphosphates at the expense of ATP ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8931563 Deville-Bonne et al. 1996]). NDP kinase is transiently phosphorylated on an active site histidine as part of the catalytic process (see [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9786875 Schneider et al. 1998 and references therein]).
This enzyme plays a crucial role in equilibrating the cellular nucleotide pools (see [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9786875 Schneider et al. 1998 and references therein]). Besides this role in intermediate nucleotide metabolism
column2: NDP kinase has been implicated in a large number of cellular functions. Part of the cellular NDP kinase is associated with the plasma membrane and stimulated by cell surface cAMP receptors. The GTP produced by the action of NDP kinase is capable of activating G-proteins as monitored by altered G-protein-receptor interaction and the activation of the effector enzyme phospholipase C ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8389692 Bominaar et al. 1993]). Nucleoside diphosphate kinase is also associated with the cytoskeleton where it channels ATP to the myosin molecule ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8816286 Aguado-Velasco et al. 1996]). Yet another role for NDP kinase is to feed GTP into the translation machinery
column3: as inferred by its association with active ribosomes ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7733916 Sonnemann and Mutzel 1995]). Knock down of NDP kinase expression suppressed the phenotypic defects that are caused by AMPK ([/gene/DDB_G0277905 snfA])
column4: hyperactivity resulting either from overexpression of AMP alpha T or from mitochondrial dysfunction. These included rescue of defects in slug phototaxis
column5:
fruiting body morphology and growth in a liquid medium. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21374069 Annesley et al. 2011]).
The X-ray structure of nucleoside diphosphate kinase (NDP kinase) from ''Dictyostelium discoideum'' has been determined ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1846924 Dumas et al. 1991]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7966307 Morera et al. 1994]). The protein is a hexamer with D3 symmetry. The X-ray structure of wild type and several mutants nucleoside diphosphate kinase bound to substrates
column7: co-factors and inhibitors has also been determined (see [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12171931 Gallois-Montbrun et al. 2002]
column9:
and references therein).
Nucleoside analogs are currently used in antiretrovirus therapies. The best known example is AZT
column10: one of the first drugs to be used for the treatment of AIDS. However
column11: only the triphosphate derivatives of these compounds act as substrates of the viral reverse transcriptase. Since these compounds cannot enter cells
column12: nucleoside analogs are administered and phosphorylated by cellular kinases
column13: including nucleoside diphosphate (NDP) kinase. Studies of the enzymatic mechanism of this enzyme provide essential information for the design of new nucleoside analogs with increased efficiency in antiretroviral therapies ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11768316 Schneider et al. 2000]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14641909  (Kollmar and Glockner 2003)]. There is a SAM domain at the N-terminus that can associate with SAM domains in other proteins. The motor domain is central in Kif6. Reduction of ''kif6'' expression by regulated RNAi indicated that this kinesin plays a vital role in ''Dictyostelium''. As the level of Kif6 went down
column3: many of the spindle assemblies became abnormal and the chromosomes were seen to lag during anaphase [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19286984  (Tikhonenko et al. 2009)]. Based on the sequences of the motor domains six of the 13 kinesins ([/gene/DDB_G0267396 kif2]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0285101 kif4]
column6: [/gene/DDB_G0291039 kif11]
column8: and [/gene/DDB_G0288361 kif13]) are members of mitotic motor families. Like each of the other mitotic kinesins
column9: ''kif6'' mRNA levels are low in growing cells and increase to relatively high levels between 12 and 18 hrs of development before returning to very low levels [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9693369  (de Hostos et al. 1998)]
column10: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0279151	Robert Dodson	''cenB'' encodes a centrin which is 51% identical to CenA but is not localized to the centrosome. CenB is found throughout the nucleus in interphase cells but disappears as the cells enter mitosis even though the nuclear envelop does not fully breakdown during mitosis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20539780  (Mana-Capelli et al. 2010)]. Cells lacking CenB have enlarged nuclei with protrusions of the envelop and abnormal centrosome-nucleus anchoring. There are also supernumerary centrosomes and defects in the organization of the microtubule-organizing center (MTOC) in the mutant cells. CenB appears to be required to maintain nuclear architecture during interphase and to be part of the machinery that regulates centrosome duplication. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19465563  (Mana-Capelli et al. 2009)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated
