DDB_G0272110	Robert Dodson	The ''gskA'' gene encodes the ''Dictyostelium'' homologue of glycogen synthase kinase 3 (GSK3)
column2: a highly conserved serine/threonine kinase. It is required for the cAMP induced formation of prespore cells and inhibition of stalk cells. Disruption of ''gskA'' creates a mutant that aggregates but forms few spores and an abnormally high number of stalk cells [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7813009  (Harwood et al. 1995)]. Extracellular cAMP activates GskA through the cAMP receptor cAR3 ([/gene/DDB_G0277829 carC]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9847246  (Plyte et al. 1999)] and the tyrosine kinase ZAK1 ([/gene/DDB_G0276025 zakA]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10571182  (Kim et al. 1999)]
column3: stimulating prespore differentiation. A second receptor
column4: cAR4 ([/gene/DDB_G0277831 carD])
column5: appears to negatively regulate GskA [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9284050  (Ginsburg and Kimmel
column7:
to promote prestalk formation. GskA itself was shown to phosphorylate STATa ([/gene/DDB_G0281381 dstA]) and enhance its nuclear export [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11032815 (Ginger et al. 2000)]. There is also evidence that GskA phosphorylation activates the beta-catenin homologue aardvark ([/gene/DDB_G0288877 aarA]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11130075 (Crimson et al. 2000)].
It has been proposed that cAMP receptor-mediated pathways converge at GskA suggesting that the anterior (prestalk) / posterior (prespore) axis of ''Dictyostelium'' is regulated by an ancient mechanism that is shared by the Wnt/Fz circuits for dorsoventral patterning during early ''Xenopus'' development
column8: and establishing ''Drosophila'' segment polarity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9284050  (Ginsburg and Kimmel
column9: 1997)]. In ''Dictyostelium'' it has been suggested that a single ligand
column11: activating receptors cAR3 and cAR4 with distinct affinities
column15:
2000)].
While the original ''gskA''-null mutant was created in the uracil auxotroph DH1 strain
column16: Schilde ''et al.'' deleted the gene in AX2. This had the advantage of creating a mutant with a milder phenotype
column17: where a significant number of cells progress through development with relatively normal spore/stalk cell proportions. In this AX2/''gskA''-null strain
column18: early development is accelerated but slug migration is impaired. Consistent with the accelerated early development
column21: and [/gene/DDB_G0267412 pspA] are precociously expressed. ''ecmB'' expression in wildtype is restricted to the slug tip
column22: just as they commit themselves to stalk cell differentiation. In the AX2/''gskA''-null mutant
column24: ''ecmB'' is expressed throughout the prestalk region of the slug
column25: suggesting that ''gskA'' is involved in a repressive signalling pathway preventing premature stalk cell commitment. Microarray analysis identified the large gene C2 family ([/gene/DDB_G0280847 2C]) that requires ''gskA'' for optimal expression
column26:
suggesting that ''gskA'' may also play an activator role [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15342480 (Schilde et al. 2004)].
''gskA'' null mutants have aberrant aggregation and defective chemotaxis toward both cAMP and folate. In addition
column27: ''gskA'' was shown to be required for both phosphatidylinositol 3
column29: 5-trisphosphate (PIP3) and target of rapamycin complex 2 (TORC2)-mediated signalling. Furthermore
column30: ''gskA'' null mutant cells do not generate cAMP pulses during aggregation
column31: demonstrating that GskA plays a major role in the regulation of chemotaxis and early ''Dictyostelium'' development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20534815  (Teo et al. 2010)]. Using phosphoproteomics ([/gene/DDB_G0274383 pdeD])
column32: ([/gene/DDB_G0283767 dct]) and ([/gene/DDB_G0293044 sogA]) were identified as substrates which are phosphorylated by GskA. Knockout mutants of all 3 genes are defective in chemotaxis. The carboxylesterase D2 ([/gene/DDB_G0276969 D2B]) is a downstream effector of GskA [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29626371  (Baumgardner et al. 2018)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0289967	Robert Dodson	Sirtuins are evolutionarily conserved NAD-dependent protein deacetylases which play important roles in various biological processes. This activity was later attributed to the [/gene/DDB_G0275699 gnt1] gene ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12244115 van der Wel et al. 2002]). GNT1 specifically adds GlcNAc (N-acetylglucosamine) to Skp1 ([/gene/DDB_G0269230 fpaA]/[/gene/DDB_G0273251 fpaB-1])
Glycosylation of Skp1 has been extensively studied in ''Dictyostelium''. The initial step in Skp1 glycosylation involves the hydroxylation of Pro143 by a proline hydroxylase ([/gene/DDB_G0277759 phyA]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9660787 Teng-umnuay et al. 1998]). HyPro143 is then modified by the glycosyltransferase [/gene/DDB_G0275699 gnt1]
column3: which transfers a GlcNAc (N-acetylglucosamine) to the Skp1 protein ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10593934 Teng-umnuay et al. 1999]). The Skp1-GlcNAc is extended by a bifunctional diglycosyltransferase
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0283761 pgtA]
column5: which processively adds galactose and fucose ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11423539 van der Wel et al. 2001]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12244067 van der Wel et al. 2002]). Subsequently two additional galactose residues are added by [/gene/DDB_G0283005 agtA] to yield the Skp1 pentasaccharide (GGFGGnOSkp1; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16495217 Ercan et al. 2006]
column7:
reviewed in [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31128470 West and Kim 2019]).

column1: DDB_G0267422	Robert Dodson	''tipC'' was isolated from a REMI mutant that was picked because its development was arrested when multiple tips formed on aggregates ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10402673 Stege et al. 1999)]. It encodes a large protein with a C-terminal domain similar to the one in yeast and human vacuolar sorting protein VPS13. This protein is involved in the transport of proteins to the vacuole in yeast. The human protein VPS13A is mutated in the neurodegenerative disease chorea-acanthocytosis. column1: DDB_G0267650	Robert Dodson	During endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress
column2: unfolded proteins accumulate in the ER lumen. A highly regulated pathway known as the unfolded protein response (UPR) has evolved to restore ER homeostasis. The putative serine/threonine protein kinase ''ireA'' is orthologous to the highly conserved IRE1 gene which is involved in the regulation of the UPR. IreA was found to localize to the ER
column3: and ''ireA'' null cells fail to cope with ER stress
column4: displaying lysed cells with poor growth and collapsed ER cisternae. In addition
column5: IreA participates in an ER stress-induced transcriptional response which modulates the levels of a diverse set of transcripts. In control cells
column6: ER stress triggers autophagy and autophagy is also induced in ''ireA'' null cells
column7: demonstrating that ''ireA'' is not required for autophagy induction. However in ''ireA'' cells
column9: abnormal and trapped at the ER
column10: suggesting that they are unable to degrade autophagic cargoes and that IreA-mediated recovery of ER homeostasis is required to achieve a fully functional autophagy-dependent degradation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29632077 Ongay-Larios et al. 2018])
column11: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29890774 Dominguez-Martin et al. 2018]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column4: [/gene/DDB_G0286187 proB]) suppressed the profilin null endocytic defects and phagocytic increases

DDB_G0292998	Robert Dodson	''rasB'' encodes a guanine nucleotide-binding protein (G protein) of the Ras family of small GTPases. G proteins are key components of signal transduction networks in which they function as molecular signaling switches
column2: binding to GDP in the off state while binding GTP in the on state. Guanine nucleotide-exchange factors (GEFs
column3: rasGEFs) promote the exchange of GDP for GTP on Ras GTPases thus activating them
column4: while GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs
column5:
rasGAPs) inactivate Ras GTPases. RasB is activated by the RasGEF Q ([/gene/DDB_G0289665 gefQ]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18504297 Mondal et al. 2008)] and inactivated by the RasGAP DdNF1 ([/gene/DDB_G0271750 nfaA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18948008 Zhang et al. 2008)].
''rasB'' is expressed at maximum levels during vegetative growth and the first 8 hr of development
column6: and is activated upon cAMP stimulation by rasGEF Q. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8455930 Daniel et al. 1993)]
column7: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18504297 Mondal et al. 2008)]. RasB is predominantly localized in the nucleus during most of the cell cycle but assumes a diffuse cellular localization during mitosis and cytokinesis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11606416 Sutherland et al. 2001)]. Constitutively active RasB mutants have an increased proportion of multi-nucleated cells
column8: revealing a defect in cytokinesis. ''rasB'' null cells are unstable and exhibit growth defects
column9: defects in both phagocytosis and macropinocytosis
column10: and decreased F-actin levels in the phagocytic cup ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11606416 Sutherland et al. 2001)]
column12:
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30967009 Williams et al. 2019)].
Ras signaling through RasB is a critical mediator of several processes in ''Dictyostelium'': the regulation of myosin II assembly
column14: and actin assembly during phagocytosis. Both rasGEF Q and constitutively active RasB directly interact with the myosin heavy chain kinase MHCK-A ([/gene/DDB_G0291231 mhkA]) to regulate myosin II assembly ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18504297 Mondal et al. 2008)]. RasB and RasG ([/gene/DDB_G0293434 rasG]) regulate cytokinesis through the protein kinase NdrC ([/gene/DDB_G0284839 ndrC]). ''ndrC'' null cells also display a cytokinesis defect and pull-down assays show that NdrC binds both activated RasG and RasB. The aberrant cytokinesis phenotype of activated RasB suggests that RasB is a negative regulator of cytokinesis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24986648 Mueller-Taubenberger et al. 2014)]. Null mutants of rasGAP NfaA are also reported to display cytokinesis defects. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18948008 Zhang et al. 2008)]. Similar to the ''rasB'' null mutant phenotype
column15: ablation of the actin filament elongator formin G ([/gene/DDB_G0277175 forG]) results in significantly decreased phagocytosis and aberrant F-actin organization within phagosomes. Constitutively active RasB and RasG accumulate in endocytic cups where they directly interact with and regulate formin G
column16: thus linking Ras GTPase signaling with actin polymerization in phagocytosis and macropinocytosis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27821733 Junemann et al. 2016)]. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column13:

column9: C2GAP1 ([/gene/DDB_G0278483 ngap]) and IqgC ([/gene/DDB_G0288977 iqgC]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18948008 Zhang et al. 2008)]
column11: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30622175 Marinovic et al. 2019)]. ''rasG'' is expressed only during growth and early development
column12: although a quantity of the RasG protein is present throughout development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2644652 Robbins et al. 1989])
column14: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10837033 Wilkins et al. 2000]). ''rasG'' is activated by cAMP
column15:
and this activation does not occur in a number of cAMP signaling mutants. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15143344 Kae et al. 2004)].
RasG
column16: either alone or in combination with other Ras proteins
column17: is involved in mediating chemotaxis to cAMP
column20: and macropinocytosis. ''rasG'' null cells are multinucleate and display a wide range of defects in control of the actin cytoskeleton

column25: decreased cell polarity and decreased F-actin polymerization ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15534002 Sasaki et al. 2004)]. ''rasG'' null cells also have a defect in fluid uptake ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27960076 Veltman et al. 2016)]
column26:
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30967009 Williams et al. 2019)]. Cells overexpressing an activated form of RasG fail to aggregate ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8754814 Khosla et al. 1996]).

DDB_G0290963	Robert Dodson	''kif1'' encodes a large
column2: 248 kDa kinesin that functions as the major molecular motor for transport of organelles to the plus-ends of microtubules [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10545495  (Pollock et al. 1999)]. Kif1 has an N-terminal motor domain highly similar to human kinesin KIF1B and ''Caenorhabditis elegans'' ''unc104'' motor domain that is followed by a Forkhead-associated domain that can bind phosphoproteins
column3: and a Pleckstrin homology domain that can bind membrane-associated phosphatidylinositol (4
column4: 5) bisphosphate (PIP2). In ''Dictyostelium''
column5: Kif1 functions as a dimer and appears to cluster in PIP2 containing rafts [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12015984  (Klopfenstein et al. 2002)]. Kinesins move along microtubules by a "hand-over-hand" mechanism in which they tilt over to allow the motor domains to step past one another using the energy of ATP hydrolysis. Endosomes are transported along microtubules with frequent reversals in direction due to a tug-of-war between kinesin (kif1) pulling to the plus-end and dynein ([/gene/DDB_G0276355 dhcA]) pulling to the minus-end [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19864630  (Soppina et al. 2009)]. A knockout of ''kif1'' results in a 60% decrease in organelle transport
column6: but the cells can still grow [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10545495  (Pollock et al. 1999)]. ''kif1'' is transcribed throughout development. Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0274597	Petra Fey	Developing ''Dictyostelium'' cells aggregate to form fruiting bodies. The group size of aggregates is largely regulated by a secreted complex of 4 polypeptides called counting factor (CF). CF is composed of countin (encoded by the [/gene/DDB_G0274597 ctnA] gene)
column3: [/gene/DDB_G0269248 cf45-1] and [/gene/DDB_G0284363 cf60]. In transformants with a disrupted ''ctnA'' gene
column4: aggregation streams do not break up
column5: resulting in large fruiting bodies ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10444594 Brock and Gomer 1999]). The presence of caffeine rescued the ''ctnA'' null increased aggregate size phenotype and induced formation of smaller aggregates ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22269093 Jaiswal et al. 2012)]. CF regulates group size by negative regulation of cell adhesion ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11090633 Roisin-Bouffay et al. 2001])
column6: cell motility ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11818526 Tang et al. 2002])
column7: down-regulating the cAMP-induced cGMP pulse through inhibition of guanylyl cyclase activity
column8: and decreasing the cAMP-stimulated cAMP pulse ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11371560 Tang et al. 2001]). In contrast
column9:
recombinant countin potentiates the cAMP pulse ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14557265 Brock et al. 2003]). The presence of countin enhances the cAMP-stimulated transient translocation of [/gene/DDB_G0268620 pkbA] and [/gene/DDB_G0285161 dagA] from the cytosol to membranes ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15470246 Gao et al. 2004]).
CF increases actin filament polymerization and myosin phosphorylation and redistribution ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11818526 Tang et al. 2002]). The specific roles of countin have been investigated by comparing the effect of addition of recombinant countin to cells compared to addition of semi-purified CF. The responses to recombinant countin and CF are similar with respect to cAMP signal transduction
column11: countin does not decrease cell-cell adhesion or group size to the extent that semi-purified CF does ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12070154 Gao et al. 2002]). Cells lacking bioactive CF have high glucose levels
column12: whereas transformants over-secreting CF have low glucose levels. Adding exogenous glucose negates the effect of high levels of extracellular CF on group size and mimics the effect of depleting CF on glucose levels
column17: and motility. These results suggest that glucose is a downstream component in part of the CF signaling pathway ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12161440 Jang et al. 2002]). In support
column18:
it has been shown that CF decreases the activity of the gluconeogenic enzyme glucose-6-phosphatase ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15643062 Jang and Gomer 2005]).
Countin represents a new family within the amoebapore superfamily of proteins based on the presence of three predicted disulfide bridges and a tertiary structure similar to that of other members of the superfamily. Amoebapore superfamily proteins bind membranes and are extremely stable ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10998571 Zhai and Saier 2000]). CF is over-secreted in [/gene/DDB_G0287587 smlA] mutants ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10444594 Brock and Gomer 1999]). Secreted countin appears to be protected from degradation by CF50 [/gene/DDB_G0273175 cf50-1] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12117815 Brock et al.2002]). The eIF2alpha kinase [/gene/DDB_G0272837 ifkA] can stabilize and enhance the translational efficiency of countin mRNA ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12697064 Fang et al.2003]). CF and group size have also been mathematically modeled [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16371424 (Dallon et al. 2006)]
column19: which together with experimental evidence has been reviewed in [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18426773 Jang and Gomer 2008].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0276027	Robert Dodson	''pdeE'' encodes a cAMP-stimulated cAMP phosphodiesterase which participates along with RegA ([/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA]) in breaking down intracellular cAMP. The affinity of PdeE for cAMP is much lower than the affintity of RegA for cAMP [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17040207  (Bader et al. 2007)]. PdeE has a beta-lactamase catalytic site followed by two cNMP binding sites
column2: the same order of domains found in the highly related cGMP-activated cGMP phosphodiesterase PdeD ([/gene/DDB_G0274383 pdeD]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12429832  (Bosgraaf et al. 2002)]
column3: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12574165  (Meima et al. 2003)]. cGMP is also hydrolyzed by PdeE but much more slowly than cAMP. '' pdeE'' is expressed between 6 and 16 hours of development when it could regulate PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column4: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) activity affecting post-aggregation differentiation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. ''pdeE'' knock-out strains have high levels of cAMP and are sporogenous much like ''regA'' nulls. Over-expression of ''pdeE'' leads to very slow aggregation [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12429832  (Bosgraaf et al. 2002)]. In shallow cAMP gradients
column5: the stalk cell differentiation factor
column6: differentiation-inducing factor 1 (DIF-1)
column7: inhibits chemotaxis through a ''pdeE''-dependent pathway [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19684855  (Kuwayama and Kubohara
column9: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28619991  (Kubohara et al. 2017)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0269240	Robert Dodson	''racH'' encodes a guanine nucleotide-binding protein (G protein) of the Rho family of small GTPases. G proteins are key components of signal transduction networks in which they function as molecular signaling switches
column2: binding to GDP in the off state while binding GTP in the on state. Guanine nucleotide-exchange factors (GEFs) promote the exchange of GDP for GTP on Ras GTPases thus activating them
column3: while GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs) inactivate Ras GTPases by binding to them and promoting their intrinsic GTPase activity to hydrolyze bound GTP to GDP. Possible GEFs for RacH include RGBARG ([/gene/DDB_G0269934 rgbA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32531280 Buckley et al. 2020])
column4:
GxcC ([/gene/DDB_G0284845 gxcC]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23363311 Plak et al. 2013]) and gxcDD ([/gene/DDB_G0279733 gxcDD]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17584488 Mondal et al. 2007]).
RacH is a key mediator in signaling pathways that regulate vesicle trafficking ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26940518 Rivero et al. 2016]). ''racH'' mRNA is expressed as two transcripts
column5: both of which are undetectable at the vegetative stage
column6: but expression increases at the onset of development. ''racH'' expression reaches a maxium level during the aggregation stage followed by continued
column7: but decreased expression during later stages of development. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11201251 Okuwa et al. 2001])
column8: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11222756 Rivero et al. 2001]). RacH localizes predominantly to membranes of the endoplasmic reticulum
column9: Golgi apparatus and nuclear envelope. ''racH'' null mutants have defects in pinocytosis
column11: the acidification of early endosomes and the secretion of acid phosphatase from the lysosome. In addition
column12: the distribution of the post-lysosomal marker vacuolin ([/gene/DDB_G0289485 vacA]) is altered in ''racH'' null mutants
column15: cell motility and chemotaxis are normal. In a cell-free system
column17: suggesting that RacH is involved in actin-based trafficking of vesicular compartments ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17004322 Somesh et al. 2006]). ''racH'' also plays a role in host-pathogen interactions. ''racH'' null mutant cells are more susceptible to infection by ''Mycobacterium marinum'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17587329 Hagedorn et al. 2007]) and ''Legionella pneumophila'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21655438 Balest et al. 2011]). RacH is also involved in the release of bacteria from the infected cell. ''racH'' mutant cells are deficient in intercellular spreading of mycobacteria and lack an F-actin based structure termed the ejectosome that is responsible for the nonlytic release of cytosolic mycobacteria ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19325115 Hagedorn et al. 2009]). ''atg1'' ([/gene/DDB_G0292390 atg1]) null mutants are also defective in intercellular transmission of mycobacteria
column18: indicating that a functioning autophagy pathway is required for the ejection of mycobacterium from ''Dictyostelium discoideum'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25646440 Gerstenmaier et al. 2015]). ''Yersinia pestis'' YopE blocks the effects of overexpressing RacH
column19: suggesting that RacH could be a target of YopE ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19602247 Vlahou et al. 2009]). Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column5:
et al. 2013]) and also to the Legionella-containing vacuole [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28183814 (Schmolders et al. 2017)].

column6: contractile vacuole function and response to osmotic stress. Rab2A over-expressing cells and dominant-negative (DN) Rab2A cells display a significant decrease in the rate of phagocytosis
column7: while the rate of phagocytosis is significantly increased in constitutively active (CA) Rab2A cells. Both CA and DN Rab2A mutants also had defects in development
column9: and cell-cell adhesion [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25157910  (Maringer et al. 2014)]. column12: indicating that these cells were not able to expel water and these cells eventually lysed. DN Rab2 mutant cells were swollen and lacked contractile vacuoles [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27240981  (Maringer et al. 2016)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0272324	Robert Dodson	Shwachman-Diamond syndrome (SDS) is characterized by exocrine pancreatic insufficiency
column2: bone marrow failure and skeletal abnormalities
column3: and is caused by mutations in the highly conserved SBDS gene. ''Dictyostelium'' ''sbds'' encodes the ortholog of human SBDS with which it exhibits an overall identity of 38% and similarity of 69%. Attempts to create null mutants of ''sbds'' were unsuccessful
column4: but conditional mutants using temperature-sensitive self-splicing inteins were engineered and introduced into the ''sbds'' gene to assess its function. In ''sbds'' conditional mutants
column5: growth is abolished at the restrictive temperature and development arrests at the loose mound stage. In addition
column6: the mutants have increased levels of free 40S and 60S ribosomal subunits and decreased levels of mature 80S ribosomes
column7: indicating that SbdS has a conserved function in ribosomal subunit joining. These phenotypes can all be complemented by expression of human SBDS. Overexpression of ''eIF6'' ([/gene/DDB_G0276493 eIF6]) also impairs ribosomal subunit joining. eIF6 binds pre-60S subunits in the nucleus and is exported with them into the cytoplasm. The ribosomal subunit joining defect in ''sbds'' mutants
column8: as well as their growth and developmental phenotypes
column9: can also be suppressed by expressing a mutant form of eIF6 with reduced affinity for 60S ribosomal subunits. SBDS and Elongation factor-like GTPase EFL1 ([/gene/DDB_G0279689 eftud1]) interact directly ''in vivo'' and are bound in close physical proximity on the surface of the 60S ribosomal subunit
column10: where they activate nascent 60S ribosomal subunits for translation by catalyzing eviction of the anti-association factor eIF6 from nascent 60S ribosomal subunits. These findings support the hypothesis that SDS is a ribosomopathy caused by impaired release of eIF6 and defective ribosomal subunit joining due to mutations in the ribosome assembly factor SBDS [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21803848  (Wong et al. 2011)]
column11: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26479198  (Weis et al. 2015)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0270658	Robert Dodson	Acyl-CoA Binding protein is a small
column2: highly conserved facilitator of intracellular lipid trafficking that is encoded by ''acbA''. It is also the precursor of an intercellular peptide signal that is referred to as DBI (Diazepam Binding Inhibitor) in humans and SDF-2 (spore differentiation factor) in ''Dictyostelium'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15897458 Anjard and Loomis
column3: 2005)]. SDF-2 binds to the receptor histidine kinase DhkA ([/gene/DDB_G0280961 dhkA]) and converts it to a protein phosphatase. During culmination
column4: GABA secreted by prespore cells triggers release of AcbA from other prespore cells. The protein has to diffuse to prestalk cells near the top of the rising stalk to be processed by the extracellular protease TagC ([/gene/DDB_G0286121 tagC]) and generate the 34 amino acid peptide that is SDF-2 ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9473320 Anjard et al. 1998)]
column5: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15897458 Anjard and Loomis
column6: 2005)]. When SDF-2 binds DhkA on prespore cells
column7: the response regulator region of the cAMP phosphodiesterase RegA ([/gene/DDB_G0284331 regA]) is dephosphorylated leading to reduced enzymatic activity. The resulting accumulation of cAMP stimulates PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column8: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) activity leading to rapid sporulation. The SDF-2 cascade is initiated by a steroid binding to the G protein-coupled-receptor GrlA ([/gene/DDB_G0271684 grlA]) that signals GABA release and AcbA secretion and processing ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19176583 Anjard et al. 2009)]. column1: DDB_G0281385	Robert Dodson	''rasC'' encodes a G protein of the Ras family of small GTPases. G proteins are key components of signal transduction networks in which they function as molecular signaling switches

column3: rasGEF) promote the exchange of GDP for GTP on Ras GTPases thus activating them
column4: while GTPase-activating proteins (GAP
column5: rasGAP) inactivate Ras GTPases by binding to them and promoting their intrinsic GTPase activity to hydrolyze bound GTP to GDP. RasC activation is abolished in a ''gefA'' null mutant ([/gene/DDB_G0284329 gefA])
column6: indicating that ''gefA'' is the GEF which activates RasC ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11500376 Lim et al. 2001])
column7:
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17380187 Kae et al. 2007]).
''rasC'' is expressed throughout the life cycle with peak expression during development at 20 hours
column8: and with expression enriched in prestalk cells ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11500376 Lim et al. 2001]). ''rasC'' null cells are incapable of aggregation
column9: but this defect is rescued by exogenous cAMP pulses. ''rasC'' null cells do not produce cAMP in response to 2'-deoxy-cAMP
column10: indicating that G-protein-coupled cAMP receptor activation of adenylate cyclase is regulated by RasC. ''rasC'' null cells also exhibit decreased chemotaxis to cAMP during development and reduced phosphorylation of protein kinase B (AKT/PKB) ([/gene/DDB_G0268620 pkbA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11500376 Lim et al. 2001])
column11: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16885420 Bolourani et al. 2006]). Prior to development
column12: vegetative ''rasC'' null cells exhibit reduced random motility
column13: are less polarized and have an altered F-actin distribution. They also have an increased number of lateral pseudopods and an increased rate of endocytosis. ''rasC'' null cells chemotax poorly to folate and exhibit reduced F-actin accumulation
column14: reduced ERK2 ([/gene/DDB_G0283903 erkB]) phosphorylation and reduced PKB phosphorylation in response to folate
column15:
indicating that RasC is also involved in transducing chemotactic signals in vegetative cells. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15878331 Lim et al. 2005]).
RasC is a crucial mediator of the chemotactic response to cAMP. Activated RasC binds to the catalytic domain of tor ([/gene/DDB_G0281569 tor]) and stimulates TORC2 to phosphorylate downstream protein kinases
column17: as well as to activate adenylyl cyclase ([/gene/DDB_G0281545 acaA]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27172998  (Khanna et al. 2016)]
column20: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19763972  (Kamimura et al. 2009)]. Rap1 ([/gene/DDB_G0291237 rapA]) positively regulates the RasC-mediated activation of TORC2
column21: suggesting that dual Ras/Rap1 regulation of TORC2 may allow for integration of Ras and Rap1 signaling pathways in directed cell migration. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27172998 Khanna et al. 2016)]. The Sca1 Ras signaling complex
column22: which includes the RasGEFs GefA and GefH ([/gene/DDB_G0276963 gefH])
column23: and the scaffold protein Sca1 ([/gene/DDB_G0277843 scaA])
column24: is recruited to the plasma membrane of the leading edge of chemotaxing cells during cAMP stimulation where it regulates F-actin dynamics and signal relay by controlling the activation of RasC and the downstream TORC2-PKB pathway. PKB and PKBR1 phosphorylate Sca1 and regulate the membrane localization of the Sca1 complex
column25: and thereby RasC activity
column26: in a negative feedback fashion ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20493808 Charest et al. 2010]). In ''pkaC'' ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]) null cells stimulated with cAMP
column27: RasC activation is decreased and Sca1 fails to localize to the plasma membrane
column28: indicating that PKA ([/gene/DDB_G0283907 pkaC]
column29: [/gene/DDB_G0279413 pkaR]) is also needed for optimal RasC activation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28302905 Scavello et al. 2017)]. column3: TorC2
column4: PLA2
column5: and sGC. Their results demonstrate that Ras is activated at the leading edge
column6: through a pathway consisting of G-alpha/beta/gamma
column7: which does not depend on either of the four pathways. The authors measured chemotaxis of mutant cells exposed to cAMP gradients with different steepness and found that many mutants will chemotax in shallow gradients
column8: despite a reduced sensitivity. Expression of multiple pathways increases sensitivity
column9: with some combinations of pathways exhibiting weak amplification while others produce good chemotaxis with strong signal amplification. The results of cluster analysis revealed that one cluster of signaling pathways
column11: is involved in inducing orientation of the cell towards the gradient
column12: while a second cluster consists of cGMP + PLA2 and functions as a memory of current direction. Thus one individual pathway does not contribute strongly to chemotaxis
column13: but it can synergize with other pathways
column14: which together increases the sensitivity about 150-fold. These results suggest a conceptual model of chemotaxis in which a basal signaling module consisting of heterotrimeric and monomeric G proteins provides activation of Ras at the leading edge

DDB_G0281663	Robert Dodson	The gene product encoded by [/gene/DDB_G0281663 aprA] is a secreted protein that exists in a 150 kDa protein complex. The AprA protein contains the PhoPQ-activated pathogenicity-related protein domain
column2: which is thought to play a role in virulence of Salmonella. From its mutant phenotype
column3: AprA functions in negative regulation of cell proliferation and is also clearly important for sporulation. Although it plays a role in cell proliferation
column4: AprA does not have an effect on cell growth
column5: as evidenced by an unchanged mass per number of cells in comparison to wild-type. Four proteins in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome are highly similar to AprA: [/gene/DDB_G0286625 DDB_G0286625]
column8:
[/gene/DDB_G0282135 DDB_G0282135] ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16176950 Brock and Gomer 2005]).
It has been demonstrated that Galpha8 (gene [/gene/DDB_G0284469 gpaH]) and Gbeta (gene [/gene/DDB_G0277143 gpbA]) are part of a signaling pathway used by AprA to inhibit cell proliferation but not growth
column9: while Galpha9 (gene [/gene/DDB_G0283419 gpaI]) is part of a different pathway that regulates both proliferation and growth. Similar to aprA- and [/gene/DDB_G0281605 cfaD] null mutants
column10:
cells lacking these G-proteins proliferate faster than wild type ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19635129 Bakthavatsalam et al. 2009]).
In 2012 AprA has been found to also function as a chemorepellant. Wild-type cells at the edge of a colony showed directed movement outward from the colony
column11: whereas cells lacking AprA did not. Starved cells are not repelled by recombinant AprA
column12: suggesting that aggregation-phase cells are not sensitive to the chemorepellant effect. The secreted protein CfaD
column14: and the kinase QkgA are necessary for the chemorepellant activity of AprA as well as its proliferation-inhibiting activity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22711818 Philips et al. 2012]). The Retinoblastoma protein (gene [/gene/DDB_G0290551 rblA]) has been implicated in AprA function as recombinant AprA inhibits the proliferation of wild type cells
column15: but not that of rblA- cells
column16:
and RblA is required for chemorepulsion ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24390142 Bakthavatsalam et al. 2014]).
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29440579 Tang et al. 2018]) identified four mutants that show insensitivity to AprA: ([/gene/DDB_G0271686 grlB])
column20: cells lacking GrlH show most of the phenotypes expected for cells lacking the AprA receptor
column22:
suggesting that GrlH is an AprA receptor.
The P21 activated protein kinase D (gene [/gene/DDB_G0269696 pakD]) was identified to being required for AprA dependent chemorepulsion ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24797076 Philips et al. 2014]). Both cAMP chemotaxis and AprA chemorepulsion use G protein-coupled receptors
column24: and Ras
column25: and both involve receptor-mediated activation of Ras. AprA uses a subset of chemoattraction signal transduction pathways including Ras

column30: but does not require the PI3 kinase/Akt/PKB and guanylyl cyclase pathways to induce chemorepulsion. Genes involved in ArpA-mediated chemorepulsion include ([/gene/DDB_G0282459 grlH])
column46: ([/gene/DDB_G0269696 pakD]) and ([/gene/DDB_G0287969 cnrN]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30462573 Rijal et al. 2018]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0279483	Robert Dodson	Phospholipase D hydrolyzes the membrane phospholipid phosphatidylcholine
column2: producing choline and a phosphatidate. Three orthologs of mammalian phospholipase D1 (PLD1) are present in ''Dictyostelium'': ([/gene/DDB_G0281031 pldA])
column3:
''pldB'' and ([/gene/DDB_G0277949 pldC]).
The ''pldB'' transcript first appears at the onset of development
column4: peaking around 20 hr. Deletion of the ''pldB'' gene results in cells that are unable to sense cell density and aggregate at low cell concentrations. Conversely
column5: cells over-expressing ''pldB'' do not aggregate
column6: even at high cell densities. Additionally
column7: ''pldB'' null cells develop precociously in submerged culture and on filter pads ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15821129 Chen et al. 2005]). PldB regulates chemotaxis and cell sorting
column8: and was also found to mediate CMF-dependent quorum sensing by regulating G protein signaling ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20950684 Ray et al. 2011]). PldB and ([/gene/DDB_G0274109 paxB]) functionally interact to regulate the organization of the actin cytoskeleton ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21531871 Pribic et al. 2011]). The protein kinase ''pkcA'' ([/gene/DDB_G0288147 pkcA]) positively regulates phospholipase D activity
column9: and PkcA and PldB functionally interact to regulate aggregation
column11: and cell-cell adhesion during development. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28257811 Singh et al. 2017)]Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0292804	Robert Dodson	''arcC'' encodes the 21 kDa subunit of the Arp2/3 complex [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11807934  (Insall et al. 2001)]. The seven subunits of this 200 kDa complex are encoded by ([/gene/DDB_G0277825 arcA])
column3: ''arcC''
column4: ([/gene/DDB_G0269102 arcD])
column5: ([/gene/DDB_G0288319 arcE])
column6: ([/gene/DDB_G0272106 arpB]) and ([/gene/DDB_G0283755 arpC]). The subunits of mammalian Arp2/3 are very similar to ''Dictyostelium'' homologs. Arp2/3 binds to the side of F-actin filaments and initiates polymerization of a new F-actin chain at an angle of 70 degrees leading to a branched actin network that can alter the shape of cells. The ability to nucleate new actin filaments is greatly stimulated by direct interactions with members of the WASP/SCAR family [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11807934  (Insall et al. 2001)]. The Arp2/3 complex largely mediates the actin polymerization response to chemotactic stimulation and contributes to cell motility
column7: pseudopod extension and adhesion in Dictyostelium chemotaxis. The complete Arp2/3 complex is essential for growth; partial loss of activity of either ArcB or ArpB impairs growth and chemotaxis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17553489  (Langridge and Kay
column8: 2007)]. mRNA from each of the genes encoding Arp2/3 subunits accumulates coordinately to reach a peak at 3 hours of development and gradually decreases thereafter [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. The Arp2/3 complex interacts with the protein CARMIL
column9: which serves as a scaffold for the assembly of a larger complex of proteins involved in the nucleation and termination of actin filament assembly. The complex consists of CARMIL ([/gene/DDB_G0292386 carmil])
column13: and type I myosins MyoB ([/gene/DDB_G0289117 myoB]) and MyoC ([/gene/DDB_G0276617 myoC]) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11425877  (Jung et al. 2001)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0267446	Robert Dodson	The regulatory subunit of calcineurin is encoded by ''cnbA''. The primary sequence of this calcium/calmodulin dependent protein phosphatase is very similar to the sequences of calcineurin B in mammals that all have two calcium binding EF hands [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11352578  (Aichem and Mutzell
column2: et al. 2001)]. In the absence of calcium
column3: calcineurin A ([/gene/DDB_G0276883 canA]) and calcneurin B form inactive heterodimers that are converted to active heterotetramers when they bind Ca++/calmodulin [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25518940  (Sugden et al. 2014)]. RNA-seq studies have shown that canA and cnbA are coordinately expressed during early aggregation and reach a peak at 11 hrs of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Inhibition of calcineurin activity with the polyphenolic aldehyde
column4: gossypol
column5: reduces the rate of growth and the number of aggregates formed after 24 hrs of development [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15621416  (Weissenmayer et al. 2005)]. cAMP relay is inhibited within 10 minutes of addition of 10 microM gossypol. Gossypol also stimulates nuclear translocation of the prestalk transcription factor DimB ([/gene/DDB_G0291372 dimB]) within a few minutes and blocks nuclear translocation of the transcription factor TacA ([/gene/DDB_G0291342 tacA]) in response to calcium indicating that calcineurin mediates these responses [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22944283  (Thewes et al. 2012)]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25518940  (Sugden et al. 2014)]. Cells lacking calcineurin as the result of expression of RNAi for either canA or cnbA form a reduced number of fruiting bodies with short stalks [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16512895  (Boeckeler et al. 2006)]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23686520  (Thewes et al. 2013)] These mutant strains are also hypersensitive to high levels of cations showing that calcineurin is responsible for stress responses as in other organisms.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column3: with highest levels of expression between 8 and 12 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16086850 Wilkins et al. 2005)]. The phenotype of mutants that have lost GbpD is almost opposite that of mutants that have lost GbpC; ''gbpD'' null mutants are hyperpolarized
column4: make few lateral pseudopods and have improved chemotaxis. Overexpression of ''gbpD'' results in cells that are unable to polarize
column5: extend many lateral pseudopodia and are greatly impaired in chemotaxis to cAMP
column6: much like gbpC null mutants
column7: suggesting that overexpressed GbpD might block the function of GbpC [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15827084  (Bosgraaf et al. 2005)]. Consistent with this interaction
column8: the phenotype of double mutants lacking both GbpC and GbpD is indistinguishable from that of cells lacking only GbpC [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12952076  (Bosgraaf et al. 2002)]. Moreover
column9: GbpD is an exchange factor for the small GTPase Rap1 ([/gene/DDB_G0291237 rapA]) which binds to the Ras-binding domain of PI3K ([/gene/DDB_G0278727 pikA]
column11: and [/gene/DDB_G0275011 pikC]) and stimulates its activity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16769729  (Kortholt et al. 2006)]
column12: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20089846  (Kortholt et al. 2010)]. Rap1-GTP is found preferentially at the leading edge of cells migrating chemotactically. Cells overexpressing GbpD have high levels of PIP3 in the membrane resulting in the formation of multiple lateral pseudopods and increased cell-substratum adhesion. However
column13: overexpression of GbpD in pikA/pikB null cells does not induce the cell-substratum adhesion or multiple lateral pseudopods phenotypes
column14: indicating that a GbpD/RapA/PI3K pathway helps control pseudopod formation and cell polarity. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20089846  (Kortholt et al. 2010)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0284725	Robert Dodson	''docD'' encodes a putative Rho guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF

column3: cited in Para
column4: 2009). In response to cAMP
column5: DocD rapidly translocates to the cell cortex
column6: and in chemotaxing cells
column7: DockD preferentially localizes to the leading edge. Translocation is impaired in (PI3K) ([/gene/DDB_G0278727 pikA]

column12: either before or after chemoattractant stimulation. In addition
column13:
the DocD-ElmoA complex associates with the Rho small GTPases: Rac1A ([/gene/DDB_G0277869 rac1A]) and RacC ([/gene/DDB_G0293526 racC]) suggesting that DocD is a GEF for Rac1A and RacC.

column14: developmentally competent ''docD'' null mutants chemotax with moderately reduced speed and polarity in a cAMP gradient. The chemotaxis defect is more pronounced in ''docA''/''docD'' ([/gene/DDB_G0291974 docA]) double null mutant cells which have a further reduction in speed and polarity. column1: DDB_G0291079	Robert Dodson	''gbpC'' (''gefT'') encodes a large multi-domain
column2: high affinity cGMP-binding protein. There is a leucine rich repeat (LRR) at the N-terminus followed by a Ras-related domain and a mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase kinase (MAPKKK) domain; these domains are followed by a RasGEF domain
column3: and two cyclic nucleotide binding domains with a GRAM domain in between [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12011437  (Goldberg et al. 2002)]
column4: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12952076  (Bosgraaf et al. 2002)]. ''gbpC'' is expressed throughout growth and development
column5: with highest levels of expression between 4 and 12 hours of development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16086850 Wilkins et al. 2005)]. GbpC is a founding member of the Roco family of proteins (Ras of complex proteins) which includes human leucine rich repeat kinase 2 (LRRK2) that can cause late-onset Parkinson's disease [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14654223  (Bosgraaf and van Haastert 2003)]
column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24981771  (Civiero et al. 2014)]
column7: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24847205  (Gilsbach and Kortholt 2014)]. ''gbpC'' may have resulted from the fusion of two independent genes
column8: one encoding Ras-MAPKKK and one related to GbpD ([/gene/DDB_G0282373 gbpD]) containing a RasGEF domain and an ancient cAMP-binding (cNB) motif. [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12615006  (Roelof et al. 2003)]. Mutants lacking GbpC have lost all high affinity cGMP binding activity
column10: and are greatly impaired in chemotaxis to cAMP gradients [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15827084  (Bosgraaf et al. 2005)]. In wild type cells
column11: cAMP induces rapid phosphorylation of myosin regulatory light chain (RLC) ([/gene/DDB_G0276077 mlcR]) by a cGMP-dependent pathway
column13: cAMP induces significantly less phosphorylation of RLC in ''gbpC'' null cells
column14: confirming the role of cGMP in myosin II regulation. When cGMP binds to GbpC
column15: it initiates an intramolecular signaling cascade in which the RasGEF activates Ras which stimulates the protein kinase activity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18703517  (van Egmond et al. 2008)]. The MAPKKK may then initiate a protein kinase cascade activating the myosin light chain protein kinase MLCK-A ([/gene/DDB_G0279925 mlkA]) that phosphorylates RLC to promote myosin motor activity [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16814425  (Bosgraaf and van Haastert 2006)]. cGMP bound GbpC also leads to actin polymerization [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24136144  (Pfannes et al. 2013)]. Independently of cGMP signaling
column16: cAMP stimulation results in rapid translocation of GbpC from the cytoplasm to the cell perimeter where it may locally phosphorylate effector proteins. The GRAM domain of GbpC is required for membrane association and its function in chemotaxis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22119747  (Kortholt et al. 2011)]. When developed on filters
column17: ''gbpC''- mutant cells can aggregate slowly by accretion resulting in the delayed formation of mounds which then develop normally.Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column9: and the cell leading edge. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22891261 Veltman et al. 2012]). Hspc300 interacts directly with Scar ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17314411 Caracino et al. 2007])

column11: including decreased cell motility speed and smaller

column12: and recruitment of the bacterium to Mycobacteria-containing vacuole (MCV). However
column14:
Mycobacterium also uses its ESX-1 secretion system to repress autophagic flux and support its survival inside the MCV. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28414774 Cardenal-Munoz et al. 2017]).

column18: and an increase in ubiquitinylated proteins and a concomitant decrease in proteasomal activity. However knockout mutants of both genes displayed more severe phenotypes than the single ''atg8a'' mutant
column19:
indicating that both proteins function in parallel. Immunofluorescence analysis of knock-out strains suggests a crucial function for ATG8b in autophagosome-lysosome fusion. Atg8b localized around ATG8a and was presumably mainly present on the outer membrane of the autophagosome while Atg8a appears to be mainly associated with the inner membrane. These results suggest that Atg8b predominantly acts as adapter for the autophagy machinery at the outer and Atg8a as cargo receptor at the inner membrane of the autophagosome. column11: 1995)]. CAR1 and CAR3 have 56% amino acid identity and show approximately equal affinity to cAMP in vitro [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1537842  (Johnson et al.
column12: 1992)]. Both are coupled to trimeric G proteins with the Galpha2 subunit (gene ''[/gene/DDB_G0276267 gpaB]''). CAR1 is expressed immediately after the initiation of development. column13:
2001)]. column14: 1990)]. Stimulation of cAMP and cGMP accumulation in response to addition of cAMP is lost in these cells. However

column16: 1998)]. A double ''carA/carC'' mutant lacking both receptors shows no response to cAMP and an abolished synthesis of cGMP [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7949426  (Insall et al.
column18: Brzostowski and colleagues demonstrated that receptor phosphorylation is required to regulate adenylyl cyclase adaptation

column20: coupling to G proteins and regulated phosphorylation were delineated by PCR-mediated random mutagenesis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8999903  (Kim et al.
column22:
1997)].
Binding of cAMP to CAR1 results in the transient activation of TorC2 and the adenylyl cyclase ACA through a Ras pathway [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20660630 (Cai et al.
column24: 2013)]. An incoherent feedforward loop in which ligand bound CAR1 activates both a Ras-GEF and a Ras-GAP can result in perfect adaptation of activated Ras about 20 seconds after addition of cAMP in a spatially uniform manner [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22215733  (Takeda et al.
column25: 2012)]. The LEGI model points out that membrane localization of the activator (GEF) and free diffusion of the inhibitor (GAP) can generate a spatial gradient of activated Ras within the cells in response to an external gradient of cAMP [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10221901  (Parent and Devreotes
column26: 1999)]. Ultrasensitivity resulting from the opposing activities of GEF and GAP can dramatically amplify the signal and ensure that cells only respond to constant or rising concentrations of cAMP and that they do not respond to the decreasing concentrations of cAMP in the back of a wave [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25249632  (Skoge et al.
column27: 2014)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated 08-DEC-2015 PF; summary contribution: Bill Loomis

column1: DDB_G0274125	Robert Dodson	The gamma subunit of heterotrimeric G proteins is a small evolutionarily conserved protein that carries a lipid tail for membrane association. In ''Dictyostelium'' ''gpgA'' encodes a G gamma protein of 69 amino acids that requires the phosducin-like protein PhLP1 ([/gene/DDB_G0292850 phlp1]) for addition of a lipid tail to the carboxy terminal amino acid motif CSVL [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11598203  (Zhang et al. 2001)]
column2: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16135826  (Knol et al. 2005)]. G gamma forms a stable dimer with G-beta ([/gene/DDB_G0277143 gpbA]) and is involved in multiple signal transduction pathways. Both subunits are required for these functions. G-beta/G-gamma reassociates with G-alpha subunits to form a heterotrimeric G protein that can associate with surface receptors of the GPCR family. The subunits remain as receptor bound heterotrimers until GDP is displaced by GTP on G-alpha subunits. Amplification of the external chemoattractant signal appears to occur downstream of the G protein response since G-beta/G-gamma is distributed on the surface membrane in direct proportion to the concentration of external cAMP in a gradient [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10669414  (Jin et al. 2000)]. G-beta/G-gamma associates with an ELMO/DOCK complex that may act as a Rho guanine nucleotide exchange factor (RhoGEF) [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22754623  (Yan and Tin
column3: 2012)]. RacB ([/gene/DDB_G0279605 racB]) and the Arp2/3 complex are also found together with G-beta/G-Gamma and this complex may mediate signaling from GPCR to the actin cytoskeleton during chemotaxis [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22647486  (Xu and Jin
column4: 2012)]. The rate of dissociation of G-beta/G-gamma from the membrane increases when cAMP is bound to CAR1 ([/gene/DDB_G0273397 carA-1]
column5: [/gene/DDB_G0273533 carA-2]) which may facilitate activation of cytosolic components such as RasGAPs [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19584094  (Elzie et al. 2009)].Gene has been comprehensively annotated

''tgrB1'' encodes a cell surface glycoprotein that acts in conjunction with TgrC1 ([/gene/DDB_G0280531 tgrC1]) to mediate post-aggregation EDTA-resistant cell-cell adhesion and kin recognition [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21700835 (Hirose et al. 2011]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23477311 Chen et al. 2013]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24490801 Chen et al. 2014)]. Independent isolates from nature show a high degree of polymorphism of TrgB1 and TgrC1. Cells with compatible TgrB1 / TgrC1 pairs form common aggregates but distant kin that express variants are excluded. This mechanism of kin recognition protects from potential cheaters that fail to make their fair share of stalk cells [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23910661 (Ho et al. 2013]; [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26018043 Ho and Shaulsky 2015)]. column6: [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25887420  (Rosengarten et al. 2015)]. Poly ADP-ribose is generated by the polymerase Adprt1a ([/gene/DDB_G0278741 adprt1A]) at sites of DNA DSBs. column4: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22366457 Pakes et al. 2012]) and gxcDD ([/gene/DDB_G0279733 gxcDD]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17584488 Mondal et al. 2007]). column7:
([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26940518 Rivero et al. 2016]).

column3: while constitutively active RasC(G12V) significantly enhanced the membrane translocation of NgaP
column4: indicating that NgaP membrane localization is dependent on activated Ras. ''ngap'' null mutant cells have multiple phenotypes

column7: and a higher level of activated Ras. In response to persistent cAMP stimulation
column8: ''ngap'' null mutants display the same initial
column9: transient Ras activation as wild type (wt) cells
column10: but fail to adapt persistently to the stimulation. In addition
column11: ''ngap'' null cells have a chemotaxis defect
column13: decreased speed and a shorter travel path compared with wt cells at higher (10 microM) levels of cAMP
column14: but normal chemotaxis at lower (100 nanoMolar) levels of cAMP. column19: while ''cbpG'' ([/gene/DDB_G0283609 cbpG]) null cells with higher basal [Ca2+ ] levels upon cAMP stimulation exhibited little membrane translocation of NgaP
column20: indicating that calcium negatively mediates the membrane targeting of NgaP. and it functions as a GAP for RacE ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27009206 Senoo et al. 2016]). DGAP1 ''rgaA'' ([/gene/DDB_G0287585 rgaA]) is also a possible GAP for RacE ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9739079 Faix et al. 1998]).

GTP-bound ''rasC'' ([/gene/DDB_G0281385 rasC]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31263268 Senoo et al. 2019]). column17: and 14-3-3 ([/gene/DDB_G0269138 fttB]) all fail to localize to the cell cortex ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10953006 Robinson et al. 2000])

column25: and pseudopods are abnormally extended from the lateral sides of migrating cells resulting in impaired chemotaxis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24248334 Wang et al. 2013]). GflB is required for both chemotaxis to cAMP and cytokinesis
column26: and GflB activates RasG ([/gene/DDB_G0293434 rasG]) and also inactivates RacE. As RacE and RasG ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10725225 Khosla et al. 2000]) also function in cytokinesis

GflB may coordinate signal transduction of RacE and RasG for both chemotaxis and cytokinesis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27009206 Senoo et al. 2016]).
RacE occupies a unique position as a signaling molecule in cell migration by connecting GPCR activation to mTORC2-AKT signaling. column2: binding to GDP in the off state while binding GTP in the on state. Guanine nucleotide-exchange factors (GEFs
column3: rasGEFs) promote the exchange of GDP for GTP on Ras GTPases thus activating them
column4: while GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs
column5: rasGAPs) inactivate Ras GTPases. The similarity in phenotypes of ''rasS'' and RasGEF B ([/gene/DDB_G0269222 gefB]) null mutants suggests that RasS is activated by RasGEF B ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11102804 Wilkins et al. 2000)]
column6: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12854977 King and Insall et al. 2003)]. RasS interacts with the protein kinase Phg2 ([/gene/DDB_G0283699 phg2]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15194808 Gebbie et al. 2004)] and the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinases pikA
column8:

column10: and a higher rate of cell motility during growth ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10652263 Chubb et al. 2000)]. However
column11: ''rasS'' null cells from an AX2 background have opposite phenotypes-decreased cell motility and cell polarity ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16822579 Pollitt et al. 2006)]

column1: DDB_G0269138	Robert Dodson	14-3-3 proteins are a group of well-conserved adaptor proteins that form dimers and bind to phosphorylated serine/threonine residues on target proteins. 14-3-3 proteins are involved in the regulation of signaling pathways. ''fttB'' is the sole 14-3-3 related gene in the ''Dictyostelium'' genome. Highest levels of ''fttB'' expression are observed in vegetative cells with decreased expression during development; however FttB protein levels remain constant during development ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9223628 Knetsch et al. 1997]). FttB is found in the cytosol ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32818671 Li et al. 2020])
column2: is enriched at the cell cortex ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20951045 Zhou et al. 2010])
column3: and is localized to the centrosome during cytokinesis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25298405 Plak et al. 2014]). FttB interacts with numerous proteins
column4:
including the ankyrin repeat-containing protein kinase A ([/gene/DDB_G0289555 arkA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14597204 Aubry et al. 2003]) the TOR complex 2 protein PiaA ([/gene/DDB_G0277399 piaA]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16079174 Lee et al. 2005]) and the SH2 domain protein LrrB ([/gene/DDB_G0287823 lrrB]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20457612 Sugden et al. 2010]).
In ''Dictyostelium'' FttB coordinates three major cytoskeletal elements: microtubules
column5: actin
column6: and myosin II-to control two critical processes
column7: cytokinesis and cortical mechanics ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20951045 Zhou et al. 2010]). In addition
column8: FttB plays a role in cAMP signaling during development and contributes to the regulation of chemotaxis to cAMP and tip formation ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32818671 Li et al. 2020]). Down-regulated FttB cells have a slower growth rate and are multi-nucleated and have an altered cleavage furrow morphology
column9: indicating a cytokinesis defect. The cells also have a defect in cytoskeleton organization with shorter microtubules and decreased cortical tension ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20951045 Zhou et al. 2010]). Down-regulated FttB cells also have defects in chemotaxis to cAMP and form mounds with multiple tips ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32818671 Li et al. 2020]). FttB fails to localize to the cell cortex in ''racE'' null cells ([/gene/DDB_G0280975 racE]) and over-expression of FttB partially rescues the mechanical defect in ''racE'' null cells
column10: suggesting that FttB functions downstream of RacE to regulate the cell cortex and cytokinesis. FttB also interacts with the myosin II heavy chain ([/gene/DDB_G0286355 mhcA]) to regulate its distribution and assembly ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20951045 Zhou et al. 2010]). Large scale immunoprecipitation identified 100 proteins that potentially interact with FttB
column11: including the protein kinases PakA ([/gene/DDB_G0269166 pakA]) and Fray1 ([/gene/DDB_G0278863 fray1])
column12: and the Ras guanine nucleotide exchange factors (RasGEFs) GefM ([/gene/DDB_G0274607 gefM]) and GefQ ([/gene/DDB_G0289665 gefQ]). FttB binding to GefQ regulates tip formation through the Ras GTPase RasB ([/gene/DDB_G0292998 rasB]) ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32818671 Li et al. 2020]).Gene has been comprehensively annotated

column1: DDB_G0286557	Robert Dodson	The concentration of membrane phospholipid
column4: 5)-trisphosphate (PIP3)
column5: is higher at the front of cells in a chemotactic gradient than at the back ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12802064 Huang et al. 2003)]. Not only is PIP3 synthesized more rapidly at the front
column6: it is also converted to PIP2 less rapidly at the front of cells than at the back. The conversion of PIP3 to PIP2 is catalyzed by the PIP3 3' phosphatase encoded by ''pten'' ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12062103 Ijima and Devreotes 2002)]
column7: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12062104 Funamoto et al. 2002)]. Exposing cells to a gradient of cAMP results in rapid release of PTEN from the membrane followed by return of PTEN to the membrane at the rear and the sides. Cells lacking PTEN migrate poorly because they extend multiple spiky pseudopods in all directions and fail to suppress lateral pseudopods ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12062103 Ijima and Devreotes 2002)]
column8: ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17623773 Wessels et al. 2007)]. column15: with mutual inhibition between PIP3 and PTEN leading to a a clear spatial separation between PIP3 and Pten on the membrane ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30367048 Matsuoka et al. 2018]). Pten is involved in the signal transduction pathway responsible for AprA-dependent ([/gene/DDB_G0281663 aprA]) chemorepulsion. column2: developmental arrest at the mound stage. SCAR orthologs exist in mammals

column11:
and [/gene/DDB_G0274519 napA] and involved in positive regulation of actin filament polymerization. The first 96 amino acids of ScrA are necessary for interaction with [/gene/DDB_G0267956 abiA] and [/gene/DDB_G0279175 hspc300]. This interaction is essential for SCAR complex function as the deletion of the amino terminus in ''scrA'' causes defects in chemotaxis to cAMP and cytokinesis ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17314411 Caracino et al. 2007]).
''scrA'' null mutants grow at normal rates but are smaller in size than normal wild type. The cytoskeleton is aberrant in ''scrA''- cells: there is decreased levels of filamentous actin
column12: suggesting a role for SCAR in positive regulation of actin filament polymerization. Moreover
column13:
these cells are less polarized during aggregation and have an increased tendency to for lateral pseudopods. ''scrA'' null develops approximately 3 hours faster than wild type cells and form multiple tips. Each tip forms an individual slug and a relatively normal fruiting body ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9732292 Bear et al. 1998]).
[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11683394 Seastone et al. 2001] demonstrated that rates of fluid phase macropinocytosis and phagocytosis are significantly reduced in ''scrA'' null cells. In addition
column14: fluid phase exocytosis is delayed and movement of the fluid phase from lysosomes to post-lysosomes is also delayed. Furthermore
column15: deletion of ''scrA'' in the profilin null background resulted in a further decrease in endocytosis and fluid phase release compared to either mutant alone

suggesting that profilin and SCAR both functionally contribute to regulate fluid phase endocytosis and endosomal membrane trafficking.
SCAR/WAVE is activated during mitosis and localizes to the cell poles
column17: driving the separation of daughter cells. SCAR activity was shown to be essential for myosin-independent cytokinesis

stabilizing the cleavage furrow and thus ensuring symmetrical cell division. ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20530573 King et al. 2010]).
Results from unphosphorylatable and phosphomimetic ''scrA'' mutants revealed that dephosphorylation of SCAR controls normal pseudopod dynamics ([http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22386315 Ura et al. 2012]).
In wild type cells
